<FIRST>u a AM-SkySniper 1stLd-Writethru a0720 05-16 0516</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sky Sniper, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0720,0528</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Told Judge of Threats Before Aerial Sniping</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf, `Albert J. ..., to CORRECT name to Alfred, sted
Albert; note that quote in 10th graf, ``All of ...,'' is cq.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALEM, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman told a judge her ex-husband
threatened to kill her hours before her slaying and his arrest for
commandeering an airplane and firing an assault rifle into Boston
from the air, a newspaper said Tuesday.
   Alfred J. Hunter, 42, is accused of shooting his ex-wife,
Elvira, eight times with the assault rifle in front of their
5-year-old son on May 10.
   He then took the plane at gunpoint, and performed aerobatics
over the area while firing randomly into Boston, authorities say.
   Earlier that day, the divorced couple appeared before Salem
Superior Court Judge David T. Doyle for Hunter's trial on charges
of assault and battery, violating a restraining order and making
criminal threats against Mrs. Hunter.
   ``Well, he, he told me that if I don't drop the charges, he'll
kill me,'' Mrs. Hunter, a native of the Philippines, told Doyle in
halting English, according to an audio tape of the trial obtained
by The Beverly Times.
   Hunter denied in court that he had made the threat.
   According to the tape, the couple had been living together for
10 months even though Mrs. Hunter had obtained a court order to
keep her husband away a year earlier.
   The couple gave differing accounts of a Dec. 31 fight that sent
Mrs. Hunter to the hospital with a fractured rib and resulted in
Hunter's trial.
   Mrs. Hunter said she was lying in the living room watching
television when her husband came in and became angry with her
because she didn't leave.
   ``All of a sudden he just punch me and put his knees in my ribs,
pushing me down on the couch,'' she said. ``I couldn't breathe
because he put his knees on me,'' according to the tape.
   Hunter said he was watching a program with his son when his
ex-wife came in to change the channel. He said he reached for the
remote control and his wife, an experienced martial arts student,
tried to kick him. Hunter said he punched her in self-defense.
   Hunter insisted that the bruises shown in a photograph taken of
his wife after the incident were inflicted with an open hand.
   ``If I hit her with my fist it would be worse than that, believe
me,'' he told Doyle.
   Doyle found Hunter guilty on all counts and sentenced him to a
year's probation. The Times quoted courtroom observers as saying
that Hunter called the court a ``kangaroo court,'' and that he
would not submit to probation.
   The probation officer on duty protested, but Hunter was allowed
to leave the courtroom, the newspaper said.
   The next day, Hunter was brought before Doyle to be arraigned
for murder.
   Hunter pleaded innocent to charges of murder and armed robbery,
and was sent to Bridgewater State Hospital for 20 days of
psychiatric evaluation. If convicted, he could be sentenced to life
in prison.
</TEXT>
