<DOCNO> AP890516-0008 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-89 0030EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Europe     05-16 0693</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Europe,0713</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anti-Thatcher Blast Lights Fire Under `Euro-Boredom'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   European unity, a subject that traditionally
leaves the British cold, is suddenly a hot issue.
   The reason is a sustained attack by Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher on the unity concept, and a ferocious counterblast from
her predecessor, Edward Heath.
   The long-term source of the discord is 1992, when the 12 nations
of the European Economic Community are to drop their tariff
barriers and become a single trading bloc with complete freedom of
movement for people and goods.
   But where Britain tends to see 1992 as an economic advance and
little more, most continental Europeans see it as a major step
toward political unity.
   Of more immediate import is next month's European Parliament
election. Usually the British voter turnout, at under 32 percent,
is by far the lowest in the EEC. But the Heath-Thatcher conflict
has injected excitement into this year's election, because it
signals a split in the Tory party as it vies for Britain's 81 seats
in the 518-seat Parliament.
   The Times of London called it an ``astonishing public outbreak
of internal discord.''
   For months, Mrs. Thatcher has been attacking the EEC's vision of
unity, saying it means a ``superstate'' of faceless bureaucrats in
Brussels, throwing all sorts of socialist-tinged obstacles in the
path of her free-market revolution.
   This in turn leads many continentals to call the British
``reluctant Europeans'' _ an island race more loyal to the United
States than Europe, a nation of shopkeepers who are only in the EEC
for the money.
   Mrs. Thatcher first raised the ``superstate'' specter at a
speech in September, and she returned to the theme Friday in a
speech to her Conservative Party, saying she wanted ``our kind of
Europe; not a socialist superstate in Brussels which submerges our
identity and snuffs out our sovereignty, but a free Europe.''
   This was too much for Heath, who took Britain into the EEC in
1973 and has since been its ardent defender.
   In a BBC-TV interview Sunday, Heath called Mrs. Thatcher's views
``absolute nonsense,'' misleading and aimed at turning the public
against the EEC.
   He derided Mrs. Thatcher's claim that the EEC was top-heavy with
bureaucrats, saying it had 9,200 employees administering 320
million people, compared with 11,800 civil servants in Scotland
governing 5.5 million people.
   He said there was no reason to fear a socialist EEC when so many
EEC governments were non-socialist, and reminded Mrs. Thatcher that
she had signed the Single European Act, which makes 1992 possible
and broadly lays out the European future she is now so determined
to resist.
   Mrs. Thatcher worries the EEC wants to go beyond pure trading
issues and set social standards, like a pan-European minimum wage,
worker participation in industrial management and harmonized
welfare systems.
   She calls this ``socialism through the back door'' at a time
when she is cutting back trade union power and trying to trim
welfare spending.
   She also is hostile to EEC proposals for monetary union and a
European central bank, fearing it will undermine her freedom to
make economic policy.
   Some critics say Heath's attacks on Mrs. Thatcher stem from his
resentment toward her for unseating him as Conservative Party
leader in 1975.
   Tory lawmaker John Carlisle said Heath, 72, ``should be put out
to grass and not bother the nation any more.''
   But other Tories worry that Mrs. Thatcher's combative stance
will alienate the EEC. Former Defense Secretary Michael Heseltine
fears if Britain stands aloof, France and West Germany will
dominate the bloc. ``Every hostile speech breeds at best despair,
at worst contempt,'' he wrote in a book published Tuesday.
   On Monday, Mrs. Thatcher made no direct comment on Heath, but
managed a subtle dig at the continentals by reminding them that
they owed their liberation from Nazi tyranny to Britain and the
United States.
   Europe, she said, ``would not have been liberated unless we
stood and unless America joined us.'' Britain had fought to free
Europe of Nazism, she said, and now it was fighting to keep it free
of ``a bureaucracy of standardization and harmonization.''
</TEXT>
