<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RADNOR, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A temperamental Roseanne Barr reportedly
threatened to quit her hit series ``Roseanne'' during taping of
early episodes and battled the executive producer, who has since
left.
   ``She would come to me and say, `I can't go on. I can't do it. I
have to quit,''' Drew Ogier, the ABC sitcom's prop master, said in
this week's TV Guide. ``And I'd say, `Just do this show.' We'd all
have to help her out.''
   According to the Radnor-based magazine, executive producer Matt
Williams left the show after Barr said either he or she had to
leave. Ellen Falcon, the show's director, also left the series in
mid-season.
   The magazine quoted unidentified insiders with the show as
saying Barr and Williams disagreed strongly over her character's
development.
   Once, Barr objected to a line her character was supposed to say
to her husband, Dan, played by John Goodman. But Williams resisted
any script change.
   ``She felt he did not take her seriously,'' said Ogier, ``She
left the set. It would happen over and over again. Sometimes she'd
leave the set; sometimes she'd grin and bear it.''
   Spokesmen for Barr, Williams and Falcon all declined requests
for interviews, TV Guide said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Gov. George C. Wallace, bedridden
and unable to hear or see well, promised a return to better health
on the 17th anniversary of the assassination attempt that shattered
his presidential dreams.
   ``I can't be as active as I've been,'' said the 69-year-old
Wallace, who was left paralyzed in the legs after being shot by
Arthur Bremer while campaigning in Laurel, Md., on May 15, 1972.
   In an interview with The Alabama Journal published Monday,
Wallace said complications in his left hip forced him to curtail
his activities. The newspaper gave no details on the ailment.
   ``It's hard to tell what I would have been or done if I had not
been shot,'' said Wallace. ``I would not have had to endure all
this pain, but I don't let that hinder me. I don't think much about
it except having no ill feeling toward Arthur Bremer. I hardly ever
think about him.''
   The Journal said Wallace, dressed in a hospital gown, spoke with
a strong voice during the interview Friday at his Montgomery home.
But the newspaper said it was evident he could not hear questions,
which were asked by a reporter and then written down by one of
Wallace's guards in large letters.
   Wallace said he hopes to resume duties this week for Troy State
University, which he serves out of a Montgomery office. He said he
has been signing letters seeking contributions for the school.
   ``I'll be out of here in a couple of days,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>AUGUSTA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Mother's Day concert by country star
Willie Nelson was a boon for boaters but a bust for the promoter.
   Promoter Jerry McElveen said he lost $15,000 on the show at
Augusta's riverfront, which attracted fewer than 3,000 paid
ticketholders.
   He claimed at least 1,000 people listened to the show for free
from boats anchored in the river and 100 or more others heard it
from a restaurant balcony. He also said a lot of money was tied up
in tickets sold at outlets that were closed Sunday.
   There were some tense moments before Nelson went on stage when
his road manager learned McElveen might not have enough cash to pay
the star, the promoter said. Nelson went on with the show once
arrangements were made to pay his fee, manager Darrell English said
Monday.
   Tony Conway, Nelson's booking agent in Nashville, Tenn., said
Nelson's contract probably cost about $40,000 to $45,000.
   McElveen said he wouldn't attempt to bring another big-name act
to the riverside venue.
   Dayton Sherrouse, executive director of the Augusta Port
Authority, said there was no easy way to prevent people from seeing
concerts from their boats. ``It's a public river and a navigable
waterway,'' he said.
</TEXT>
