<FIRST>u i AM-Mexico-ForeignInvestment 1stLd-Writethru a0778 05-16
0575</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Foreign Investment, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0778,0589</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mexico Announces Liberalization Of Foreign Investment Rules</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with details, background. CORRECTS
percentage in 6th pvs, `The new...' No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN WRIGHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mexico announced a sweeping liberalization of
its rules on foreign investment Monday in hopes of attracting badly
needed capital to its debt-crippled economy.
   The new rules will open areas previously closed to outsiders and
raise the amount of foreign ownership permitted in others. In some
key areas, such as tourism, Mexico will for the first time allow
100 percent foreign ownership.
   Under Mexico's 1973 Foreign Investment Law, foreign ownership
has been limited to 49 percent in most industries.
   The announcement came as negotiations on restructing the $107.4
billion foreign debt were to resume in New York. Mexico's pledge to
modernize its protectionist economy are a crucial feature of the
debt talks.
   ``No country can modernize without attracting fresh
investment,'' Commerce Secretary Jaime Serra Puche told a news
conference. ``The tendency in the world is moving toward
interdependence.''
   The new regulations, which take effect immediately, open up
previously closed areas such as telecommunications, auto parts,
fishing and secondary petrochemicals to 49 percent foreign
ownership.
   In tourism, a critical item on President Carlos Salinas de
Gortari's economic development agenda, the 49 percent limit is
being abolished. Outsiders will now be allowed 100 percent
ownership.
   The new rules will double to 60 years foreign leases on
oceanfront property, Serra Puche said. Foreign ownership of coastal
real estate is prohibited by the Mexican constitution.
   Serra Puche declared it ``historic'' that investors will now be
able to remit 100 percent of profits.
   Many areas deemed strategic such as banking, petroleum, mineral
exploration, electrical generation and broadcasting will remain
off-limits to foreigners, Puche said.
   Mexicans are sensitive to even the suggestion of foreign
ownership in the nation's principal industries, such as petroleum.
Primary petrochemical production will remain off-limits, while
secondary production of by-products such as polyester and nylon
will open to foreign participation.
   Serra Puche said the liberalization is aimed at generating
employment and modernizing the Mexican economy. He also said the
government plans to simplifying paperwork for investors.
   ``The new law eliminates discretionary decisions with clear
regulations as to the criteria for accepting new foreign
investment,'' he said. ``It will bring a high degree of automatic
acceptance in the decisions about foreign investment.''
   The new rules will consolidate regulations pertaining to the
border maquiladora industry, Serra Puche said, but not change them.
   Under the maquiladora program, foreign-made parts are imported
duty-free to Mexico for final assembly. When the finished product
is exported to the United States for sale, the United States taxes
only the labor or the value added in Mexico.
   Serra Puche said the new regulations will steer foreign
investment away from the overcrowded, polluted industrial areas of
Mexico City, Monterrey and Guadalajara.
   The Mexican economy has been battered by the debt and low oil
prices to the point of near zero-growth. Mexican officials say
foreign capital is essential to stimulating growth.
   The Commerce Department said that foreign investment totalled
$3.1 billion last year.
   The new investment regulations follow other economic reforms
such as a wage and price control program that cut inflation from a
record 159 percent in 1987 to 51.7 percent last year, joining the
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, stimulation of
non-petroleum exports and the privatization or closure of some
state-owned business and industries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890516-0014 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-89 0107EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i BC-Sino-SovietSchism     05-16 0797</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Sino-Soviet Schism,0825</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet-Chinese Troubles Began Centuries Ago</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL PUTZEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese and Soviet reformers led the movement in their countries
that brought about the momentous declaration Tuesday that the big
communist powers agreed to normalize relations.
   They had been feuding for 30 years over border and ideological
disputes, but the mistrust was rooted in centuries.
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev and China's senior leader,
Deng Xiaoping, used their Beijing summit to declare a new beginning.
   Strained relations deteriorated further following the Beijing
summit in 1959 when Nikita S. Khrushchev and Mao Tse-tung both took
hard lines.
   Years later Khrushchev wrote in his memoirs: ``You might say
that China is both close to us and far from us. It's close in that
it's our next-door neighbor and shares a long border with our
country. At the same time, China is far away in that the Chinese
have little in common with our people.''
   When the Chinese Communists defeated the Nationalists in 1949
there was apprehension in the West that China, the world's most
populous nation, would unite with the Soviet Union, the strongest
Communist power, and threaten the free world.
   But the romance was brief. In 1972 the United States and China
began normalizing relations, leaving the Soviets in a backwash of
hostility.
   Chinese-Soviet mistrust dates to at least the 13th century when
Mongol forces invaded Russia, destroying towns, slaughtering most
residents and enslaving the suravivors.
   Soviet children still are taught of the brutality and of the
victory of Ivan the Great who ``threw off the Mongol yoke'' and
established the Russian state in 1480.
   More recently suspicion was planted in the infancy of the
international Communist movement.
   In 1927, a decade after the Bolshevik revolution, Chiang
Kai-shek began a purge of Chinese Communists with whom he
ostensibly had been allied.
   Soviet dictator Josef Stalin remained silent, apparently
unwilling to alienate Chiang, and during World War II the Soviets
aided Chiang's Nationalists fighting Japan.
   But when Chiang and his Nationalists fled to Taiwan in 1949, the
Soviet Union was first to recognize China's new Communist
government.
   Mao traveled to Moscow but spent much of the 10 weeks he was
there impatiently waiting to see Stalin. They signed a 30-year
Treaty of Friendship.
   The Soviets wanted access to Chinese resources but Mao resisted,
mindful of the unequal treaties and trade concessions extracted by
the English, Portuguese and others.
   In 1954, Khrushchev invited China to send a million laborers to
Siberia to help exploit the esources, but when Mao accepted the
Soviets became convinced he was trying to take over the Siberian
economy and absorb the vast, sparsely populated territory.
   ``In short, they wanted to make Siberia Chinese rather than
Russian,'' Khrushchev wrote. ``It was a clever maneuver, but it
didn't work.''
   The Kremlin quickly ended the labor program.
   Relations were further exacerbated by Khrushchev's denunciation
of Stalin, who died in 1953, at a Soviet Party Congress in 1956.
   Mao initially joined in criticizing Stalin, but then reversed
his stand and began praising him, according to Khrhshchev.
   ``I think that secretly, he (Mao) disapproved all along of our
censuring Stalin for his crimes,'' Khrushchev wrote. ``Why do I
think so? Because I believe Mao suffered from the same megalomania
Stalin had all his life. He had the same diseased outlook on other
people.''
   Mistrust turned to animosity when the Soviets reneged on an
agreement to provide China with nuclear-weapons technology.
Khrushchev claimed Mao was eager to use the bomb on his enemies.
   Despite the icy relations Khrushchev made a secret trip to
Beijing in hopes of persuading Mao to let the Soviet navy build a
communications base and refueling facilities on Chinese territory.
Mao resisted.
   At the last summit in September 1959 in Beijing, ``the warmth
had gone out of our relations with China and it had been replaced
by a chill that I could sense as soon as I arrived,'' Khrushchev
recalled.
   Soviet advisers and engineers assigned to projects in China
became the target of anti-Soviet feelings and in the summer of 1960
the Kremlin withdrew all technical personnel, leaving hundreds of
projects unfinished.
   Mao's rejection of what he considered Soviet revisionism brought
China's 1966-76 Cultural Revolution intended to purify Chinese
communism. That widened the gulf and Soviet and Chinese troops
fought several border skirmishes in 1969.
   As recently as 1979, the year the United States and China
restored relations, there was talk of war long the frontier.
   Soviet author Victor Louis predicted China's ethnic minorities
would rise up and seek unity with their cousins in pro-Soviet
Mongolia and Soviet Central Asia.
   Louis, widely believed to have ties to the KGB secret police,
said fighting could start at any moment and hundreds of thousands
of Soviet ``volunteers'' would rush to aid the oppressed minorities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890516-0015 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-89 0041EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Navajos-MacDonald     05-16 0214</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Navajos-MacDonald,0223</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Rules Against MacDonald in Landmark Tribal Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINDOW ROCK, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Navajo tribal judge ruled Monday
that the Tribal Council acted within its authority in placing
Chairman Peter MacDonald and Vice Chairman Johnny Thompson on
administrative leave.
   The action was unprecedented in Navajo law: The 200,000-member
tribe, which has operated since the 1920s under a Tribal Code but
without a written constitution, never had tried to oust its chief
executive.
   The long-awaited, 50-page ruling by District Judge Robert Yazzie
enjoins MacDonald and Thompson from ``attempting to assert official
authority which has been declared withdrawn.''
   The council's 49-13 vote against MacDonald on Feb. 17 stemmed
from U.S. Senate subcommittee testimony linking MacDonald to
kickbacks from contractors and personal profit from a $33.4 million
tribal land purchase.
   MacDonald has denied any wrongdoing. He has not been charged,
although a federal grand jury in Phoenix is looking into
allegations raised in the hearings.
   The council placed Thompson on leave March 10.
   MacDonald attorney Thomas J. Hynes of Farmington, N.M., declined
to comment on the ruling and said he wasn't sure if there would be
an appeal to the tribe's Supreme Court.
   ``That would be up to the chairman,'' he said.
   Neither MacDonald nor Thompson could not be reached for comment
Monday.
</TEXT>
