<DOCNO> AP890516-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-89 0148EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-US-Soviet     05-16 0517</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Soviet,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Some Praise, Some Criticism For Soviets</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration is mixing praise for
Mikhail S. Gorbachev's efforts to revamp Soviet economics and
politics with skepticism about the Soviet leader's proposals to
reduce nuclear weapons in Europe.
   ``What is going on in the Soviet Union is truly revolutionary
when you consider the economic and political system they have had
for the last 70 years,'' Secretary of State James A. Baker III said
Monday.
   Just back from Moscow and a 3{-hour meeting with Gorbachev, the
U.S. official said he favored normal trade with the Soviet Union,
which is now restricted by the 1974 Jackson-Vanik amendment, and
gave a positive appraisal of perestroika, the economic
restructuring Gorbachev outlined at length in their meeting.
   ``It's light years away from where they were a few years ago,''
Baker said. ``It's important to recognize that what is going on is
real.''
   Talking to a group of constituents of Sen. Christopher Dodd,
D-Conn., he said the Soviets are unilaterally reducing their
military forces, as urged by the United States.
   ``They're saying that their economic and political system has
failed,'' Baker said. ``They're having elections. They're trying to
open up politically and economically. Clearly they are coming in
our direction and we ought to welcome that.''
   In fact, Baker told the Connecticut group, ``They are singing
out of our own hymn book.''
   But he also said the United States should not let its guard
down, and he described Gorbachev's decision to withdraw 500
short-range nuclear missiles, bombs and artillery shells from
Eastern Europe as ``a very small step.''
   At the same time, a State Department spokesman denounced a
statement by Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze that
the Soviets might retain 200 nuclear missiles banned in a 1987
treaty with the United States if NATO proceeds with a program to
upgrade its short-range missiles.
   Spokesman Richard Boucher said, ``We think Shevardnadze's
remarks are an outlandish statement. One day the Soviets announce
small unilateral reductions; the next day they are talking about
breaking a recently concluded treaty.''
   Shevardnadze, on a visit to Bonn, West Germany, last Saturday,
said the Soviets might retain their SS-23s, which have a range of
310 miles, just within the range of banned missiles, or develop a
new short-range nuclear missile if NATO more than triples the range
of its Lance missiles.
   The program, which West Germany and several other NATO allies
are trying to delay, would extend the range of the Lance to about
250 miles. There are 88 Lance launchers, most of them in West
Germany, with about 700 single-warhead missiles.
   Boucher said the SS-23s undoubtedly were covered by the 1987 INF
treaty and short-range missiles were not covered. He said ``a look
at the text'' would confirm the U.S. position.
   ``We find it especially ironic that the Soviets threaten to
break the INF treaty in an effort to pressure the West on
short-range systems which they have just finished modernizing and
where they hold at least a 12-1 advantage over the West,'' the
spokesman said.
</TEXT>
