<FIRST>r w PM-ScotusRdp     05-16 0693</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus Rdp,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>High Court Rules Against Prisoners Again</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's prison inmates again find
themselves in a legal position they have faced often in the 1980s _
losers in a Supreme Court decision.
   The court, continuing to limit rights behind bars, gave prison
officials broad power Monday to decide what inmates may read and
who may visit them.
   In a pair of 6-3 rulings, the court made it easier for officials
to censor inmate reading materials and said inmates generally do
not have to be told why they are prohibited from having visitors.
   The court upheld the power of wardens to ban any publication at
federal prisons the wardens believe is ``detrimental to the
security, good order or discipline of the institution or ... might
facilitate criminal activity.''
   The justices ordered further hearings to determine whether
inmates should be allowed to read any of 46 publications federal
officials want to ban.
   Among the publications on the list, for example, was an issue of
The Call, a left-wing newspaper that included an article charging
``inhumane treatment ... by racist guards'' in federal prisons.
   Government lawyers had told the justices that between Sept. 1,
1986, and Aug. 31, 1987, some 1,700 publications were withheld out
of 1.8 million sent to federal inmates.
   In the prison visits case, Kentucky officials had argued that
regulations covering aspects of prison life from job assignments to
telephone privileges could be jeopardized by giving inmates a
due-process right to an explanation each time they are denied some
privilege.
   Justice Harry A. Blackmun wrote for the court in both rulings
against the inmates. Justices Thurgood Marshall, William J. Brennan
and John Paul Stevens dissented in each one.
   In both cases, the court reversed rulings that had favored the
inmates _ a result not uncommon during the past decade.
   In a key 1984 ruling, the court said inmates have absolutely no
right of privacy. The justices said inmates cannot depend on the
Constitution to protect them from allegedly unreasonable _ or even
malicious _ searches of their cells and seizure of their property
by prison guards.
   In 1981, the court ruled it is not automatically
unconstitutional to house two inmates in a cell designed for one.
   A 1983 ruling allowed prison officials to put inmates in
solitary confinement indefinitely after only an informal hearing,
even in states that have special laws to protect prisoners' rights.
   The court that year also ruled that state officials may transfer
inmates to another state at their own discretion, even if it means
the inmates will be thousands of miles from home.
   In 1985, the court ruled that officials do not immediately have
to supply reasons when they bar inmates from calling witnesses at
disciplinary hearings.
   And in 1987, the court upheld a rule that prohibits
correspondence between inmates in different prisons.
   In other matters Monday, the court:
   _Reinstated a Charlotte, N.C., man's lawsuit against five city
police officers by ruling unanimously that people who sue over
alleged police brutality must prove only that the officers acted
unreasonably, not ``maliciously and sadistically.''
   _Ruled unanimously in a case from New York City that civil fines
heaped on top of criminal penalties sometimes amount to
unconstitutional double jeopardy, multiple punishment for the same
crime.
   _Agreed to decide in a Pennsylvania case whether the Bush
administration may have to start giving Supplemental Security
Income benefits to, potentially, more than 250,000 disabled
children.
   _Turned down the appeal of an Oklahoma couple sentenced to two
years in prison for their ill child's death because they relied on
prayer and divine intervention rather than seek medical care.
   _Let stand a Massachusetts court's ruling that the public has no
constitutional right of access to a court document sealed by a
judge during a much-publicized murder prosecution.
   _Ruled, by a 5-4 vote in a Texas case, that investors who allege
they have been defrauded by their brokers must submit the dispute
to arbitration and may not sue in court if they have signed a
contract calling for such arbitration.
   _Refused to kill a California horse-racing figure's libel suit
against a newspaper, The Fresno Bee.
</TEXT>
