<DOCNO> AP890516-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-89 0234EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Fed-InterestRates     05-16 0785</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fed-Interest Rates,780</SECOND>
<HEAD>Steady Course by Fed Predicted</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: closed-door meetings; top prospects uncertain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal Reserve policy makers are likely to
adopt a wait-and-see attitude toward further interest rate hikes as
they scrutinize the economy for signs inflation has abated,
economists say.
   Signs of slower economic growth abounded as members of the
Federal Open Market Committee gathered for a closed-door meeting
today to set interest rate and monetary policy through June.
   But many analysts said it remains unclear whether the slowdown
has been sufficient to curb accelerating price increases and most
said they expected the central bank to leave credit policies
unchanged.
   The 12-member committee, composed of Federal Reserve Board
members and regional Fed bank presidents, meets in secret eight
times a year. The decisions made at today's meeting won't be
revealed until early July.
   ``This will be a time when they can sit back and relax a bit and
wait for further evidence,'' predicted former Fed member Lyle
Gramley, now chief economist at the Mortgage Bankers Association of
America. ``They ought to be breathing a bit of a sigh of relief.''
   The Fed has been walking a tightrope since March 1988 as it
engineered a rise in short-term interest rates of about 3
percentage points.
   Its aim has been to cool the economy just enough to prevent
inflation from spiraling out of control but not so much as to
topple the country into a recession.
   Finally, after months of increasingly tighter money, it looks
like the Fed is getting what it wants _ slower but continued growth
coupled with moderating price increases.
   In April, retail sales rose a less-than-expected 0.4 percent,
the unemployment rate ticked up to 5.3 percent and industrial
production rebounded only moderately from two weak months.
   Wholesale-price inflation, excluding a large spurt in gasoline
prices, actually dropped. That report Friday sent a wave of
euphoria through financial markets and pushed stocks to a
post-crash high.
   However, it was only a few months ago _ in January and February
_ that wholesale prices showed back-to-back surges of 1 percent,
and economists said the Fed isn't likely to declare victory over
inflation just yet.
   ``You can't afford to jump to conclusions on one month's
report,'' Gramley said. ``Inflation is like a glacier; once it gets
started its awfully hard to stop.''
   ``There are signs wage inflation is starting to heat up,''
agreed economist David Wyss of Data Resources Inc., a Lexington,
Mass., forecasting firm.
   Average hourly wages shot up 0.7 percent in April. Also,
Bethlehem Steel Corp. workers won an immediate 8 percent wage hike
earlier this month and Los Angeles teachers are seeking a 21
percent raise over two years.
   ``If that sort of thing becomes common, the Fed is going to have
to hit the brakes hard and that's almost certainly going to turn
into a recession,'' Wyss said.
   But economist David Jones of Aubrey G. Lanston &amp; Co., a
government securities dealer, predicted Fed officials would ``ever
so subtly ease back a bit.''
   ``I think the way that they will do it is to go to a neutral
stance, meaning they will be just as willing to ease or tighten. In
previous meetings they have always been balanced toward restraint.
That's a subtle shift, but it will be an important one,'' Jones
said.
   William C. Dunkelberg, dean of the Temple University business
school, said unchanged policy would permit interest rates, which
have edged down a bit over the last month, to drift a little
further if the market sees additional signs of slower growth or
moderating price hikes.
   ``If, in fact, the economy really is slowing down some, that
should reduce the demand for credit and that should put downward
pressure on interest rates without Fed action,'' Dunkelberg said.
   One analyst, economist Paul W. Boltz of T. Rowe Price Associates
in Baltimore, said the Fed, fearing that the sluggishness it
induced could get out of hand, may even lean explicitly toward
easier money.
   ``I think from their perspective a recession would be a
calamity. It would stop the ... process (of reducing the budget
deficit), it would greatly exacerbate the S&amp;L problem by causing
widespread bankruptcies and it would create problems with Third
World debt,'' Boltz said.
   Indeed, the Bush administration, which is counting on lower
interest rates to help it pursue its economic agenda, has changed
the tenor of its comments about the Fed from criticism to cautious
praise.
   ``It appears the Federal Reserve has paused to see what
cumulative effect their tightening has had,'' Michael Boskin,
President Bush's chief economic adviser, said in a speech last
week. ``That, it seems to me, is a sensible thing to do.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
