<FIRST>r w PM-North-Iran-Contra     05-16 0402</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-North-Iran-Contra,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Lawyers Renew Dismissal Motion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Saying the government's case was tainted,
Oliver North's lawyers are renewing a motion made before his
conviction to dismiss criminal charges against him because of his
1987 congressional testimony.
   North ``submits that it is impossible as a matter of law for the
government to make the requisite showing that no use has been
made'' of his congressional testimony given under a grant of
immunity, his lawyers asserted.
   The government made the ``extraordinary decision'' to compel
testimony from North, ``to broadcast his testimony to tens of
millions of people around the world, and then to indict and try him
for the matters as to which he had previously testified,'' North's
defense team said in a court filing Monday.
   North was convicted May 5 of aiding and abetting an obstruction
of Congress, destroying government documents and of taking an
illegal gratuity.
   If the court doesn't dismiss the indictment, a court hearing
ought to be held in which the government would attempt to show the
case was not tainted by his immunized testimony, said North's
lawyers.
   In a 1972 case entitled Kastigar v. United States, the Supreme
Court held that any direct or indirect use against a defendant of
testimony given under a grant of use immunity violates the Fifth
Amendment.
   North's lawyers submitted a 10-page list of documents and
information they said the prosecution must produce before any
hearing. They said any such inquiry includes a
``witness-by-witness, item-by-item showing'' of the sources for all
evidence presented by grand jury and trial witnesses.
   North says the prosecution must produce all materials in its
office referring to steps taken to comply with the requirement that
no use be made of the immunized testimony.
   North's lawyers said they want the prosecution to produce any
information showing how news reports were censored in the office to
eliminate information derived from the immunized testimony.
   ``This is not limited to news stories but also includes, for
example, political cartoons, presidential press conferences, talk
shows, and entertainment such as Johnny Carson's `Tonight Show,'
`Sesame Street,' Bob Hope's specials, or `Saturday Night Live,'''
said the court filing.
   North's attorneys asked for ``all redacted or screened copies of
every newspaper, magazine, periodical or other documentary
material, or any electronic transmission, which any member of the
IC staff read, saw, or heard'' after North was granted immunity.
</TEXT>
