<DOCNO> AP890516-0027 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-89 0243EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Panama-Carter     05-16 0178</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Panama-Carter,0184</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ex-President Says Trying to Seize Noriega Would Be Mistake</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Panama</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOT SPRINGS, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trying to seize Panamanian leader Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega to face drug charges in the United States
would be a mistake, former President Carter said.
   ``The best thing we could do for Noriega and the worst thing we
could do for ourselves is to send Marines into Panama and try to
catch this man,'' Carter told the Arkansas Bankers Association on
Monday.
   ``We shouldn't do anything in a belligerent way in Panama
because it would only lead to making Noriega a hero and he doesn't
deserve it.
   ``It would play into his hands and would make us undertake a
very bloody operation that might be unsuccessful,'' Carter said.
``It would also alienate every other nation in this hemisphere if
we invaded Panama.''
   Carter was among the international monitors in Panama for the
May 7 presidential elections. The opposition claimed victory, but
the Noriega-backed government nullified the presidential elections.
   Noriega is under indictment in the United States on drug charges.
</TEXT>
