<FIRST>r w PM-Alar-Apples     05-16 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Alar-Apples,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alar Use to be Halted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Apple growers are halting use of Alar in the
wake of decreasing apple sales because of reports linking the
controversial chemical to cancer.
   The International Apple Institute said its members have decided
to stop using Alar, which regulates growth and extends the shelf
life of the fruit.
   ``By September of this year, the already low levels of Alar will
be reduced to virtually zero,'' Derl I. Derr, president of the
International Apple Institute, based in nearby McLean, Va., said
Monday in a news conference. ``Simply, the U.S. apple industry is
not going to use Alar.''
   ``This action is not taken because we believe there is a health
risk associated with Alar, but because public confusion reigns
supreme and consumer confidence in apples is faltering,'' the
industry spokesman said.
   The Food and Drug Administration estimated on March 16 that Alar
was used on 10 percent of the nation's apple supply.
   Industry spokesmen say sales have been hurt severely by consumer
reaction to news reports focusing on assertions that Alar poses a
risk of cancer, particularly to children.
   Derr's prediction came as two new requests were made to the EPA
for an immediate ban on Alar. The requests came from the Natural
Resources Defense Council and consumer activist Ralph Nader.
   Janet S. Hathaway, an attorney for the NRDC, said at a news
conference that Alar will be applied to this year's crop in June if
the EPA does not take emergency action.
   Last weeekend, the EPA announced it has started a procedure that
could lead to an Alar ban in about 18 months, but Ms. Hathaway said
that wasn't quick enough.
   ``We believe that there is only one way to restore public
confidence, restore apple sales and protect public health,'' Ms.
Hathaway said. ``A total ban under EPA's suspension powers should
occur as of today.''
   EPA spokesman Al Heier said, ``The data we now have available is
preliminary data. We will get the final data by early next year and
at that time we hope to be able to take final cancellation action.''
   ``We do not believe eating apples or any food that has been
treated with Alar poses a grave risk. We think there is some risk,
but we think the risk is small for the additional year'' before the
EPA ban takes effect, he said.
   On Capitol Hill, Nader told the Senate subcommittee on toxic
substances that Congress ``should ban Alar by name, unilaterally
and immediately.''
   Nader said there is ``a convergence'' of interest between
consumers who don't want Alar on apples and apple growers hurt by
plummeting sales. He maintained the only opposition to an immediate
ban comes from suppliers of Alar, or daminozide.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
