<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Glance     05-16 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Glance,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Anti-Crime Proposals at a Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush-Crime</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are main provisions of the
$1.2 billion anti-crime package President Bush proposed Monday.
   Bush would:
   _Make permanent a ban on imported semiautomatic assault rifles _
if the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms rules they are not
for sport _ but allow U.S. manufacturers to keep making and selling
such weapons.
   _Ban semiautomatic ammunition clips of more than 15 rounds.
   _Double the current five-year minimum sentence for using a
semiautomatic firearm in a crime.
   _Block the practice of dropping many gun-use charges through
plea bargaining.
   _Spend $1 billion for new prison construction; identify
government properties and facilities for conversion to jails and
prisons.
   _Execute people who commit such federal offenses as murder for
hire, killings by federal prisoners serving life sentences,
terrorist murders of American citizens, and murders of hostages.
Also allow executions for such crimes as treason and espionage
under provisions now in disuse because statutes do not satisfy
Supreme Court guidelines.
   _Authorize 825 new federal agents and staff in the Bureau of
Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms, the U.S. Marshals Service and the
FBI.
   _Amend the Armed Career Criminal statute to include juvenile
convictions when deciding whether someone is a habitual criminal
and thus subject to an enhanced sentence.
   _Expand the existing ban on firearm sales to people convicted of
certain violent crimes, to cover anyone convicted of violent
misdemeanor offenses.
   _Add 1,600 positions in federal prosecutors' offices.
</TEXT>
