<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-89 0323EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-TrainDerail     05-16 0616</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Train Derail,0634</SECOND>
<HEAD>Authorities: Engineer on Runaway Train Silent on Faulty Brakes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARBARA METZLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN BERNARDINO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An engineer at the rear of a
runaway freight train that killed four people knew the brakes
weren't working on one of the engines but failed to notify the lead
engineer, investigators said.
   Engineer Larry Hill was interviewed by federal investigators
Monday along with his brakeman, Robert Waterbury. Hill was in
charge of guiding the brakes on the train's rear engines while the
lead engineer, Frank Holland, who was injured in Friday's crash,
watched the front ones.
   The Southern Pacific freight train jumped the tracks at 90 mph
Friday on a curve trains are supposed to take at 30 mph. Cars
slammed into six homes, burying two boys who died and killing two
crewmen.
   The brakes were faulty on at least two of the train's six
locomotives, the National Transportation Safety Board said Sunday.
   ``We learned that as the train crested the hill, engineer
Holland radioed Hill asking if he was giving all that he had, all
the dynamic braking that he had,'' said James Kolstad, acting NTSB
chairman.
   Hill answered ``yes,'' even though he told investigators he was
aware the dynamic brakes weren't working, Kolstad said Monday night.
   ``We asked him why there was not more communication, and he did
not have an answer,'' Kolstad said. The engineers also did not
communicate in the moments before the train plunged through the
homes, Kolstad said.
   Locomotives have two kinds of braking systems. Air brakes apply
pressure to the wheels, much like a car, while dynamic braking uses
the engine to slow the train, similar to downshifting in a car.
   Investigators also interviewed workers who loaded the train with
sandy sodium carbonate, which is used to make potash, in Rosamond,
said Ted Lopatkiewicz, an NTSB spokesman.
   A shipping document indicated ``each of the hopper cars had
about a two-thirds load, but we have witnesses that say some of the
cars were loaded up to the edge,'' he said.
   Crew members may not have known how heavy their train was and
may have miscalculated the braking capability during their descent
from 4,109-foot Cajon Pass into the Los Angeles basin, said
Lopatkiewicz.
   On Sunday night, investigators said two of the train's five
crewman had previous safety violations. Tests to indicate if the
crew was using alcohol or drugs on Friday were incomplete,
authorities said.
   Holland was cited for driving a train too fast in March 1986 and
for failing to connect brake lines properly between locomotives in
February 1988, Kolstad said. Holland was in fair condition Monday
with a collapsed lung in the intensive-care unit at St. Bernardine
Medical Center.
   Brakeman Allan R. Riess, who was killed, had been cited in
October for failing to act when an engineer exceeded authorized
speed, Kolstad said.
   Conductor Everett S. Crown of Bakersfield, who also was killed,
had no violations on his record. The records of Waterbury, 57, and
Hill, 42, who escaped serious injury, were unavailable.
   NTSB officials examined crew members' job records for any
pattern of recklessness. But Lopatkiewicz said, ``it is not unusual
after a number of years on the line for trainmen to have violations
on their record.''
   Riess' brother-in-law, Dale Jenkins, said the 43-year-old
Bakersfield man had failed to report the October incident because
of tremendous pressure from superiors at work. But he said, ``Allan
was real conscientious.''
   Southern Pacific spokesman Jerry Pera declined to comment on
crew safety violations, saying the NTSB had asked the railroad not
to talk about the investigation while it continued.
   About 250 people remained at hotels Monday because of the
accident that wrecked their neighborhood, authorities said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890516-0033 </DOCNO>
