<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     05-16 0567</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agencies Seek to Improve Bike Safety, Increase Use of Helmets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two federal agencies say they'll work together
to boost bicycle safety, including increasing the use of helmets
which officials say are worn by fewer than one in 10 riders.
   Officials of the Consumer Product Safety Commission also said
Monday they are evaluating several types of bicycle helmets to
determine effectiveness in preventing injuries and will consider a
proposal from safety groups to set uniform federal standards.
   An engineer for the commission, John Preston, said testing
indicates that helmets without a hard shell may be just as
effective in absorbing the energy of a fall or collision as those
with a hard shell.
   The comission and the National Highway Safety Administration
signed a memorandum Monday that sets up communication between the
two agencies on bicycle safety research and seeks to coordinate
local and national efforts to increase public understanding of
bicycle safety requirements.
   A group of safety and consumer groups organized as the National
Safe Kids Campaign petitioned the safety commission on Monday to
set performance standards for both adult- and child-size bicycle
helmets. The group said federal standards would help reduce the
1,000 deaths and half-million serious injuries each year in bicycle
accidents.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Bush Administration Says Wheelchair Lift Decision `Burdensome'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Requiring wheelchair lifts on all new public
buses would put a costly burden on transit agencies, Bush
administration officials told a federal appeals court.
   Before Monday's court hearing, 13 disabled spectators were
wheeled into the courtroom. Some spectators wore Revolutionary
War-era hats.
   ``This is the case that will mean independence for disabled
people,'' said Stephen Gold, attorney for Americans Disabled for
Accessible Public Transportation, or ADAPT, which filed the lawsuit
the government is appealing.
   The nation should keep the current system of balancing special
services for the disabled with the costs, U.S. Transportation
Department lawyer Jeffrey Clair told the 3rd U.S. Circuit of
Appeals.
   The case has attracted the attention of dozens of
disabled-rights groups, many angered by the government's decision
to ask the full appeals court to review a decision handed down by a
three-judge panel Feb. 13.
   In the 2-1 decision, the panel ruled the Department of
Transportation failed to provide the handicapped ``equal
accessibility'' as intended by Congress. The judges invalidated a
Transportation Department provision allowing communities to provide
van service instead.
   Clair said requiring lifts on all new buses would be too rigid
and ``overly burdensome.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<NOTE>Labor Department Says Youth Labor Force Smaller Than Last Summer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of 16- to 24-year-olds seeking work
this summer will be about 706,000 below the level of last year
because of a continued population decline in that age group, the
government says.
   An estimated 3.3 million people in that age group, mostly
students seeking summer jobs and high school and college graduates
looking for permanent jobs, will enter the labor force between now
and July, the Labor Department said.
   It said there were 21.3 million people aged 16 to 24 in the
civilian labor force as of last month and projected the number
would swell to 24.6 million by July, down from 25.3 million last
year.
   The 21.3 million April figure is down from last year as well.
There were 21.6 million 16- to 24-year-olds who either had jobs or
were looking for jobs in April 1988, the department said.
</TEXT>
