<FIRST>u a PM-SpringBreakBacklash Bjt   05-16 0661</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spring Break Backlash, Bjt,0685</SECOND>
<HEAD>Many Feel Students Out of Control This Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Excessive drinking, gridlock and
trashed hotels are causing some residents to question whether the
welcome mat to this spring break mecca should be rolled up.
   When Fort Lauderdale more or less told students to go elsewhere
for their weeks of unbridled partying, Daytona Beach took over as
the nation's top spring break destination.
   It attracted 500,000 students during the four weeks that ended
in early April, according to Georgia Carter, of the tourism
promotion agency Destination Daytona.
   Although students spent $100 million here, they left behind
angry residents who complained about car stereos blaring throughout
the nights on clogged streets, and youths urinating on lawns and
passing out in driveways.
   ``It's basically what happened here,'' said Carolyn Michaels,
assistant director of tourism, convention and business development
for the Fort Lauderdale Chamber of Commerce.
   Fort Lauderdale officials last year adopted plans to renovate
the beachfront area into a family-oriented resort, cracking down on
public drinking and shelving marketing campaigns at college
campuses.
   More than 200 miles north of Fort Lauderdale, Daytona Beach's
success in attracting students has divided residents.
   On one side are those who dread the hordes of drunken students
and on the other are those who see dollar signs for the motels,
hotels, restaurants, bars and gift shops.
   ``Daytona Beach likes to have the money, but they don't want the
problems,'' said Lt. Jimmy Powell, head of the Daytona Beach office
of the state Division of Alcoholic Beverages and Tobacco.
   ``Daytona is going to have to decide if they are going to
control it or get rid of the whole thing,'' he said. ``There are a
lot of upset people in Daytona Beach.''
   Many have said enough is enough.
   This is a city election year and politicans are apt to be
responsive to residents' concerns.
   ``A lot of citizens are saying we'll give you one more year'' to
fix the problems of spring break or they'll seek to abolish the
annual rites of spring in much the way that Fort Lauderdale has,
said Dick Moores, immediate past president of the local motel
association.
   ``We are going to solve the spring break problem, we've got
to,'' said Moores, who owns the Daytona Sands Beach Motel.
   Some attribute the problems to Playboy magazine, which featured
a risque pictorial from Daytona Beach in its April issue, and to
MTV, the popular music video channel, which has broadcast live from
``the World's Most Famous Beach'' for the past two years.
   ``MTV gave kids the impression that in Daytona is where anything
goes,'' Moores said. ``We don't want them back.''
   Allan Cohen, whose family owns the Texan Motel, disagrees.
   ``It could be devastating if they (MTV) don't show in Daytona
Beach,'' said Cohen, whose motel was used by MTV this spring.
   For years, he said, tourism officials have worked to attract
young people.
   ``Daytona Beach didn't happen overnight. We've been fighting and
fighting to get the break here. We got the break so big it was
unbelievable,'' Cohen said. ``Everybody got caught with their pants
down.''
   The Daytona Beach Chamber of Commerce recently established
subcommittees to address the problems.
   Some of the solutions under consideration include setting up
portable toilets; preventing youngsters from entering residential
neighborhoods near the beach; restricting sales of beer and alcohol
to certain times; banning beach concerts; and taxing beer.
   ``The Number One culprit in the whole thing was over consumption
of alcohol,'' Moores said.
   One of those who dealt daily with the alcohol problem was
Powell, with the state alcoholic beverage division. His office made
1,200 arrests during spring break, but he said he could have made
12,000 arrests if he had enough officers.
   Despite the problems, many are confident about reaching
solutions before next year's invasion.
   ``Everybody is ready to give spring break another shot,'' Cohen
said, ``but they want to see more control.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
