<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0177</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Nikkei Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar held its ground against the yen Tuesday,
and share prices rose sharply on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which lost 150.04 points
Monday, regained 210.16 points, or 0.62 percent, to bounce back to
33,926.45.
   The dollar finished trading at 137.00 yen, up 0.20 yen from
Monday's 136.80-yen close.
   After opening higher at an 18-month record of 137.30 yen, the
dollar ranged between 136.95 yen and 137.65 yen.
   During the morning session, ``Japanese investors bought the
dollar like a sponge absorbs water,'' Daiwa Bank dealer Takamasa
Yamasaki said.
   But the currency fell slightly in the afternoon as investors
started to sell it in profit-taking, other traders said.
   Meanwhile, the Bank of Japan sought to support the yen during
the morning session by selling about $400 million. The central bank
does not comment on its activities.
   On the stock exchange, dealers said the Nikkei rose sharply in
the afternoon session as Japanese investors started to buy
high-tech issues.
</TEXT>
