<FIRST>r a PM-CottonClub     05-16 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cotton Club,0506</SECOND>
<HEAD>Producer Wins Battle Not to Testify in Murder Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A witness who said he helped dispose of
murder weapons implicated four people in the slaying of a producer
but never mentioned former Paramount production chief Robert Evans,
who won a battle not to testify.
   The slaying has been linked to Evans' movie ``The Cotton Club,''
and police reports have suggested that witnesses will implicate
Evans. The producer invoked Fifth Amendment protection against self
incrimination.
   Municipal Judge Patti Jo McKay had threatened to jail Evans, who
is not charged in the slaying of New York theatrical producer Roy
Radin, for contempt for refusing to testify.
   But on Monday, McKay said she was swayed by arguments from
Evans' attorney, who cited a report in Saturday's Los Angeles Times
that Evans has been linked by two potential witnesses to the
killing.
   Evans, producer of such hits as ``The Godfather,''
``Chinatown,'' and ``Love Story,'' had been scheduled as the first
witness in a preliminary hearing.
   But on Monday, as he listened nervously, McKay and supervising
Municipal Court Judge David Horwitz excused him from testifying.
They based their rulings on the published reports. Evans' lawyer
has said in court Evans is ``absolutely innocent of any
involvement'' and would testify if granted immunity from
prosecution.
   ``At this point, unless the people are prepared to offer Mr.
Evans immunity as a witness, he cannot be forced to testify in the
Radin matter,'' said McKay.
   Deputy District Attorney David Conn refused to give him immunity
and told reporters he would not reconsider that decision.
   The hearing's first witness was Carl Plzak, who worked as a
security guard for defendant Karen Delayne ``Laynie'' Greenberger
and for former Hustler magazine publisher Larry Flynt, who is not a
defendant.
   Mrs. Greenberger, also known as Elaine Jacobs, is credited with
having introduced Evans and Radin who negotiated financing of ``The
Cotton Club.'' She is charged with murder as are three former Flynt
security guards, William Molony Mentzer, Alex Lamota Marti and
William Ulmer Lowe. Lowe is fighting extradition in Maryland.
   The hearing is to determine if there is enough evidence for the
defendants to stand trial.
   Plzak testified that all four defendants were involved in
Radin's killing and that it was related to a theft of cocaine and
money. He said he helped the defendants get rid of the murder
weapons.
   Evans was in the midst of negotiations with Radin to raise funds
for ``The Cotton Club'' in 1983 when the producer disappeared. At
the time, a dispute had arisen about Mrs. Greenberger's demand for
part of the film's profits.
   Radin was seen stepping into a limousine with Mrs. Greenberger
on May 13, 1983, en route to dinner at the fashionable La Scala
restaurant in Beverly Hills. His body was found a month later in a
dry riverbed 65 miles north of Los Angeles. He had been shot in the
head.
</TEXT>
