<FIRST>r a PM-INS-MarcosParty     05-16 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-INS-Marcos Party,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>Immigration Official Defends Marcos Prayer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM DAHLBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. immigration official says he was acting
out of compassion when he led a prayer that Ferdinand Marcos be
allowed to return to the Philippines.
   Harold Ezell said Monday he led the prayer during an Aug. 3
party where he also danced with Marcos' wife, Imelda, because the
deposed Philippine president had expressed a desire to return home
to bury his mother.
   ``It has nothing to do with U.S. policy. It has something to do
with a human being who has feelings as I have,'' said Ezell,
western regional commissioner of the U.S. Immigration and
Naturalization Service.
   Ezell said he now regrets attending the party at Marcos' mansion
overlooking Honolulu, but doesn't regret offering the prayer.
   ``I think I can express my personal views,'' said Ezell. He said
his father, a minister, also had died a year earlier and he
sympathized with Marcos about the death of the ousted Philippines
president's mother.
   ``If it's wrong to pray for a person, I'll take the heat for
that,'' Ezell said.
   Ezell, answering questions following a news conference to
promote the agency's amnesty program, also said he didn't think
there was anything wrong with asking immigration officials from
several western states to join him in the prayer during the party.
   ``Americans are free to do what they want,'' Ezell said. ``They
don't have to join in. I'm not the commander or dictator of the
immigration service.''
   A videotape obtained by The Honolulu Advertiser shows Ezell
embracing Marcos and dancing with Marcos' wife while Ezell's wife
danced with the former president. The newspaper did not reveal the
source of the videotape.
   ``Eat your heart out,'' Ezell called out as he danced with Mrs.
Marcos to the beat of ``Don't Throw My Love Away.''
   Ezell noted that the party was held before a New York grand jury
indicted the Marcoses on racketeering charges in October. They are
accused of looting more than $100 million from the Philippines to
buy art and real estate in New York.
   The commissioner said too much was being made of the immigration
officials attending the event.
   ``To me it's ridiculous, it's a social event,'' Ezell said.
``But if I had to do it over again, I would not.''
   U.S. policy since Marcos fled to exile in Hawaii in 1986 has
been to support Philippine President Corazon Aquino's repeated
refusals to allow Marcos return home. Mrs. Aquino has cited
national security in denying his requests.
</TEXT>
