<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     05-16 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0356</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nikkei, Dollar Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index rebounded
today, and the dollar continued rising against the yen despite
central bank intervention in support of the Japanese currency.
   The dollar closed at 137.00 yen, up 0.20 yen from Monday's
136.80-yen close. It opened at an 18-month high of 137.30 yen and
ranged between 136.95 yen and 137.65 yen.
   The dollar has gained 2.56 yen over the past four trading days.
   The Bank of Japan sold between $400 million and $500 million
during the morning session to check the dollar's increase, traders
said. The Bank of Japan does not comment publicly on its market
intervention.
   Ichiro Ikeda, a trader with Chemical Bank in Tokyo, said the
dollar's downward trend in the afternoon, however, was the result
of profit-taking, and not of central bank intervention.
   ``Having bought all those dollars, a majority of participants
seemed to start collecting profits,'' Ikeda said.
   On the stock exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 issues
rebounded to 33,926.45, regaining 210.16 points, or 0.62 percent.
It had lost 150.04 points Monday.
   New Japan Securities dealer Kazuhiro Murata attributed the
index's sharp rise in the afternoon session to strong performances
by hi-tech issues.
   ``Investors turned their interest to hi-tech issues, trying to
take advantage of the yen's recent weakness against the dollar,''
he said. The lower yen helps exports.
   Another dealer at a Japanese brokerage, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said institutional investors remained on the sidelines
because of concern over possible interest rate hikes and continuing
political uncertainty.
   Market sources have been speculating that the dollar's sharp
rise against the yen could lead to higher interest rates in Japan.
   Meanwhile, the governing Liberal Democratic Party has not been
able to find a successor for Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita, who
has announced he is resigning to take responsibility for an
influence-peddling scandal.
   The yen's weakness on the foreign exchange market also
discouraged stock investors, the dealer said.
   Trading was thin, with first section volume estimated at 600
million shares, up from Monday's 400 million.
</TEXT>
