<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-89 0513EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CarrierFire     05-16 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Carrier Fire,0447</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Sailors Died of Asphyxiation, Navy Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The two sailors killed in a fire aboard the
aircraft carrier USS America died of asphyxiation, the Navy said.
   Petty Officer 3rd Class Richard E. Childress, 22, of Ham Lake,
Minn., and Airman Recruit Larry J. Brunson, 19, of Akron, Ohio,
were on watch in a jet fuel pump room when the fire broke out
Saturday evening as the ship was cruising several hundred miles off
North Carolina.
   ``They sounded the alarm and were evacuating the space when they
were overcome by fumes and noxious gas,'' Lt. Cmdr. Michael John, a
Navy spokesman, said Monday night.
   Both were asphyxiated, John said.
   A team of Navy investigators on Monday flew from Norfolk Naval
Air Station to the carrier, said John.
   In addition to seeking a cause of the fire, the team will assess
the damage to determine how and where the ship will be repaired, he
said.
   John said a shipboard memorial service was held for the two
sailors. Their bodies were returned to Norfolk on Sunday.
   The 1,047-foot carrier, which left here Thursday with a crew of
about 5,000, continued toward the Mediterranean Sea for a six-month
tour of duty.
   Childress' stepfather, Timothy Holleman, said Sunday that Navy
officials told him that Childress and Brunson apparently noticed a
fuel leak while working the fire watch in a pump room. The carrier
contains miles of pipes through which jet fuel circulates.
   Childress apparently notified the bridge of the problem and was
returning to the room when an explosion occurred, Holleman said.
Officials told the family that Brunson might have died in the
explosion and that Childress might have died going back into the
room, possibly to look for Brunson, Holleman said.
   The fire was the third fatal blaze aboard a Navy ship in less
than a month. Before last month, the Navy had had three fatal
shipboard fires in the last five years, said Lt. Bruce Cole, a Navy
spokesman in Washington.
   An Apri1 19 explosion and fire in a gun turret on the battleship
USS Iowa killed 47 sailors while the ship was off Puerto Rico. On
May 9, six sailors died in an engine room fire on the supply ship
USS White Plains in the South China Sea.
   John said there is no evidence linking the three fires, and the
Navy said it had made no changes because of the blazes.
   ``We place great emphasis on safety and on training on a daily
basis in every ship,'' said Navy Lt. Cmdr. Craig Quigley, a
spokesman in Washington.
</TEXT>
