<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-89 0523EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Lawyer-Weapons     05-16 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lawyer-Weapons,0465</SECOND>
<HEAD>Weapons Charges Dropped; Government Misconduct Found</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DURANGO, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge who dismissed weapons charges
against a lawyer arrested as part of an undercover drug
investigation said law enforcement officials may have committed
perjury in the case.
   The false charges were filed in La Plata County Court here
against an undercover deputy to give the officer a reason to hire
lawyer Robin Auld to defend him, District Court Judge Richard Brown
said Monday.
   ``This court is not aware of any case or statute which sanctions
the filing of false and perjured documents in an official court
proceeding as part of an undercover operation,'' Brown wrote.
   The government plan had called for the undercover officer to pay
Auld in drugs for his legal services, and then pressure Auld to
``set up'' drug traffickers in southwest Colorado, according to
testimony in previous hearings.
   Auld, 43, refused to accept drugs but later took possession of
an Uzi machine gun, according to testimony. The prosecution charged
he took the gun as payment; Auld contended he kept it as collateral.
   The gun belonged to the Durango Police Department on loan from
the FBI, according to court documents.
   Auld's trial was to have started May 22 in Durango.
   Brown, a visiting judge who heard the case after 6th Judicial
District judges in Durango disqualified themselves, said, ``The
public has a right to demand and to expect that the courts will do
their utmost to remain impartial and to promote the public's
confidence in the integrity of the courts.''
   Filing the false affidavits was ``an impermissible taint upon
the integrity and impartiality of the courts,'' he wrote.
   Auld said he was ``very happy'' with the ruling, but did not
want to comment because the decision might be appealed.
   ``It takes guts, but it's the right thing. He (Brown) wouldn't
put up with the corruption of court records,'' said Hal Haddon,
Auld's lawyer.
   A notice of claim seeking at least $1 million in civil damages
on Auld's behalf has been filed, but the attorney has not brought a
formal lawsuit.
   Keith Cross, the special prosecutor in the case, said he will
appeal.
   ``If this decision stands, it means the attorney never has to
face a jury on fairly serious charges,'' Cross said.
   Cross said he considered the false affidavits before he filed
the charges of theft by receiving and possession of a dangerous
weapon against Auld.
   ``In my opinion, there were no indictable offenses committed by
the DA or law enforcement officials,'' Cross said. ``There is no
question that two documents filed and sworn to weren't true, but I
believe there is a difference in doing that and taking the stand
and perjuring themselves.''
</TEXT>
