<FIRST>r a PM-PigeonProblems     05-16 0204</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pigeon Problems,0210</SECOND>
<HEAD>NYC Pigeons Don't Give a Hoot About the Scare-Owls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Down at the landmark Tweed Courthouse, city
officials posted plastic owls to try to scare away the
peril-dropping pigeons. But it isn't working.
   ``The owls are turning into pussycats,'' said Ed Barbini, a
spokesman for the General Services Department.
   The exterior of the marble building behind City Hall is in the
throes of renovation. In December, officials strung up a dozen
18-inch-high plastic owls, hoping they would keep away the pigeons
whose droppings contain a natural acid that harms stone.
   They even moved the bogus birds around for the sake of realism.
   But it didn't work for long. These are street-wise pigeons.
   ``They're basically stupid animals, but not that stupid,'' said
Mike Feller, chief naturalist for the Parks Department.
   When the $20 million renovation is done, the city plans more
permanent and proven measures to keep the pigeons from perching on
the courthouse ledges.
   Birds get a mild shock, for example, when they run across City
Hall, thanks to low-voltage wiring. And at Brooklyn Borough Hall,
the inviting bronze statue of Justice atop a cupola becomes less
attractive when a pigeon-troubling ultrasound device disturbs the
sound waves.
</TEXT>
