<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-89 0556EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-PolarTrek     05-16 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Polar Trek,0395</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tired, Weatherbeaten Explorers Head Home After North Pole Trek</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RESOLUTE, Northwest Territories (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eight explorers who
trekked 620 miles to the North Pole to draw attention to humanity's
assault on the fragile Arctic environment began their journey home
looking haggard but happy.
   The team on Monday flew to Eureka and then to their base camp in
Resolute Monday night.
   The explorers _ from Britain, Canada, the United States, the
Soviet Union, Japan, Australia and West Germany _ reached the North
Pole on Sunday and planted a U.N. flag. They were to fly to Ottawa
today.
   With their uncut hair and sunburned faces, the team members
appeared haggard and exhausted on Monday night.
   Expedition leader Robert Swan of Britain told a news conference
that he hoped the trek, called Icewalk, achieved its goal of
bringing attention to the environment and would spur politicians to
do more to protect nature.
   ``We've got to work together as one world to take on the
environment,'' said Swan, who became the first person to walk to
the North Pole and South Pole. He had reached the South Pole in
1986.
   The adventurers, who walked and skied, said temperatures were as
low as 67 degrees below zero during the 56-day trek.
   All suffered some health problems, from frostbite to influenza,
but the American, Darryl Roberts, 23, of New York, suffered the
worst.
   Severe frostbite on his feet made him limp much of the time, but
he never thought of quitting, said Roberts, the first American to
walk to the North Pole.
   ``With the moral support of the other team members, I knew I was
going to be able to make it,'' he said.
   The adventurers left Cape Aldrich on Ellesmere Island in
Canada's Northwest Territories on March 20.
   They made their journey in an effort to spur political action on
halting pollution and slowing down global warming _ the so-called
Greenhouse effect _ which is produced by the combustion of fossil
fuels.
   Icewalk had a high-power public relations operation promoting it
and corporate sponsorship supporting its $4 million budget.
   It differed from other Arctic expeditions because participants
used only human power to travel and take supplies along in sledges
that each carry about 250 pounds of cargo.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890516-0056 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-89 0602EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DisabledAccess     05-16 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Disabled Access,0461</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Says It Can't Afford Wheelchair Lifts On All New Buses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation cannot afford the $90 million
annual cost of requiring transit systems to equip new buses with
wheelchair lifts, a Bush administration lawyer told a federal
appeals court.
   Instead, communities should stick with the current system of
balancing special services for the disabled against the costs of
those services, U.S. Department of Transportation attorney Jeffrey
Clair told the 3rd Circuit of Appeals on Monday.
   The case has attracted the attention of dozens of
disabled-rights groups, many angered by the government's decision
to ask the full appeals court to review a Feb. 13 decision by a
three-judge panel.
   In the 2-1 ruling, the panel said the Department of
Transportation failed to provide the disabled equal accessibility
as intended by Congress.
   The panel struck down regulations that transit systems need
spend no more than 3 percent of their average annual operating
costs on measures for the disabled, so long as the government
approves. It also disallowed a provision allowing communities to
meet obligations by providing special vans that must be reserved in
advance.
   Before Monday's hearing, building security officials helped
wheel 13 disabled spectators into the courtroom. Some observers
wore hats reminiscent of the Revolutionary War era.
   ``This is the case that will mean independence for disabled
people,'' said Stephen Gold, attorney for Americans Disabled for
Accessible Public Transportation, or ADAPT, which filed the lawsuit
the government is appealing.
   Clair said requiring lifts on all new buses would be too rigid
and ``overly burdensome.'' He said lifts on 50 percent of buses was
more acceptable.
   He recited a quip attributed to the late Sen. Everett Dirksen:
``A billion here and a billion there, pretty soon you're talking
about real money.''
   Clair botched the quote, substituting millions for billions, and
was corrected by one of the judges. But he said the idea was an
approach ``that allows communities to respond with a program
tailored to local needs.''
   A wheelchair lift costs $10,000 to $15,000, while a bus costs up
to $200,000. In its petition, the government said transit agencies
across the country would pay a total of $90 million annually for
the lifts.
   ADAPT merely wants the court to require lifts on new buses,
meaning entire fleets probably will not be accessible until the
year 2001, said Timothy Cook, an ADAPT lawyer.
   Cook argued that van service denies the handicapped spontaneous
use of mass transit by requiring the disabled to make reservations
up to 24 hours in advance.
   ``Don't perpetuate forever a clearly inferior system because
that would be contrary to the rule of Congress,'' Cook said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890516-0057 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-89 0618EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     05-16 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell in moderate European trading this
morning. Gold prices were mixed.
   Foreign currency dealers said the drop on the heels of Monday's
surge was the result of profit-taking and consolidation. European
markets, except Britain's and Italy's, were closed Monday for the
Pentecost holiday.
   Traders said they expect positive dollar-buying sentiment to
push the dollar higher unless there is some decisive action taken
by central banks.
   ``The trend is still very strongly upward,'' said a trader in
Milan, Italy. ``Fundamentally, nothing has changed, but there's a
bit of a reflective pause.''
   In Tokyo, where trading ends as Europe's business day beings,
the dollar closed up 0.20 yen at 137.00 yen, despite reported
intervention by the Bank of Japan. The dollar has gained 2.56 yen
over the last four trading days.
   Later in London, the dollar traded at 136.85 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Monday:
   _1.9366 West German marks, down from 1.9415
   _1.7330 Swiss francs, down from 1.7438
   _6.5465 French francs, down from 6.5725
   _2.1839 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1905
   _1,408.50 Italian lire, down from 1,411.00.
   _1.1876 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1905.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.6455, more expensive for
buyers than $1.6385 late Monday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $374.55, up from $374.00
late Monday. At midmorning, the city's five major bullion dealers
fixed a recommended price of $374.40.
   In Zurich, gold was quoted at a bid 374.40 dollars, down from
379.25 late Friday. Bullion markets were closed in Switzerland on
Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 69 cents an ounce to close at
$375.99.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.51 a troy
ounce, down from $5.53 late Monday.
</TEXT>
