<HEAD>Showers, Thunderstorms in Plains, Appalachians</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 7th graf pvs, `Fair weather ...' to add
forecast; picks up 8th graf, `Temperatures at ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms continued across parts of the Plains
and the Appalachians this morning.
   Severe storms hit Texas Monday evening, with tornadoes sighted
near Wildorado and Hereford in the northwest part of the state.
There were no reports of damage or injuries.
   Thunderstorms also dropped golf ball-size hail in northwest
Texas and nickel-size hail in southern Oklahoma, while hail the
size of goose eggs broke windows in homes around Endee, N.M.
   Powerful storms also hit parts of the central and northern
Plains, hitting Cody, Wyo., with dime-size hail and generating 60
mph wind gusts near Goodland, Kan.
   Showers and thunderstorms this morning covered much of northern
Texas, southern Oklahoma and southwestern Arkansas, as well as from
western Kansas to eastern Wyoming.
   Low pressure off the middle Atlantic Coast continued to produce
showers and thunderstorms from North Carolina to the lower Great
Lakes.
   Fair weather prevailed across the rest of the nation, although
fog was developing in South Carolina, West Virginia and Upper
Michigan.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from
southern Mississippi across Louisiana to much of Texas, Oklahoma,
Kansas, western Nebraska, and western South Dakota. Thunderstorms
may be severe in the southern Plains. Showers and thunderstorms
were forecast across much of the Rocky Mountains and parts of Utah,
Nevada and Idaho. Showers were predicted from Virginia to the lower
Great Lakes and northern Atlantic Coast states.
   Highs were expected to be in the 50s and 60s from New England to
the lower Great Lakes and the mid-Atlantic states, and from Montana
across Colorado and northern Arizona, eastern Nevada, much of Idaho
and Washington, and the southern coast of California; the 80s in
Florida, from western Georgia across western Tennessee, much of the
Mississippi Valley, eastern Oklahoma and much of Texas; and the 70s
elsewhere.
   Temperatures at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 34 degrees at Yellowstone
Park, Wyo., to 81 degrees at Corpus Christi, Texas.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 57 fair; Boston 48 foggy; Buffalo 53 foggy;
Charleston, S.C. 67 fair; Cincinnati 50 fair; Cleveland 49 foggy;
Detroit 49 cloudy; Miami 75 partly cloudy; New York 55 rain;
Philadelphia 59 cloudy; Pittsburgh 50 rain; Portland, Maine 48
foggy; Washington 59 rain.
   _Central: Bismarck 58 partly cloudy; Chicago 53 fair;
Dallas-Fort Worth 72 cloudy; Denver 47 cloudy; Des Moines 58 partly
cloudy; Indianapolis 51 fair; Kansas City 60 cloudy;
Minneapolis-St. Paul 62 fair; Nashville 51 fair; New Orleans 72
foggy; St. Louis 63 cloudy.
   _West: Albuquerque 58 cloudy; Anchorage 43 partly cloudy; Las
Vegas 65 fair; Los Angeles 57 fair; Phoenix 69 rain; Salt Lake City
47 fair; San Diego 61 cloudy; San Francisco 53 fair; Seattle 53
partly cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 54 fair; Toronto 52 cloudy.
