<FIRST>r a PM-StanfordRacism     05-16 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stanford Racism,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Students Occupy President's Office</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STANFORD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fifty-five students protesting racism on
the Stanford University campus were arrested following a takeover
of the president's office.
   Meanwhile, at Michigan State University in East Lansing, a
sit-in at the school's administration building by black students
entered its eighth day today.
   MSU President John DiBiaggio resumed meetings with black
students on Monday who were demanding, among other things, more
black faculty members.
   The peaceful sit-in at Stanford attracted several hundred
supporters Monday and prompted 12 faculty members to sign a
statement of support deploring the use of police and asking
university president Donald Kennedy to negotiate with the students.
   ``I think it's only the beginning, actually,'' said Julie Su,
20, a spokeswoman for the Asian American Students' Association.
``It shows students aren't going to let down, they aren't going to
be intimidated.''
   Most of those arrested were released after being cited for
misdemeanors that included unlawful asssembly, trespassing and
failure to disperse, said university spokeswoman Eileen Walsh.
   About 60 students occupied or barricaded Kennedy's office Monday
morning. Daylong negotiations between students and university
officials failed, and Santa Clara County Sheriff's deputies began
arresting protesters in the late afternoon.
   Twelve of those arrested were taken to the county jail in San
Jose, where they were booked for investigation of misdemeanor
charges, Walsh said.
   Another 40 were cited and released after a crowd of several
hundred cheering supporters prevented the sheriff's bus full of
arrestees from leaving by creating a blockade of bodies, cars and
bicycles, Walsh said.
   Three other participants were cited for resisting and delaying
an officer, Walsh said. They were released.
   The protest was organized by the Stanford Asian-American
Students Association, the Black Student Union, the American Indian
Organization, the Committee on a Democratic Education, and MEChA, a
group representing Chicano students.
   The students sought a meeting with Kennedy to discuss demands
relating to minority hiring, discrimination and undergraduate
education.
</TEXT>
