<FIRST>u w PM-HousingStarts     05-16 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Housing Starts,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Housing Construction Down 2.7 Percent in April</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Housing construction, feeling the bite of
higher interest rates, fell 2.7 percent in April to the lowest
level in more than six years, the government said today.
   It marked the first time housing construction had dropped for
three straight months since the pace of activity slowed for five
months in a row from February through June 1987, the Commerce
Department reported.
   Last month's decline followed decreases of 4.5 percent in March
and 12.7 percent in February.
   New homes and apartments were built at a seasonally adjusted
annual rate of 1.36 million units in April, the slowest pace since
the 1.30 million pace of December 1982.
   The housing industry has been among the sectors of the economy
hardest hit as interest rates have edged upward over the past year.
Interest on fixed-rate mortgages last month was averaging over 11
percent, up a full percentage point from a year earlier, according
to a national survey by the Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp.
   The Federal Reserve Board for a year has been pushing up
interest rates rates in an effort to restrain inflation by
restraining economic growth.
   Construction of single-family homes rose 5.1 percent in April to
an annual rate of 1.04 million units, after dropping 4.2 percent in
March and 14.2 percent in February.
   Apartment construction, meanwhile, continued its decline,
falling 21.3 percent last month to an annual rate of 325,000 units.
Construction of multi-family units had fallen 5.3 percent in March
and 9 percent in February.
   The overall decline in housing construction last month was led
by 10.8 percent decrease in activity in the West, where starts fell
to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 347,000 units.
   Declines also were recorded in the Midwest and South.
Construction was down 9.5 percent in the Midwest to a annual rate
of 277,000 units and off 4 percent in the South to a rate of
529,000.
   The Northeast, meanwhile, recorded a 35.9 percent surge in
construction to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 208,000 units.
   Applications for building permits, a barometer of future housing
activity, turned up 7.2 percent in April after dropping in the
three previous months.
</TEXT>
