<FIRST>r a PM-People-Pavarotti     05-16 0191</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Pavarotti,0197</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tenor Walks Off Stage With Bad Throat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Italian tenor Luciano Pavarotti walked off the
stage during the third act of Puccini's ``Tosca'' after his voice
cracked due to throat problems.
   Monday night's production began 45 minutes late at the Benedum
Center as doctors attended to Pavarotti backstage. He decided to go
on, but was forced to end the opera early in the third act when his
voice cracked on the high B-flat.
   Pavarotti mumbled ``Sorry'' and signaled the conductor to start
again, but he approached the same note with the same results.
   ``I cannot do it. I am sorry,'' he told the audience. He then
put his head down and walked off the stage.
   After a few moments, the curtain fell and the houselights came
on. The audience applauded.
   It was Pavarotti's first appearance in Pittsburgh in a fully
staged opera production.
   Pittsburgh Opera Director Tito Capobianco said a decision would
be made today on whether Pavarotti would repeat the performance
tonight for the same crowd, some of whom paid $90 to hear the famed
tenor. Four more sold-out performances are scheduled through next
week.
</TEXT>
