<FIRST>r a PM-LibraryReopens     05-16 0300</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Library Reopens,0311</SECOND>
<HEAD>Los Angeles Library Opens New Chapter Three Years After Fires</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Los Angeles Central Library has reopened
for business, nearly three years after two arson fires destroyed or
damaged more than 1 million books.
   ``Everybody's very excited,'' Central Library Director Betty Gay
said on opening day Monday. ``It's like show time, the first day.''
   The reopening in temporary quarters marked the culmination of
months of work by 300 librarians and hundreds of volunteers, who
restored the 700,000 books damaged by fires in April and September
of 1986.
   Much of the damage was caused by water, and the books had to be
freeze-dried and stored in a refrigerated warehouse to prevent mold
and mildew.
   The library's temporary home is eight floors of the downtown
Title Insurance Building until workers complete renovation of the
landmark library building, probably in 1992.
   ``They took so long to open _ three years,'' said Roger Fuentes,
a 55-year-old retiree and library patron. ``I live nearby, and I
spend my days in the library. It fills up my time and, at the same
time, I always learn something new.''
   The first arson fire destroyed 375,000 books and caused $22
million in damage.
   The second fire, five months later, destroyed 25,000 books and
caused another $2 million in damage.
   Many librarians said Monday that working the checkout counter
again was a lot better than restoring books.
   ``Three years of cleaning, stacking and inventory,'' said Sherie
Sanford, shaking her head.
   The reopening also will make more books available to the city's
63 branch libraries, which borrow books from the Central Library.
   ``Today is a joyous day,'' said library spokesman Bob Reagan,
``not only for the general public but also for the library system
itself.''
   No arrests were made for either fire.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
