<FIRST>r i PM-SouthAfrica-Activists     05-16 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa-Activists,0402</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Frees Prominent Activists Held Since 1986</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORT ELIZABETH, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two prominent black
activists were freed today after being jailed without charge for
nearly three years, but they were placed under nighttime house
arrest and barred from political activity.
   Henry Fazzie, 65, and Mkhuseli Jack, 31, led community groups in
Port Elizabeth's black townships that were affiliated with the
United Democratic Front, a banned anti-apartheid coalition. They
were principal organizers of a highly effective black consumer
boycott of white-owned stores in 1985-86.
   The two were arrested along with several colleagues in August
1986, two months after President P.W. Botha declared a national
state of emergency.
   An estimated 30,000 activists have been held without charge for
varying periods during the emergency, although all but a few dozen
have been freed.
   Fazzie, Jack and four colleagues were released today from St.
Albans Prison in Port Elizabeth, ending speculation that the
government might lodge treason charges against them. Fazzie's wife,
Beauty, and several other activists were freed last week.
   During nationwide black unrest in 1985, Port Elizabeth's
townships were considered to have among the most militant and
best-organized opposition activity.
   The consumer boycott, which continued through mid-1986,
inflicted heavy losses on many white businessmen and prompted the
local chamber of commerce to engage in negotiations over the black
community's grievances.
   Restrictions imposed on the six men freed today bar them from
attending any meetings, restrict them to their homes between dusk
and sunrise, prohibit them from leaving the Port Elizabeth area,
and prohibit them from writing articles for publication or granting
interviews.
   Human rights groups say restrictions have been imposed on a
majority of the roughly 900 detainees freed since a wave of hunger
strikes began in January.
   The Human Rights Commission, an independent group founded by
anti-apartheid activists, alleged Monday that the government had
transferred 10 hunger-striking detainees from Johannesburg to
Bloemfontein, about 240 miles away.
   The government has said previously that detainees who stage
hunger strikes might be moved to Bloemfontein, but Law and Order
Minister Adriaan Vlok said last week that no such protests were
being conducted by any detainees.
   The Human Rights Commission said the 10 black detainees had gone
without food or liquids since May 7. It described the transfer from
Johannesburg as an attempt ``to bully them into submission by
isolating them.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
