<FIRST>r i PM-India-DoctorsStrike     05-16 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India-Doctors Strike,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Doctors Strike at Government Hospitals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 5,000 doctors at government
hospitals here went on strike today for higher pay, forcing
hundreds of patients to seek medical care elsewhere.
   Doctors want a $53 dollar a month raise, an increase from $16 to
$40 in a government allowance that compensates for them not being
allowed to maintain private practices, and a promotion schedule.
   ``Unless the government meets our demands there is no way we are
going to resume work,'' said Dr. Ashwani Bhatnagar, a leader of the
Doctor's Association which is leading the strike.
   At the capital's Ram Manohar Lohia Hospital, 225 of the 300
doctors walked off the job and many of the 800 beds were left
empty. Many patients at the hospital were discharged Monday night
in anticipation of the strike.
   ``We normally treat 2,500 to 3,000 people daily,'' said C.D.
Chauhan, a senior doctor, who alone was responsible for the 50
emergency room patients today. ``This morning I have managed to see
only about two dozen people.''
   ``It is painful to watch people suffer, but we had given enough
time to the government to settle our demands,'' Bhatnagar said.
   In India, government doctors are not permitted to maintain
private practices, but many prefer the state jobs, which provide a
certain financial security.
   New Delhi's 10 government hospitals together have 5,000 beds and
normally treat more than 20,000 to 25,000 people daily. The poor
receive low cost or free health care at the state hospitals.
</TEXT>
