<SECOND>PM-BRF--Bundy-Bones,0162</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bones Were From Animal, Police Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FAIRVIEW, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bones found during a search last week
belonged to an animal, according to authorities searching for the
remains of a woman slain by serial killer Ted Bundy.
   Officers have been searching for the remains of Debi Kent, 17,
of Bountiful. Bundy said in interviews before his execution Jan. 24
in Florida that he buried her body in Fairview Canyon in central
Utah.
   Bountiful Police Sgt. Ira Beal said the medical examiner's
office determined Monday that the bones found last week were from
an animal.
   Previous searches have turned up many animal bones and a human
knee cap. That bone is being analyzed in an attempt to determine
the age and sex of the person.
   ``We have no intentions of going back unless something else
develops,'' Beal said. ``We've searched that area as thorough as
you can. There really isn't a lot more to go on.''
