<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Ligachev     05-16 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Ligachev,0431</SECOND>
<HEAD>Politburo Member Denies Corruption Allegation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Politburo member Yegor K. Ligachev denied
allegations of involvement in high-level corruption, the Novosti
press agency said today.
   Ligachev, a conservative who is considered a rival of President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev, ``resolutely denied'' the allegations made by
a prosecutor in an election campaign, the official news agency said.
   Ligachev issued the statement to the Supreme Soviet Presidium,
the nation's top executive body, which already was investigating
the prosecutor, Nikolai Ivanov, for abuses of power.
   It was an extraordinary defense by a Politburo member of his
conduct, and remarkable in that it was made public in a telex sent
by Novosti to The Associated Press bureau in Moscow. The personal
lives of Politburo members are usually shrouded in secrecy, and are
not reported by official Soviet media.
   Ivanov and his boss, Telman Gdlyan, became nationally known
investigating corruption among local officials in the republic of
Uzbekistan. The investigation reulted in a 12-year jail sentence
for Yuri Churbanov, the son-in-law of former President Leonid I.
Brezhnev.
   On Leningrad television Friday night, Ivanov said their
investigation turned up the names of Ligachev and several other top
government officials. He did not go into details.
   Ivanov on Sunday won a seat in the newly formed parliament, the
Congress of People's Deputies.
   ``Yegor Ligachev has resolutely denied these allegations and
called the attention of the commission to the fact that the
slanderous statement was intended as a political provocation,''
Novosti said.
   ``He insists that the case be thoroughly considered and the
results reported in the press,'' Novosti continued.
   A Presidium commission was formed to consider citizen complaints
that the two prosecutors abused their power in investigating
high-level corruption. The Presidium is chaired by Gorbachev.
   The commission said in the Communist Party daily Pravda on
Saturday that the two prosecutors made ``provocative statements''
about ``violations of law'' by some political leaders, and accused
them of trying to disorient people and interfere with the
commission.
   A separate probe by the Supreme Court already has determined
that Gdlyan helped convict an innocent man in 1983 in Estonia. The
accused, an eminent scientist, died in jail. The Supreme Court has
asked the prosecutor's office to consider dismissing Gdlyan as a
result of that case.
   Gdlyan also won election to the new parliament in an earlier
round. Both prosecutors garnered overwhelming majorities of votes
in their districts during the balloting, which saw large numbers of
party loyalists upset by reform candidates.
</TEXT>
