<FIRST>r a PM-WalshFired     05-16 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Walsh Fired,0422</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ohio Highway Patrol Head Ousted After South Africa Trip</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CHALFANT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The superintendent of the Ohio Highway
Patrol has been fired because he accepted a free vacation to South
Africa as the guest of one of that racially segregated nation's
cities.
   Director William Denihan of the Ohio Department of Highway
Safety, whose agency oversees the patrol, dismissed Col. Jack Walsh
on Monday after Walsh refused a demotion to the rank of major.
   ``Given the circumstances and the sensitive political
ramifications of this all-expense-paid trip, Colonel Walsh, I feel,
exhibited a serious breach of confidence and ethics towards me,
towards this administration, and towards his fellow patrol
employees,'' Denihan said.
   Walsh took the trip without notifying Denihan or Gov. Richard
Celeste.
   Walsh, 53, who spent 31 years with the Highway Patrol, said he
saw nothing wrong with taking the trip. His expenses were paid by
the city of Johannesburg.
   Walsh could not be reached for comment; his home telephone
number is not published. But he told The Columbus Dispatch he
opposes racial discrimination.
   ``I never talked to anyone in South Africa who supports
apartheid,'' he said.
   ``I really can't see there is any conflict with my job as a
police officer, as superintendent of the highway patrol,'' Walsh
said. ``I guess the next thing is you won't be able to o to a
library and read a book on South Africa.''
   Walsh told the newspaper his trip included a tour of Soweto, a
township where 1.5 million blacks live under the policy of
apartheid, or racial separation.
   Walsh, who was paid about $54,000 annually, and his wife, Huey,
were among a group of U.S. officials who took the trip, worth an
estimated $18,000 per person. He still will be eligible for his
pension benefits from the patrol.
   Denihan said Walsh's action was an example of impaired judgment
which affected his credibility and his ability to continue as the
patrol's chief officer.
   ``This is his second (free) trip to Johannesburg, (South
Africa), not his first trip,'' Denihan said. He said expenses for
the first trip were paid by the Johannesburg Safety Council, while
the trip this month was financed by the Johannesburg City Council.
   Walsh was appointed patrol superintendent in 1979 by former Gov.
James A. Rhodes. He also was chairman of the Highway Patrol
Retirement System, a pension fund which has interests in companies
that conduct business in South Africa.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
