<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Jacobson     05-16 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Jacobson,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>Howard `Buddy' Jacobson, Once Leading U.S. Horse Trainer, Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Howard ``Buddy'' Jacobson, a one-time top
horse trainer convicted of killing his former girlfriend's lover in
a highly publicized New York City trial, died early today, a state
prison official said.
   Jacobson, 58, died at the Erie County Medical Center where he
had been under treatment for cancer, state Department of
Correctional Services spokesman James Flateau said. He had been
serving his sentence at Attica state prison, about 25 miles east of
Buffalo.
   Jacobson was the top horse trainer in the United States in 1963
and was the leading trainer at New York state tracks five times. He
also accumulated a fortune in modeling agency and real estate
ventures.
   Jacobson was serving a 25-years-to-life sentence for
second-degree murder in the Aug. 6, 1978, killing of John Tupper.
Prosecutors claimed Jacobson killed Tupper in jealousy over
Tupper's affair with model Melanie Cain.
   Tupper, 33, was shot six times, stabbed and beaten. His body was
found in a dump in the Bronx.
   Cain, who appeared on the covers of several national magazines
including Cosmopolitan and Red Book, had lived with Jacobson for
four years but the relationship ended 22 days before Tupper's death.
   Jacobson repeatedly maintained that he did not kill Tupper. He
claimed Tupper was murdered not because of the love triangle with
Cain and Jacobson but because of alleged drug-selling activities.
He was convicted in 1980.
   In May 1980 Jacobson escaped from a Brooklyn jail by changing
places with a man posing as his lawyer. He was captured 40 days
later in Manhattan Beach, Calif.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
