<FIRST>u w PM-Medicare-Catastrophic 1stLd-Writethru a0466 05-16 0634</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Medicare-Catastrophic, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0466,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Opposed to Surtax Says Many Elderly Oppose It</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Subs pvs 9th and 10th grafs, Sponsors of ... benefits, with
3 grafs to restore dropped matter and CORRECT quote</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A majority of the elderly persons who are
familiar with the new catastrophic illness provisions of Medicare
are unhappy with the program, according to a survey commissioned by
a group seeking reduction of the surtax that helps finance the plan.
   The Coalition for Affordable Health Care, a group formed to
lobby against the law that took effect Jan. 1, released a poll
Monday which suggests only about 60 percent of the 33 million
Medicare beneficiaries covered by the program are familiar with it.
   Of that 60 percent, the survey found, 53 percent said they are
disenchanted with the new program signed into law last year by
then-President Reagan after overwhelming congressional approval.
   The program, the first major Medicare expansion in the program's
history, is designed to protect Medicare beneficiaries against
catastrophic medical expenses by limiting the amount they have to
pay out of pocket for hospital bills and, starting next year,
doctor bills as well.
   The basic objections are that the program doesn't cover
long-term nursing care and costs more than it is worth,
particularly for those with enough income to make them subject to a
15 percent income tax surcharge to help pay for it.
   For more than 60 percent of those eligible for Medicare _ those
with too little taxable income to have to pay federal income taxes
_ the only additional expense this year is a $4-a month flat
premium. But for the others, the surtax can range up to $800 per
person per year.
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., who has introduced legislation to
delay implementation of the surtax and major parts of the plan that
have not taken effect, said Congress has been hit by a
``firestorm'' of protest from some of the millions who are subject
to the surtax.
   Although congressional studies indicate no more than 5 percent
of those eligible for Medicare would be hit by the maximum
surcharge, members of the coalition said they also are receiving
many complaints from those who would pay lesser amounts.
   Sponsors of the survey acknowledged that although 72 percent of
those questioned reported overall incomes of less than $30,000 and
thus would not be subject to the maximum tax, pollsters did not ask
the 1,008 people telephoned earlier this month if they knew how
much of a surtax, if any, they would have to pay. The poll,
conducted by The Wirthlin Group, had a 3.1 percent margin of error.
   T.J. Kilcline, a retired Navy vice admiral and president of the
Retired Officers Association, acknowledged that ``most people don't
really know what they're going to pay this year'' because the 1989
surtax will not be calculated by most until they fill out their tax
returns next year.
   Many elderly people who would pay tax if they were still working
for a taxable wage have little or no federal income tax liability
because most or all of their income is from tax-free Social
Security benefits.
   For example, 48 percent of those questioned for the poll said
they had gross incomes below $15,000, making it unlikely they would
be liable for any substantial surcharge _ if any at all.
   For a couple with a taxable income of $10,000, after tax-free
Social Security benefits and other deductions have been subtracted
from gross income, the catastrophic coverage surcharge would be
$225 _ or $112.50 each.
   The maximum $1,600 for such a couple _ $800 each _ would apply
to those with a taxable income of at least $53,000. Such a couple
already would be paying $10,816 a year in income taxes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
