<FIRST>r a PM-PistolPackingPastor     05-16 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pistol Packing Pastor,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>Minister Nabs Burglar At Gunpoint In Church</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Russell Barker wasn't about to rely on
blessed assurance when he came upon a burly, pipe-wielding burglar
in his church.
   Barker, pastor of the North Avenue Missionary Baptist Church in
northwest Atlanta, held his .38-caliber revolver on the suspect,
Joe Wilson, until police arrived.
   ``Sometimes you do something you don't want to do,'' Barker
said. ``But I was able to take care of myself. I made him lay down
on his face and he didn't come no further.''
   Barker, 56, said that when he arrived for work Monday morning he
heard the suspect rummaging around in a rear office of the church,
which has been burglarized at least seven times in the past three
years.
   Barker retrieved his gun from the trunk of his car and found the
suspect trying to crawl out through the ceiling in the women's
restroom. He aimed the gun at Wilson with one hand and telephoned
police with the other.
   Police said Barker's action was a brave one.
   ``He's (Wilson) a pretty good-sized guy, and the reverend's kind
of small,'' said Sgt. C.W. Richardson. ``When we got there, he was
sitting on the floor.''
   Wilson, 23, was charged with burglary and possession of burglary
tools.
