<FIRST>u i PM-Japan 1stLd-Writethru   05-16 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0568,0525</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parliament Member Resigns In Stock Scandal; Nakasone Agrees to Testify</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RETRANSMITTING to correct cycle designator</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A second opposition lawmaker linked to an
influence-peddling scandal that has rocked Japan's government has
resigned from Parliament.
   Meanwhile, former Prime Minister Yasuhiro Nakasone agreed to
testify in Parliament about his links to the scandal, Kyodo News
Service reported. Opposition parties have stalled parliamentary
business to back demands that he testify.
   Katsuya Ikeda, 51, a four-term member of the House of
Representatives, cited personal reasons today for his resignation
from Parliament and from the Clean Government Party, the
second-largest opposition party after the Socialists.
   In November, a member of the Japan Socialist Party, Takumi Ueda,
gave up his seat in Parliament after news reports linked him with
the scandal.
   Ikeda, a former journalist, acknowledged in November that his
brother, Yuzuru, bought 5,000 unlisted stock shares from Recruit
Co. at a bargain price in 1986. After public trading began and the
stock price soared, the brother made a profit of about $73,530.
   The company, accused of trying to influence government policy,
sold such shares in a Recruit subsidiary to some 160 influential
politicians, bureaucrats and businessmen.
   It also made large political contributions to politicians
including Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita, who announced last month
he would resign to take responsibility for the scandal.
   The governing Liberal Democratic Party still is searching for a
candidate untainted by the scandal but commanding widespread
support in the party to succeed Takeshita. It hopes a new leader
with a clean reputation will reverse the party's loss in popularity
before elections this summer for half the seats in Parliament's
upper house.
   Ikeda has denied personal involvement in his brother's stock
transactions, but news reports said $51,470 of the profit was
deposited into Ikeda's bank account, and that Ikeda also received
$102,940 in donations from Recruit.
   The reports said Ikeda used his influence as a member of the
government's Education Affairs Committee in 1986 for the benefit of
Recruit, which specializes in publishing employment information for
students.
   At a news conference, Ikeda denied receiving the donation, and
that the stock deal was in return for favors for Recruit.
   Prosecutors have arrested 14 public officials and Recruit
executives so far on charges of bribery and securities law
violations in the stock deals. In addition, three members of
Takeshita's Cabinet have resigned because of links with Recruit.
   Nakasone, who was prime minister at the time of the stock deals
and whose aides were among Recruit stock purchasers, previously had
said he would testify in Parliament only after prosecutors
completed their investigations of the Recruit case.
   This time, in a meeting with Ryutaro Hashimoto, the ruling
party's deputy secretary general, Nakasone did not set any
conditions, Kyodo said.
   Opposition parties want to question Nakasone about the resale of
U.S.-made supercomputers to Recruit from Japan's telecommunications
giant, Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Corp. NTT's former chairman,
Hasashi Shinto, has been arrested on charges that he took bribes
from Recruit in the form of bargain stock shares.
</TEXT>
