<FIRST>r i PM-Greece-Rashid     05-16 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Greece-Rashid,0266</SECOND>
<HEAD>Extradition Decision Postponed Until After June Elections</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Socialist government today postponed a
ruling on whether to extradite a suspected Palestinian terrorist to
the United States, saying it would decide after June 18 elections.
   The decision came four days after Greece's Supreme Court upheld
an extradition order sought by the United States. But the Justice
Ministry has final say in the matter.
   ``The Rashid case is a major one and the decision on whether he
should or should not be extradited to the United States will be
taken by the government that will emerge from the June elections,''
Justice Minister Yiannis Skoularikis said at a news conference.
   The Supreme Court had put off making a decision three times in
the sensitive case.
   Mohammed Rashid, 39, is accused of planting a bomb on a Pan Am
jumbo jet in 1982. A Japanese teenager was killed and 15 others
were wounded in the blast over Hawaii.
   American officials have described the extradition as a test of
Greece's willingness to fight terrorism.
   ``In any case, there is no question of extradition at this
moment because Rashid has to complete an eight-month sentence on
illegal weapons charges,'' Skoularikis said.
   Rashid, jailed since his arrest at Athens airport last May, was
convicted and sentenced on the weapons charge on March 28 after
guards found a set of makeshift knives in his cell.
   The Palestine Liberation Organization has said Rashid is an
officer in its military branch. They have denied U.S. charges that
he is a terrorist.
</TEXT>
