<FIRST>r i PM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0508 05-16 0677</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0508,0697</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Round up Workers From Gaza, Send Them Home</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with army forcing Palestinian workers
back to Gaza; edits to trim. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUIS MEIXLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police today rounded up Arabs from the Gaza
Strip who work in Israel and ordered them to return home, the first
such mass sweep during the 17-month Palestinian uprising.
   On Israel radio, Police Commissioner David Krauss called for
Israeli employers to send Palestinian workers home to the coastal
strip.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin said the orders were aimed at
pressuring Arabs to halt violence in the Israeli-occupied
territories.
   ``The intention is to warn the residents that permission for
free travel and work in Israel are not givens,'' Rabin told Israel
radio. ``They depend on the behavior of those who leave for work.''
   About 50,000 Arabs from Gaza and about 60,000 from the West Bank
work in Israel.
   It was uncertain how many workers were being rounded up. Most
were kept at home by a curfew declared Monday night in Gaza,
requiring all 700,000 of the strip's residents to stay at home. No
reason was given for the curfew but it was believed linked to the
recent death of an Israeli soldier, allegedly at the hands of
Palestinian guerrillas.
   Under Israeli law, Arabs from Gaza and the West Bank are not
allowed to stay in Israel overnight, but the law is widely skirted
by workers who sleep in dormitories or their work places.
   In Jerusalem, witnesses reported seeing police checking the
identities of Palestinians at major intersection. Those from Gaza
were reportedly put in police vehicles for tranport back to the
strip.
   At the Erez crossing into the Gaza Strip, hundreds of
Palestinian workers sat on the ground under army guard, a witness
said. He said most were brought to the area in Israeli taxis and
then taken by army truck back to Gaza.
   The uprising has been more violent in the Gaza Strip in recent
weeks than in the West Bank. The smaller Gaza Strip, with few roads
leading into Israel, also can be more easily controlled by
authorities.
   Also today, a Palestinian died of gunshot wounds sustained
earlier in the week in a shootout with police. The death of Ali
Mahmoud Muhammed Jabber, 23, raised to 476 the number of
Palestinians killed in the uprising. Twenty-one Israelis also have
died.
   In Gaza City today, three Palestinians were shot and wounded in
clashes with troops, including a 20-year-old who was shot in the
back, Arab hospital officials said. In the West Bank a 22-year-old
man was reported shot by soldiers.
   Israeli officials, meanwhile, shrugged off the PLO's rejection
of Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's plan for elections in the
territories and urged Palestinians to take part in the vote.
   Rabin told Israel radio that it would be the only offer of peace
by the government.
   ``There must be patience,'' Rabin said. ``They will understand
that they have only one alternative and that is based on the
government plan.... There is and will be no other alternative.''
   Foreign Minister Moshe Arens today flew to Washington to discuss
the 20-point peace plan with Secretary of State James A. Baker III.
   U.S. State Department envoy Dennis Ross was expected in Israel
this afternoon to brief Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir on his
discussions in Egypt and Jordan on the plan, and to meet with
Palestinian leaders.
   The United States has asked Israel to clarify whether elections
would include the 140,000 Arab residents of Jerusalem, the nation's
capital, and if there would be international supervision of the
balloting.
   The plan, overwhelmingly approved by Israel's Cabinet on Sunday,
calls for Palestinians to elect representatives to negotiate with
Israel on a five-year period of limited autonomy, with talks in the
third year on the final status of the territories.
   However, Israel would not negotiate with the PLO. It also
opposes formation of a Palestinian state in the West Bank and Gaza
and wants the negotiations to lead to a peace treaty with Jordan.
</TEXT>
