<FIRST>r a PM-DetroitNewspapers     05-16 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Detroit Newspapers,0233</SECOND>
<HEAD>Free Press to Reduce Staff Through Attrition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Detroit Free Press, seeking a partial merger
with its principal competitor, The Detroit News, says it will
reduce its staff without layoffs to cut costs.
   Free Press Publisher David Lawrence Jr. said Monday the staff
reductions will be accomplished by leaving vacancies unfilled
throughout the newspaper. He declined to say how many workers would
be affected.
   The comment came after Lawrence and newspaper President Robert
Hall met privately with representatives of the 11 unions at the
morning newspaper.
   Union workers at both papers have been working under extensions
of existing contracts since June 1987. Negotiations on new
contracts are scheduled to begin this week.
   The Free Press and the News are seeking permission from the U.S.
Supreme Court to combine some of their business functions.
Editorial and news departments would remain separate.
   The Supreme Court is expected to rule on the proposed joint
operating agreement within a year.
   The Free Press has promised its owner, Knight-Ridder Inc., that
it would hold losses to 1988 levels of more than $17 million while
it waits for the Supreme Court's ruling. Knight-Ridder has said
without the joint agreement, the Free Press would be closed.
   Lawrence told union representatives that the newsstand price of
the paper would not increase and that workers would be offered
raises.
