<FIRST>u i PM-Argentina 2ndLd-Writethru a0557 05-16 0790</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Argentina, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0557,0815</SECOND>
<HEAD>President-Elect Built Rapport With Workers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 6-8, `Cabinet ministers ... resignations, however.'
with three grafs to UPDATE with Alfonsin rejecting resignations. Picks
up 9th pvs: In his ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM H. HEATH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Not a necktie was in sight at a
street celebration of Carlos Menem's victory and for good reason _
the charismatic president-elect has his roots and support in the
working class.
   Menem's rapport with factory workers, gauchos _ cowboys from
Argentina's rich pampas _ and others helped return the Peronist
Party to power 13 years after it was overthrown in a military coup.
   Truck driver Alejandro Galindez, 27, who joined thousands of
other Peronists in the streets after Menem's election on Sunday,
said the victory ``is a return to our roots.''
   Menem defeated Eduardo Angeloz of the governing party by 7.8
million to 6.1 million votes, or 47.3 percent to 36.9 percent.
   The Peronist Party also won 67 seats in the Chamber of Deputies
to give it 127 overall, or exactly one half; and one Senate seat to
give it 23, also exactly a half. The party controls 17 of 22
provincial governorships.
   President Raul Alfonsin, meanwhile, rejected resignation offers
from his Cabinet today and said he wants to meet Menem as soon as
possible to discuss an orderly transition.
   Presidential spokesman Jose Ignacio Lopez said the eight
ministers met with Alfonsin for 2{ hours this morning.
   He said they did not consider advancing the date of Menem's
inauguration, now set for Dec. 10.
   In his victory speech, Menem called for ``national unity'' and
urged ``the forces of production, businessmen, farmers, workers,
everyone,'' to put aside differences and ``set the country in
motion.''
   He also pledged an end to ``the Argentina where some live well
doing nothing and others live badly although they work all day.''
   The 58-year-old governor of tiny La Rioja province faces severe
economic problems when he takes over from the Radical Civic Union.
   Until then, the Radicals and Peronists must work together. But
that will be difficult given their conflicting views.
   Alfonsin has tried to balance the budget, which is deep in the
red, by selling off state businesses. Menem's preference is to make
the companies more efficient but keep them in state hands.
   The Peronists have demanded increases in both the minimum wage
and federal aid to the provinces. Alfonsin has tried to hold the
line on each.
   Menem specifically has said he will not press Alfonsin to step
down early, but he's eager to take power. In Catamarca Province,
where he attended a rally on Monday, he said, ``We don't want to
keep administering the crisis. We want to confront it and smash
it.''
   Since February, the austral has been devalued by 84 percent,
inflation and interest rates soared to near record levels, wages
shrunk, Central Bank reserves dried up and workers were laid off.
   The foreign debt stands at $59 billion.
   Alfonsin has been widely praised for helping democracy return to
Argentina after the brutal 1976-83 military dictatorship but
refuses to step down early.
   He has said he is looking forward to Argentina's first transfer
of power to a freely elected successor in 61 years.
   Menem is a lawyer, but he looks more like a 19th century
caudillo, with his his shoulder-length hair and muttonchop
sideburns.
   The politician, who likes to drive race cars and be photographed
with showgirls, was born and raised in La Rioja, a poor, arid and
sparsely populated province of 200,000 people about 700 miles
northwest of Buenos Aires.
   The region's principal products are olives, grapes and jojoba.
   The son of Syrian immigrants who came to Argentina early in the
century and built a prosperous vinyard and winery, Menem was
educated in provincial public schools.
   Graduating from law school in 1955, one of his first cases was
the defense of Peronists arrested following the military ouster of
party founder Juan Peron in September 1955.
   Although the Peronist party was barred from political activity,
Menem's law office quickly became a provincial Peronist meeting
place and he was arrested for participation in a political
demonstration.
   A natural showman, Menem's star rose rapidly and after almost
two decades of work with the party, he was elected to the first of
his three terms as governor of La Rioja in 1973.
   Although his parents were Moslems, Menem converted in 1964 to
Roman Catholicism, the religion of most Argentines and required by
the constitution for all presidents. His wife, Zulema, also of
Syrian origin, has said she prefers to remain a Moslem.
   ``It's easy for me to communicate with people,'' Menem has said.
``I talk with everyone. I feel at home in the most humble places.''
</TEXT>
