<FIRST>r w AM-ChokingRecalls     05-16 0223</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Choking Recalls,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pacifier, Christmas Decoration Recalled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Christmas stocking decoration and a pacifier
holder that could pose choking hazards for children are being
recalled, the Consumer Product Safety Commission announced Tuesday.
   Neither has been involved in any injuries, officials said.
   The recall covers about 3,600 ``Mother's Helper'' pacifier
holders sold nationwide from October 1987 to August 1988, the
agency said.
   The recalled pacifier holders have a metal clip for fastening
the device to an infant's clothing. The metal clip could pose the
choking hazard if it separated from the rest of the holder, the
commission said.
   Embossed on the back are the words ``Mother's Helper 1986 Steven
Barrie &amp; Company.'' Consumers should return the holders to the
store where purchased for a refund or send them to Steven Barrie &amp;
Co., 1055A Louis Drive, Warminster, Pa., 18970.
   The second recall involves a Christmas stocking decorated with a
Teddy Bear and two small bells. The bells could come loose and
choke a child, the commission said.
   About 4,400 of the stockings, made of red and white furry
material and topped with the Teddy Bear head, were sold last
Christmas season, officials said.
   These can be returned to the retailer for a refund, the
commission said. Consumers may contact the Jerry Elsner Company,
Bronx, N.Y., at 1-800-223-4119 for additional information.
</TEXT>
