<FIRST>r a PM-DallasWithoutDallas     05-16 0278</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dallas Without Dallas,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dallas Series May Not Film In Dallas For Upcoming Season</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Southfork just won't be the same.
   Lorimar Productions will not shoot any of the first 12 episodes
of the 1989 season of ``Dallas'' in its namesake city, spokesman
David Stapf said Monday.
   ``They're not planning to come down at the usual time to shoot
the first 12 episodes,'' Stapf said. ``No decision has been made
for the entire year.''
   The standard number of episodes is 22, said a spokesman for CBS,
which broadcasts the show.
   The city could lose as much as $5 million if ``Dallas'' stays
away from the city for the entire season, said Joe Pope, whose
Dallas-based Film Productions Services company has provided crews
and equipment for the series' annual two-month summer shoot in the
Dallas area.
   ``From my own company, we bill more than $1 million every
year,'' Pope said. ``It means a lot. It's like being told you're
not going to see a good friend again.''
   ``It's more than economic, it's emotional,'' Pope said. ``Up
until last week, I was under the assumption they were coming in.
They couldn't justify it (the expense) anymore.''
   After last year's strike by the Writers Guild of America,
producer Leonard Katzman delayed filming in the city until last
fall.
   The first scene filmed in Dallas was Feb. 2, 1978, two months
before the show premiered.
   ``Dallas'' will be aired for at least one more season, but the
show's ratings have been steadily declining since the high-water
point in the 1983-84 season when it was prime time's most popular
attraction.
   The show's annual season-ending cliffhanger episode will be
broadcast Friday.
</TEXT>
