<SECOND>AM-BRF--Auction,0095</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Dish For Calligraphy Brushes Brings Record Price</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 12th century Chinese ceramic dish used to
wash calligraphy brushes was sold at auction Tuesday for $2.82
million, officials said.
   A private collector, Sunrider International of Los Angeles,
bought the rare mellow flower-shaped brushwasher from the imperial
court of the Song Dynasty (1127-1279), according to Sotheby's.
   A Ming Dynasty (1368-1644) decorated basin sold for $2.61
million, auction officials said.
   A Qing bowl with a mark for imperial palace of emperor Kangxi
fetched $1.34 million, Sotheby's said.
