<DOCNO> AP890516-0102 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-89 1242EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Students-Scene     05-16 0767</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Students-Scene,0793</SECOND>
<HEAD>Workers, Doctors, Officials, High School Students Support Students</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit-Students, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BEJ13</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They came Tuesday by the hundreds of thousands _
by bus and bike, on foot and on trains, doctors, lawyers, miners,
oil riggers, government officials and journalists _ to support
3,000 college students fasting for freedom in Tiananmen Square.
   Officials from the state-run labor union were there, making a
daring call for a union free of government control. Eight
newspapers and the Xinhua News Agency also joined in, demanding a
free press and an end to censorship.
   Reporters from the China Central Television Station marched and
said they wanted Ai Zhisheng to resign as minister of Radio, Film
and Television.
   ``He stops us from reporting the news, kick him out,'' said one
reporter. ``I don't care if I lose my job. How can I return to the
old ways now that I feel we are so close to freedom.''
   Composers and singers from the Beijing Song and Dance Troupe
also played their role, fighting what they said was the death of
Chinese culture.
   ``The leaders told us not to come out today but we had to,''
said one composer. ``Any Chinese person with any conscience is out
today. Those students are dying for democracy and the government is
doing nothing.''
   Several hundred high school students tagged along. ``In two
years, we will become you,'' read their banner.
   The protest by an estimated 300,000 people, which ringed
Tiananmen in a sea of banners, was unprecedented and marked the
high point of more than one month of demonstrations led by an
increasingly powerful student movement that wants a freer and more
democratic China.
   The last time workers came out in force was April 27 when
thousands of laborers pushed and shoved their way through lines of
unarmed police, opening a way for marching students.
   But Tuesday, they came to pay their respects at Tiananmen Square
where more than 3,000 increasingly weak students have been on a
hunger strike for three days. And, unlike last time, they
identified themselves with the huge red and white banners that have
become a hallmark of these demonstrations.
   ``Government _ how long will you allow the students to starve?''
read a banner carried by journalists of the conservative state-run
Guangming Daily.
   ``We won't be silent anymore,'' read another, sported by labor
union officials.
   The students were moved by the march.
   ``Mama, I can't come home when all these people are here for
us,'' said a young woman, weeping into a public telephone. ``They
are wonderful.''
   The students are demanding the government recognize their
independent student union and conduct a dialogue about democratic
reforms.
   Tuesday's demonstration highlighted the role students play as
instigators of change in China's modern history.
   Ever since May 4, 1919, when Beijing students marched against
concessions made to the Japanese after World War I and began the
May Fourth Movement, Chinese have looked to the students for
inspiration.
   ``The students dare to speak and to act,'' said a miner, one of
600 who marched to the square. ``They are the spark. We are the
fire.''
   ``Talk to the students! Talk to the students!'' chanted a group
of engineers and oil riggers from the Ministry of Petroleum.
   The ministry was one of several government bureaus, including
the Seismological Institute and the Ministry of Aeronautics and
Astronautics Industry, represented in the march.
   Government officials said they did not care about punishment.
   ``Punish me and my comrades,'' said one official at the
aeronautics ministry. ``And then punish the rest of the country.
Those old methods don't work.''
   Pan Kang and about 200 high school teachers from Hebei province
traveled about 140 miles by train to Beijing. ``We heard about the
students fasting in the square,'' he said. ``They are speaking for
us and suffering for us. We had to express our support.''
   About 160 doctors from two hospitals bicycled to the square to
express their concern. ``These children worry me. I think of them
as my own,'' said a bespectacled doctor in his 50s. ``I don't want
to see any of them sick. But I believe in their struggle.''
   Clothed in a ripped T-shirt, the words ``Democracy'' and
``Freedom'' scrawled on his back, businessman Wang Xiafeng adjusted
his position on the three-wheeled cart and shouted: ``Down with
bureacracy! Down with corruption!''
   The rag-tag Beijing City People's Group, a newly formed protest
group, shouted back.
   ``I am afraid of these people most of all,'' said one passer-by
as the group of mostly jobless youths marched by. ``They are very
angry.''
</TEXT>
