<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-89 1258EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SAfrica-Killings     05-16 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SAfrica-Killings,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ex-Policeman Convicted of Eight Murders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A white former policeman was found
guilty Tuesday of killing six blacks and an Asian man during a
shooting rampage in downtown Pretoria.
   Barend Strydom also was convicted of killing a black woman at a
squatter camp on Nov. 8, a week before the Pretoria massacre, and
of trying to kill 16 blacks who were wounded in the two incidents.
   Strydom, a member of the neo-Nazi Afrikaner Resistance Movement,
is expected to be sentenced Wednesday. The death penalty is
mandatory for murder in South Africa unless the judge determines
there were extenuating circumstances.
   Pretoria Supreme Court Judge Louis Harms halted the trial after
1{ days of testimony, agreeing with the prosecution that the case
was clear cut.
   ``There is no doubt that he is guilty of all charges,'' Harms
said.
   The judge noted that three state-appointed psychiatrists have
determined Strydom, 23, is not mentally unbalanced.
   In testimony Monday and Tuesday, witnesses described how Strydom
smiled as he strolled along Pretoria sidewalks shooting blacks at
close range.
   According to testimony, the shooting spree took place shortly
after Strydom was rebuffed in an attempt to initiate a love affair
with the wife of a policeman with whom he shared an apartment.
   According to the prosecution, Strydom admitted telephoning a
newspaper on Nov. 14 to say that ``something big'' would happen in
Pretoria the next day. Strydom also allegedly told the newspaper
that he had attended a speech by President P.W. Botha that night
and that he would have killed the South African leader if he had
announced he was freeing jailed black nationalist leader Nelson
Mandela.
   In a separate case, seven white men appeared in court Tuesday in
connection with the tarring and feathering of Mayor Gus Gouws of
Welkom, a mining town in the Orange Free State.
   The men, who face assault charges, were arrested immediately
after the Saturday incident in which Gouws was attacked while
helping to open a multiracial marathon race for handicapped people.
   Five of the seven have been identified as members of the
Afrikaner Resistance Movement, which seeks to establish a
whites-only state in the northern half of South Africa.
</TEXT>
