<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Turkey-Divorce     05-16 0190</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Turkey-Divorce,0195</SECOND>
<HEAD>Workers File Suits to Divorce Wives to Protest Low Incomes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DIYARBAKIR, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 1,000 workers in this
southeastern city filed suits Tuesday to divorce their wives on the
grounds they can't support a family on their income, a union
official said.
   Musa Celik, head of the Diyarbakir branch of the Yol-Is Trade
Union, said 1,070 workers employed by Turkey's Highway Authority
filed their individual suits in Diyarbakir civil court.
   He said the workers said in a joint petition for divorce their
income ``was not sufficient to provide even the most fundamental
needs of their families and this was causing quarrels and making
the marriage unbearable.''
   Celik said the average monthly wage of the workers was about $70.
   The suits appeared to be part of the union's campaign to bring
attention to its demands to nearly triple salaries at a time
inflation is running at 75 percent. Since the campaign began six
months ago, hundreds of thousands of workers have taken part in
daily protests that include work slowdowns and refusal to work
overtime.
   Obtaining a divorce is difficult in Turkey unless both spouses
agree.
</TEXT>
