<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     05-16 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0516</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police on Alert Against Protests Marking Kwangju Anniversary</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SEL1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Riot police blocked a protest Tuesday
by demonstrators angered by the mysterious death of a student at
Kwangju city.
   The death of student Lee Chol-kyu has affected relations with
Washington, as Seoul warned that a State Department official's
remarks about the death could harm relations.
   Police all over the nation were on alert after dissidents called
for demonstrations to mark the anniversary this week of a 1980
uprising in southeastern Kwangju. At least 192 people were killed
in the nine-day rebellion.
   Witnesses said 10,000 students and citizens chanting
anti-government slogans marched in Kwangju on Tuesday to protest
Lee's death.
   ``Down with (President) Roh Tae-woo!'' they yelled when their
march was blocked by riot police guarding the provincial government
headquarters.
   Thousands of protesters have demonstrated every day in downtown
Kwangju since the radical student's body was found Wednesday in a
reservoir near the city, which is about 170 miles south of Seoul.
   Dissidents allege Lee was tortured to death by police and that
authorities have doctored pathology tests to show that he drowned.
   Students staged street protests in two other provincial cities,
Taejon and Chonju, according to the official Yonhap news agency.
   In Seoul, police fired tear gas Tuesday to disperse about 300
radical students trying to march from Sungkyunkwan University with
firebombs. It was the first violent clash since six policemen died
May 3 in a campus confrontation.
   Many students, sensing public anger at the officers' deaths,
renounced violent tactics.
   The Seoul government said U.S. comments last week on Lee's death
were incorrect.
   ``Unnecessary comment on internal matters, particularly on a
situation in which it does not know the truth, would not be of help
to the U.S.-Korea alliance or friendly relations,'' a Foreign
Ministry official said on condition of anonymity.
   The warning responded to remarks by a State Department official
who called Lee's death ``a deplorable event.''
   ``We do not know who may have committed this atrocious act,''
the State Department official said, but ``the murderers will be
exposed and severely punished.''
   South Korea lodged a protest in Washington, contending it has
not been proved that Lee was murdered. The State Department said
Monday it did not intend to prejudge how Lee died.
   Police had sought Lee for anti-state acts and prosecutors
believe the student fell into a reservoir and drowned while fleeing
police.
   Dissidents and radical students are trying to use the growing
furor over Lee's death to step up their campaign to topple Roh.
   The opposition-controlled National Assembly convened 16
committees Tuesday to investigate Lee's death and other issues.
Opposition parties contend the government is using radical violence
as a pretext to subdue all opposition groups.
   Roh has ordered a crackdown on the dissidents he accuses of
threatening stability and democracy. The Justice Ministry announced
587 people have been charged or arrested this year for violent
protests and anti-state activities.
</TEXT>
