<FIRST>u w PM-PanamaEvacuations 3rdLd-Writethru a0581 05-16 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Panama Evacuations, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0581,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Offering Flights Out Of Panama For Dependents</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates throughout with attribution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States government has decided to
offer evacuation flights from Panama to all military dependents who
wish to leave, starting today, administration officials said.
   Dan Howard, the Pentagon's chief spokesman, said some dependents
of military servicemen and U.S. Embassy workers already had
departed Panama on ``space available'' seats on military transports
over the last few days.
   But Howard and other officials who asked not to be named said
the Defense Department was now launching a much broader effort,
using chartered commercial planes in addition to the military cargo
planes that have been ferrying extra troops to Panama.
   Howard insisted several times at a briefing the movement of
military dependents was not an ``evacuation,'' but rather ``an
accelerated drawdown.''
   The word evacuation suggests a near-panic withdrawal and that's
not what is happening now in Panama, Howard said.
   The spokesman said he didn't know how frequently flights would
operate and to which cities in the United States they would run.
But a spokesman at the Charleston, S.C., Air Force Base said today
that at least some flights would be using that city as a point of
entry.
   Lt. Lester T. Carroll Jr., the spokesman, said the first of at
least two evacuation flights of dependants from Panama was
scheduled for arrival in Charleston tonight, carrying between 200
and 300 people.
   There are about 14,000 dependents of service personnel and
Defense Department employees living in Panama.
   According to Howard, the Pentagon and the U.S. Southern Command,
which is headquartered in Panama, have decided that all so-called
``command-sponsored'' dependents will either be living inside U.S.
bases or transported home by July 1.
   The Pentagon announced Monday that that all ``command
sponsored'' military families _ those who are there under official
U.S. government sponsorship _ had moved inside U.S. military bases
in Panama under an emergency order.
   But there are not enough houses on the bases for those who had
been living off base _ about 1,396 people _ to stay there
permanently, Howard said. So while the evacuation flights are
currently voluntary, some dependents may face orders to fly home if
not enough volunteer, the spokesman said.
   Of the roughly 14,000 military dependents in Panama, 3,081 live
off base. Of that total, 1,396 are command sponsored and 1,685 are
not. The families who are not command sponsored have been urged to
move to one of the 10 U.S. military installations in Panama, but
cannot be forced to do so.
   Howard said today the flights home were being offered to all
military dependents in Panama, including those who were not
officially ``sponsored'' by the military and had decided on their
own to live there with a husband or wife.
   Howard said the administration wanted to launch its ``drawdown''
because of the difficulty of forecasting the actions of the Noriega
government. Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, the strongman behind that
government, staged and then declared void a popular presidential
election a week ago when it became clear his candidate had lost.
   President Bush subsequently ordered almost 2,000 additional
troops to Panama to ensure the safety of American citizens.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890516-0112 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-89 1331EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon-Missing 1stLd-Writethru   05-16 0308</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon-Missing, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0628,a0635,0313</SECOND>
<HEAD>West Germans Kidnapped Again</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Combines pvs and edits; no pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SIDON, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two West German relief workers who were
freed from captivity 12 days ago were kidnapped again in this
southern port city today, police said.
   They said gunmen in two cars intercepted Heinrich Struebig, 48,
and Petra Schnitzler, 26, as they were on their way from their
center to the Mieh Mieh Palestinian refugee camp at 7:30 p.m.
   A police spokesman said the pair were in two cars when the
gunmen firing in the air stopped them and took them away.
   Police could not confirm reports that their colleague, Markus
Quint, 21, who was freed from 10 days in captivity on Sunday, was
with them.
   On May 4, the three relief workers from the private West German
relief grou, ASME-Humanitas, were grabbed by five unidentified
gunmen on Sidon's southern edge, police said.
   Struebig, an administrator, and Schnitzler, a nurse, were
released 10 hours later. They said they were freed so they could
transmit the demands of the kidnappers holding Quint to West German
authorities.
   No one claimed responsibility for the abduction. Nabih Berri,
head of the Shiite Moslem militia called Amal, brought Quint back
to the organization's headquarters Sunday. But he refused to
identify the kidnappers.
   Palestinian security officials in south Lebanon quoted Struebig
and Schnitzler as saying that the kidnappers were demanding a mild
sentence for confessed TWA hijacker Mohammed Ali Hamadi.
   Hamadi, a Lebanese Shiite Moslem, is on trial in Frankfurt, West
Germany, charged with murder and air piracy in the June 1985 TWA
hijacking during which a U.S. Navy diver was killed.
   The verdict is scheduled for Wednesday and prosecutors have
demanded a life sentence.
   Struebig and Schnitzler, who also disappeared overnight last
year, had rejected numerous West German government appeals to leave
Lebanon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
