<FIRST>r a AM-PresidentialCoup     05-16 0530</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Presidential Coup,0547</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush, Mitterrand and a Gaggle of Security Agents to Visit Boston
Campus</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE DREYFOUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boston University's 5,600 seniors are taking a
final lesson in supply and demand, with some scalping tickets to
this weekend's commencement featuring President Bush and France's
President Francois Mitterrand.
   Tickets reportedly are going for as much as $100.
   About 30,000 people _ 10,000 more than usual _ are expected at
the ceremony, for which each senior was allotted four tickets.
   ``We haven't had to use a system like this in the past because
we've been able to accommodate everyone, but the students' response
this year has been overwhelming,'' BU Executive Vice President Jon
Westling said Tuesday.
   For the most part, students say their parents wouldn't dream of
missing graduation or the chance to watch two world leaders in
academic robes collect honorary degrees.
   But for some seniors whose families are small or eagerness to
make a buck is great, the opportunity for a little wheeling and
dealing is attractive.
   ``We think that it would have been preferable for students who
weren't going to be needing tickets to have turned them back so a
fair allocation procedure could have been used,'' Westling said.
``It's a very difficult thing to stop, but it's not something we
encourage or condone.''
   University President John Silber has been credited with
persuading Bush and Mitterrand to converge on the school's urban
campus, thus dominating the keen annual competition among
Massachusetts' 120 colleges for commencement speakers.
   Silber attracted not one, but two world leaders, while Harvard
University had to ``settle'' for Pakistani Prime Minister Benazir
Bhutto and Tufts University for U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez
de Cuellar.
   ``He extended the invitations, worked with the staff both at the
White House and at the Elysee to make sure that the case for coming
to Boston University was put as clearly and effectively as
possible,'' Westling said. ``And it appears to have worked.''
   BU spokesman Thomas Cashman said Silber was able to arrange the
visit through his friendship with Bush, which dates to his days at
the University of Texas in the 1960s, and his more recent
acquaintance with Mitterrand through Nobel laureate Elie Wiesel, a
BU professor and friend of the French head of state.
   The presidents also had plans to meet at Bush's summer retreat
in Kennebunkport, Maine, around graduation day, making a side trip
to Boston convenient.
   While BU's presidential coup has set the community abuzz, ``it's
been a headache'' for campus security, said Adam C. Thermos,
manager of protective services.
   Senior Cindy Carron said she and many of her friends regarded
the presidential visit as a mixed blessing, since it limited the
number of tickets available to students and required extensive
security checks.
   ``I'd almost rather have my whole family there to share in the
ceremony instead of the president, who's untouchable,'' she said.
   Lauren Goldstein, a native of New York, agreed.
   ``It's becoming such a hassle,'' she said. ``That my parents
have to get here at the crack of dawn to get through security is
ludicrous, but unfortunately that's what you have to do when a
president comes to town.''
</TEXT>
