<FIRST>u a PM-Byrne-Sentencing     05-16 0342</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Byrne-Sentencing,0352</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Sentenced to Maximum in Officer's Murder</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush Changes, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A drug dealer was sentenced today to the maximum
term of 25 years to life in prison for the murder of a rookie
policeman, whom President Bush has called a victim of ``cocaine
cowards.''
   State Supreme Court Justice Thomas A. Demakos also sentenced
Philip Copeland to five to 15 years for weapons possession, to run
concurrently. The sentence prompted thunderous applause from about
150 officers in the courtroom.
   ``You are unfit to be a member of our society,'' the judge told
Copeland.
   Demakos said he wished the law allowed him to make the sentences
consecutive. He said he would recommend no parole and said that
when he retires, his last act would be to remind the parole board
of his recommendation.
   Copeland, 23, was the first of three young men to be sentenced
in the killing. He was convicted March 29 with Todd Scott, 20, and
Scott Cobb, 25, after a two-month trial in the death of officer
Edward Byrne, who was shot five times while he guarded the home of
a drug witness in February 1988.
   Bush gave the case national publicity during last year's
presidential campaign and called it a symbol of drug-related crime.
Byrne's family gave his badge to Bush, who called the killers a
``gang of cocaine cowards.''
   Byrne's funeral drew 10,000 uniformed police officers from
around the country.
   Prosecutors charged that the defendants killed Byrne on orders
issued from jail by reputed drug kingpin Howard ``Pappy'' Mason,
who reportedly was enraged when he was jailed on a gun possession
charge.
   ``There is no doubt that of the three, Copeland was the worst,''
Demakos said. ``This arrogant act assaults our society.''
   Assistant District Attorney Eugene Kelly called Copeland ``the
mastermind'' of the plot. ``This is a crime of monstrous
proportions. ... This was a message to society.''
   Scott and Cobb face the same sentences for second-degree murder
and second-degree criminal possession of a weapon.
</TEXT>
