<FIRST>u w PM-US-Nicaragua 4thLd-Writethru a0590 05-16 0853</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Nicaragua, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0590,850</SECOND>
<HEAD>White House Doubts Soviet Arms Halt To Nicaragua</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with White House comments, edits to tighten throughout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev told the United States
that he has halted its weapons shipments to Nicaragua's leftist
government, but the White House today said the evidence shows the
opposite and accused him of ``drugstore cowboy'' rhetoric.
   President Bush is waiting for Gorbachev to match his ``words
with deeds,'' said White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater,
who also accused Gorbachev of playing ``a PR game.''
   ``We are very leery their intentions,'' he said, noting that the
Soviets have made no public statements about cutting off aid to
Nicaragua.
   Gorbachev informed President Bush of the decision in a letter
this month and confirmed it in conversations with Secretary of
State James A. Baker III in Moscow last week, an administration
official said Monday night.
   Fitzwater did not directly confirm the letter, but said the
Soviets gave private indications to U.S. officials that they were
ceasing their military aid to Nicaragua, as President Bush has
pushed them to do.
   ``At this point we don't see the evidence of any cutoff. The
military aid is still coming in. It could be that is still in the
pipeline. It could be aid from another country, from Cuba or
something on that order,'' Fitzwater said,
   He said U.S. officials have evidence showing that Nicaragua has
received military shipments amounting to ``several millions'' of
dollars since the beginning of this year, but he could not say from
where it was coming.
   Fitzwater linked the Nicaragua situation with recent Soviet arms
cut proposals, which he said ``appear to be something they're not.''
   ``That's the essence of the PR game that he's playing here,''
when asked why it seemed Gorbachev was making all the initiatives,
while Bush lays back.
   ``And that is that the United States has been very careful and
methodical in it's examiniation of our relationship with the Soviet
Union,'' Fitzwater said.
   ``We contrast that, which is an admittedly cautious approach, to
the one of throwing out in a kind of a drugstore cowboy fashion one
arms control proposal after another out of which upon examination
appears to be either very little change from existing situation
involving promises that have been made in the past, involving
reductions that are not meaningful in terms of our strategic
relationship with the Soviet Union.''
   Prior to his Moscow visit, Baker had cited Soviet support of the
Sandinistas as a litmus test for U.S.-Soviet relations, questioning
whether Gorbachev's deeds would live up to his words of
conciliation toward the West.
   Bush received Gorbachev's letter before Baker went to Moscow,
where the secretary of state met with Gorbachev and Foreign
Minister Eduard Shevardnadze.
   The United States estimated that the Soviets provided $515
million in various forms of military aid, including weapons, to the
Sandinista government in Nicaragua last year. The most potent
weapons were attack helicopters.
   A U.S. official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, stressed
that Gorbachev's assurances did not foreclose delivery of other
forms of military assistance besides weapons. That assistance could
include vehicles, supplies and clothing. Baker did not persuade the
Soviet leaders to cut off that assistance as well, the source said.
   Also, the Soviets declined to suspend their military support of
Cuba, the other prominent Soviet client state in the region, the
official said. The United States had also sought to have the
Soviets halt supplies to Cuba.
   Ernesto Palazio, head of Washington office of the Nicaraguan
rebels, said he was not convinced that Gorbachev's reported
commitment would diminish the Sandinista military capability.
   He said press reports about Gorbachev's position indicate that
Cuba may replace the Soviet Union as the Sandinistas' arms supplier.
   ``Cuba now manufactures similar arms,'' Palazio said. ``So
whether the Soviet Union does it (arms the Sandinistas) directly or
through a surrogate, we'll just have to wait and see.''
   House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, hailed the Soviet decision as
overdue.
   ``It's high time that the Soviet Union does stop supplying
military support to Nicaragua,'' Wright said, adding that he had
discussed the matter with Soviet diplomats during the Reagan
administration.
   ``It has to come,'' he said. ``If we're really to demilitarize
the zone we really do need to get foreign interests out of there.''
   Rep. Tom Foley, D-Wash., the House majority leader, called it
``a very welcome decision.''
   The Swedish foreign minister, Sten Andersson, here for talks
with Bush and Baker, today called Gorbachev's move a ``very
positive step.''
   Rebels, known as Contras and backed by the United States, have
been fighting the Sandinista forces since 1981. The United States
provided arms to the Contras, but Congress subsequently limited
U.S. assistance to so-called humanitarian aid.
   Baker, while in Moscow, said he had made headway with Gorbachev
and Shevardnadze toward cooperation in Latin America, the Middle
East and other areas, but did not disclose the Gorbachev letter.
   In the Kremlin last week, Shevardnadze reiterated to Baker that
weapons deliveries had ceased and Gorbachev underscored the
commitment at a 3{-hour meeting with Baker, the official said.
</TEXT>
