<FIRST>u i PM-Ethiopia 2ndLd-Writethru   05-16 0563</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ethiopia, 2nd Ld - Writethru,a0621,0575</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Military Takes to Streets of Ethiopia's Capital</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with source saying trouble caused
by military command dispute, troops guarding airport, calm returning to
city; no pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ABEBE ANDUALEM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shooting broke out in the capital
today and tanks circled the presidential palace and other key
government buildings in an apparent dispute among military leaders.
   A civilian employee inside the Ministry of Defense, where
shooting broke out in late afternoon, told The Associated Press by
telephone the trouble stemmed ``from an apparent division'' among
top officers.
   The employee, who spoke only on condition that he not be
identified, said a measure of calm had returned by mid-evening and
the two sides were talking within the ministry in an attempt to
resolve their differences.
   The trouble broke out several hours after President Mengistu
Haile Mariam left Addis Ababa for a previously unannounced visit to
East Germany. Sources said he took his family with him.
   There have been persistent reports of army unrest in Ethiopia,
whose Marxist government is engaged in war against separate rebel
groups in its northernmost provinces of Tigre and Eritrea.
   Government forces have been pushed out of Eritrea and Tigre
provinces in a series of humiliating, recent defeats by the
Eritrean People's Liberation Army and the Tigray People's
Liberation Army.
   Civilian and military employees were not allowed to leave the
Defense Ministry building after the trouble erupted. It was ringed
by tanks, armored cars and troops in what appeared to be defensive
positions.
   ``I don't know what we've got, quite frankly,'' said a spokesman
for the U.S. Embassy. ``We've got reports of some shooting in the
city, but not a great deal of it.''
   ``I cannot comment on what's going on,'' said Allen Collins,
head of chancellery in the British Embassy. ``We are trying to make
our own assessment and any comment would be premature.''
   In Washington, State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said
the U.S. Embassy in Addis Ababa had confirmed that there was
fighting in the streets, but had no other information about the
conflict.
   ``We don't know exactly what is going on there,'' Boucher said.
   Government sources, speaking only on condition of anonymity,
said shooting broke out inside the Defense Ministry at about 4 p.m.
just as employees were about to end their day. It could not be
determined if there were any casualties.
   Almost immediately, two Air Force MIG jet fighters began buzzing
the city repeatedly and tanks, armored personnel carriers and
troops surrounded the ministry.
   Later, tanks, armored cars and soldiers took up positions
outside other key government buildings, including the presidential
palace, the Ministry of Interior and the Ministry of Information,
which houses the government broadcasting station.
   The radio station continued to broadcast normally and there were
no announcements by the government. Internal and international
communications channels also were uninterrupted.
   Later in the evening, however, the city's international airport
was closed to all traffic. Airport controllers, monitored by radio,
gave no reason as they diverted commercial flights to nearby
Djibouti.
   Shortly after the closure, tanks and troops took up positions at
the airport.
   Between four and six Soviet-made helicopter gunships began
circling the city after the jets retired, and police and soldiers
were keeping people away from the city's center, where the Ministry
of Defense is located.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
