<FIRST>u w AM-PlasticsFax Bjt   05-16 0661</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Plastics Fax, Bjt,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Memo Sheds Light on Process of Acquiring Political Support</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANE E. ALLEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Senate office memo inadvertently faxed to a
news organization sheds new light on how Capitol Hill groundwork is
laid for the political favors that can make or break legislation.
   The bill in question here, writes a staffer for Sen. Connie Mack
of Florida, is harmless, might help at home and would be ``a big
big big favor'' to a party colleague seeking higher office in
another state.
   The legislation _ on plastics recycling _ probably isn't a vital
issue to many in Congress, but it is to Rep. Jim Courter, whose New
Jersey district would include a national headquarters for a major
recycling project if the bill passes.
   Passage of the Republican congressman's bill would be something
solid he could point to as he presses his campaign to succeed Gov.
Tom Kean in New Jersey. So while he prepares to introduce the bill
in the House, he's been searching for someone to sponsor it in the
Senate. Someone like Mack, a Florida Republican.
   That's where the memo _ accidentally sent by facsimile machine
to The Associated Press _ comes in.
   It was written by Michele Chouteau, at the time a staff member
for Mack, to the senator's administrative assistant, Mitch Bainwol.
   Ms. Chouteau, who left Mack's office on Friday to take over as
press secretary for Rep. Chuck Douglas, R-N.H., said she sent the
memo Monday to her old office and speculated it may have been
mistakenly faxed with other material to AP's New Hampshire office
in Concord.
   The undated document describes a $15 million plastics recycling
bill to provide grants to several universities, including the
University of Florida at Gainesville, the University of
Massachusetts at Amherst, and Rutgers University, which is in
Courter's district.
   Why should Mack sponsor it? Ms. Chouteau spelled out four
arguments:
   _ ``It is virtually a harmless issue.
   _ ``It gives money to UF while not being a very expensive piece
of legislation.
   _ ``It's a decent environmental initiative that can be played up
or down as much as you see fit.''
   _ ``It would be a big big big favor to a Republican seeking the
governor's slot in New Jersey. Courter needs a Senate sponsor and
is dealing with New Jersey (Bradley and Lautenberg), Massachusetts
(need we say more?) and Florida (which leaves Graham and CM). Yes,
CM is his only hope for an appropriate Senate sponsor.''
   Ms. Chouteau said Monday that she had meant that ``CM,'' Sen.
Mack, was the only Republican senator from among those states that
could expect grants.
   ``These are my analyses, really,'' Ms. Chouteau said.
``Courter's office said, `Here's the bill, what do you think?' In
trying to expedite (action by) the senator's office, I tried to put
in my arguments.''
   Courter spokesman Phil Peters declined to say whether Courter's
aides had been making the same arguments Ms. Chouteau made. ``As
far as she analyzed the legislation, I don't have any comment on
that,'' he said.
   He did take issue with her dismissing chances of sponsorship
from other states' senators, pointing to Rudy Boschwitz, R-Minn.,
as a possible candidate.
   Mack spokesman Mark Mills said he saw the memo for the first
time on Monday, but had been aware for about a week of Courter's
attempt to win Mack's sponsorship.
   ``From our standpoint, the reason we were brought in on it is
that it will impact the University of Florida in Gainesville. If it
helps Florida, we're all for it,'' Mills said. ``All the other
arguments I'm just not familiar with.''
   Mills said Mack's staff would be consulting with the university
on the legislation sometime this week.
   Courter's aide, Peters, said he understood Mack had been tied up
with monitoring the election in Panama and might have been unable
to review the legislation in the three weeks since the senator's
office had been given copies.
</TEXT>
