<DOCNO> AP890516-0119 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-89 1408EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-DefenseTechnology     05-16 0559</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Defense Technology,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>A 5-Cent Part in a $2 Box</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unnecessary Pentagon specifications have
wasted taxpayers' dollars with at least one defense contractor
forced to package a 5-cent spare part in a $2 box, witnesses told a
Senate panel Tuesday.
   Contractors described for the Senate Governmental Affairs
subcommittee on oversight of government management how strict
Pentagon specifications for commercially available products, along
with excessive requirements, have made them less than willing to
deal with the Defense Department.
   ``My manager said he'd rather have AIDS than a government
contract,'' Robert Rossow III of Midland Brake Inc., of Owosso,
Mich., told the Senate panel.
   While contractors expressed their misgivings to one
subcommittee, another panel was hearing testimony from officials of
the Office of Technology Assessment, a congressional watchdog
agency, on a report concluding that the once-large U.S. advantage
in a variety of defense technologies has diminished.
   ``The defense technology base is not in crisis,'' Alan Shaw,
manager of the office's international security and commerce
program, told the Senate Armed Services subcommittee on defense
industry and technology. ``But it does face major problems.''
   Stiff competition from an increasing number of foreign
competitors, delays in translating laboratory research and
development into practical use and a vast number of rules and
regulations that slow the acquisition process were among the
problems cited in the report.
   B. Dan Pinick, senior vice president of the Boeing Co.,
described to the Senate Governmental Affairs subcommittee one such
encounter with excessive regulations.
   Boeing, in its bid for the Navy's Long-Range Air ASW Capability
Aircraft, proposed a modified version of its 757 commercial
jetliner. At the time of the bid, the commercial jet program was 10
years old, meaning that Boeing's contracts with suppliers and
vendors had been firmly established, Pinick said.
   Based on previous contracts, Boeing proposed to the Pentagon
waiving certain contract clauses and military specifications that
are applied to new, government-designed aircraft. To comply with
the clauses, Boeing would have had to reopen and try to renegotiate
about 3,900 contacts, Pinick said.
   ``We believe there is a large base of high-quality commercial
suppliers to which the U.S. government may not have access because
of the terms and conditions associated with government contracts,''
the Boeing official said.
   Rossow described how one Pentagon overspecification required him
to package a 5-cent, brake system repair part in a plastic bag, a
box wrapped in plastic and then another box, at a cost of $2.
   ``Life has enough complications without deliberately courting
more,'' Rossow said. ``Given the complexities and risks associated
with government contracting, who needs it?''
   The complaints from the government contractors came one day
after a study by the Center for Strategic and International Studies
found that almost 100,000 companies stopped doing business with the
Pentagon over a five-year period.
   The report, by the private, non-profit think tank that studies
national security issues, found that in 1982, more than 138,000
companies provided goods to the Defense Department. But by 1987,
the number had dropped to less than 40,000.
   ``Some of the 80,000 went out of business, including about
20,000 small businesses,'' the report said. ``Most of the 80,000
firms, however, simply quit doing business with the Defense
Department and opted for other customers.''
   The report found that in comparison to other industries,
``defense is not a highly profitable business.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
