<FIRST>r a AM-ConcealedSeafood     05-16 0173</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Concealed Seafood,0179</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Than They Could Eat For $11.95</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSLY, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When restaurants around here say they don't
sell food to go, they mean business.
   A parking lot fight at a popular seafood restaurant wound up
with nine people arrested for carrying concealed fish.
   The scuffle broke out Mother's Day after one car hit another in
the parking lot and quickly escalated.
   When police arrived they arrested one man and charted him with
aggravated battery and disturbing the peace. They booked another
man on charges of disturbing the peace and took him to a hospital
for treatment of a stab wound.
   Then the officers searched the cars and booked all nine for
misdemeanor theft because they found linen napkins from the
restaurant containing fried oysters and fish _ a violation of the
restaurant's no-takeout policy.
   ``All of them had the buffet,'' said police Sgt. Bill Burke.
``They were good customers. When they left, they concealed their
food, but there is no takeout.''
   All nine were free on bail Tuesday.
