<FIRST>u a PM-AbortionConsent 2ndLd-Writethru a0631 05-16 0627</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion Consent, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0631,0639</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abortion Consent Law Left In Limbo By Florida's High Court</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with U.S. Supreme Court issuing
stay; Picks up 4th graf, ``Certainly time ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Supreme Court Justice Anthony M.
Kennedy today blocked a 15-year-old Florida girl from getting an
abortion without first getting the consent of her parents or a
judge.
   The stay came just three hours after the Florida Supreme Court
said it would allow the girl to get an abortion, clearing the way
for other minors to have abortions without such permission.
   The state's abortion-consent law, which took effect in February,
was ruled unconstitutional by a state appellate court Friday and
the state Supreme Court said today it would rule this fall on the
law's constitutionality.
   Kennedy, acting on a request by a lawyer appointed to represent
the fetus, issued a stay in Washington. His order blocks the
abortion until the full U.S. Supreme Court considers the matter,
probably at a closed conference Thursday.
   The case involves a 15-year-old girl who wants an abortion but
was afraid to seek her parents' consent.
   ``Certainly time is of the essence, and that can be determined
from the flurry of activity,'' Richard Boylston, a lawyer from
Tavares appointed to represent the interest of the fetus, had said
earlier.
   Jerri Blair, attorney for the Lake County 15-year-old, filed a
motion Monday to dissolve the stay.
   The girl is 12 weeks pregnant, and many clinics won't perform
abortions after the 13th week of pregnancy because of a greater
risk of medical complications, she noted.
   Ms. Blair refused to say today if her client had been told of
the decision and also said she would not disclose any decision the
girl makes on whether to go ahead with the abortion.
   ``I think we are examining a law that needs to be examined, that
needs to be very clear for the trial courts,'' Ms. Blair said.
``Ultimately, what will happen, it will cause the Legislature to
revisit and clarify the guidelines.''
   The state high court will set a schedule for lawyers to submit
written arguments on the constitutional issues and argue the case
before the justices in the fall.
   The case began May 2 when the girl petitioned a Lake County
court for permission to get an abortion without her parents'
consent. She said she could not approach her parents for permission
without fearing emotional or physical abuse.
   Two days later, Circuit Judge Jerry T. Lockett denied the girl's
petition, saying the state's abortion-consent law was unworkable
because it is unconstitutionally vague and does not let judges hold
proper hearings.
   Charlene Carres, legislative counsel for the Florida American
Civil Liberties Union, filed a friend-of-the-court brief Monday
claiming that the girl had a constitutional right to privacy, and
hence to an abortion, without outside consent.
   The Florida Attorney General's Office filed a motion supporting
the parental-consent law.
   Of approximately 75,000 abortions performed in Florida last
year, about a third were on minors, according to pro-choice
activists. Yet, since the new law took effect in February, few
teen-agers have gone through the court system to seek a judge's
permission for an abortion.
   Janis Compton-Carr, executive director of the Florida Abortion
Rights Action League, says many are simply bypassing the legal
system and traveling to Georgia.
   Amanda Jones, director of a Gainesville abortion clinic called
the Bread and Roses Well Women Care Center, said Monday that she
has referred 20 to 30 girls to Georgia abortion clinics in recent
months, but fears many of them wouldn't be able to afford the trip.
   ``Some girls can't even get a ride to the center, much less to
Georgia,'' Ms. Jones said.
</TEXT>
