<FIRST>r w AM-Quayle     05-16 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quayle,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quayle Returns To Senate To Praise, Jokes And A Request For Money</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Dan Quayle made a nostalgic
return Tuesday to the Senate committee room where he helped shape
the nation's largest job training program and was met with heaps of
praise, a handful of jokes and a serious request for more money.
   The topic of the unusual forum hosted by members of the Senate
Labor Committee was the Job Training Partnership Act, which Quayle,
then a senator, and Sen. Edward M. Kennedy co-authored in 1982. The
program was cited during the presidential campaign as Quayle's
major congressional achievement.
   Quayle's appearance came less than a week after Labor Secretary
Elizabeth Dole introduced the Bush administration proposals to
answer criticisms of the program.
   The administration proposed channeling most money to the
unskilled poor and teen-agers and establishing a separate program
title for youth-training programs now scattered throughout JTPA
ventures that also serve adults.
   Current formulas, written by Quayle and Kennedy in the midst of
the 1981-82 recessions, allocated two-thirds of JTPA money to areas
with high unemployment rates regardless of whether those unemployed
lack basic skills.
   Tuesday's forum was designed to promote bipartisanship as
Congress considers major revisions to the program. But with no new
ground to break, the sessions instead largely unfolded as a
love-fest for Quayle
   Kennedy, leading the praise, also took a minute to add that he
expected Quayle to lobby President Bush for additional funding for
the multi-billion-dollar program.
   ``We were genuine partners on JTPA but Dan Quayle was the senior
partner,'' said Kennedy, D-Mass. ``It was a Quayle-Kennedy bill,
not a Kennedy-Quayle bill.''
   Kennedy praised Quayle for sticking with the bill despite
opposition from the Reagan-Bush administration. Quayle himself
recalled having not-so-nice things to say about the occupants of
the White House at that time.
   ``I can remember those days, Orrin, how we referred to those
folks down there at the White House,'' Quayle said to Sen. Orrin
Hatch, R-Utah, who at the time was committee chairman.
   But he added with a smile: ``I've changed my mind.''
   There were jokes about Quayle's age, too.
   Sen. Paul Simon, D-Ill., said he missed having the 42-year-old
vice president as the ranking Republican on a subcommittee he
leads, a position now held by Sen. Strom Thurmond.
   ``He has not had as much experience in the Senate as you have
had,'' Simon said jokingly of the 86-year-old Thurmond, who has
served in the Senate since Quayle was 9 years old.
   Quayle thanked his former colleagues for their praise but said
it was their work that would bring about the needed changes to JTPA.
   After all, he told them, he was at the forum only ``as someone
remarked, somebody who used to have an important job in this town.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
