<HEAD>Evangelist Says Fund Drive Goes Over Top</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oral Roberts said Tuesday a seven-week
``life-or-death'' fund drive raised the $11 million his ministry
needs to pay creditors.
   The 71-year-old evangelist in March said he needed the money by
Oral Roberts University's graduation May 6 or creditors would start
dismantling the school, the ministry and its hospital, the City of
Faith Medical Center.
   Ministry officials met with creditors to seek additional time,
and Roberts announced in a live broadcast Tuesday that the final
$24,000 had been raised.
   Ministry spokeswoman Jan Dargatz said that does not mean the
evangelist's financial worries are over. Monthly contributions must
be kept at about $3.3 million to sustain the ministry, the
university and the hospital, she said.
   The ministry said monthly contributions declined from $5 million
to $2.7 million over the past two years. Roberts blamed ``a spirit
of skepticism'' after scandals in the ministries of Jim Bakker and
Jimmy Swaggart.
</TEXT>
