<FIRST>r a AM-DeadSeals     05-16 0182</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dead Seals,0188</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seventh Dead Seal Found; Cause Unknown</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists said Tuesday that they have
been unable to determine what killed seven seals washed ashore
since April 27 and that the deaths simply may reflect an increasing
seal population.
   ``We've seen more seals south of Cape Cod and all the way down
to Chesapeake Bay than we normally do,'' said Doug Beach, a
biologist with the National Marine Fisheries Service in Woods Hole,
Mass.
   The dead harbor seals washed ashore in Portsmouth and Tiverton.
   ``The animals must have died pretty suddenly,'' said Bernadette
Bode, spokeswoman for the Mystic Marinelife Aquarium in Mystic,
Conn. ``They weren't suffering from a long-term illness'' and
showed no signs of poisoning or injury.
   ``There were a lot of harbor seals in the area,'' she said. ``It
could be a natural occurrence. It doesn't necessarily point to any
evil against the animals.''
   Harbor seals, which grow to 160 to 200 pounds and 4{ to 5{ feet
long, normally spend winters in Long Island Sound and migrate to
northern New England in the summer.
</TEXT>
