<FIRST>r a AM-Divorce-EmbryosJudge     05-16 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Divorce-Embryos Judge,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Says Divorce-Embryos Case Extraordinary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARYVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The judge preparing for a custody battle
over frozen embryos says he's reminded of the classic Scopes
``monkey trial'' that thrust another small Tennessee court under a
national microscope 64 years ago.
   Circuit Court Judge W. Dale Young said the custody case weighs
so heavily on his mind that he reread ``Six Days or Forever,'' Ray
Ginger's account of the 1925 Scopes trial in Dayton, in which the
teaching of evolution was attacked successfully.
   That trial drew national attention as famed attorneys Clarence
Darrow and William Jennings Bryan squared off.
   ``There's not a day goes by that I don't think about the case
and what the issue will be,'' Young said of the custody battle
between Junior Lewis Davis and Mary Sue Davis. The trial is
scheduled for Aug. 7.
   ``Never in my wildest dreams did I think hearing any lawsuit in
this court would attract the attention of more than 12 jurors and
the parties,'' he told The Knoxville Journal in an interview
published Monday.
   Young said he mostly hears cases involving domestic matters,
civil suits, minor injury and malpractice. His 65-seat courtroom
probably won't be able to hold the reporters, spectators and
lawyers expected for the Davis case.
   Davis obtained a court order temporarily barring his wife from
having seven in-vitro fertilized eggs implanted for pregnancy. He
said the embryos are joint property and that implanting them would
violate his right to decide whether to become a father.
   His wife has said she considers the embryos her best chance to
become a mother. Her attorney has argued that Davis decided to
become a father when he participated in the test-tube baby program.
   Young, a soft-spoken man with an easy smile, said he won't let
the national attention affect his decision.
   ``We're going to do it in a professional manner,'' he said.
</TEXT>
