<SECOND>AM-Brites,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANNAPOLIS, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opponents of a bill to ban ``junk fax'' _
unsolicited facsimile messages _ have jammed the governor's fax
machine with protests.
   Now he's more likely to look kindly on the legislation, says an
aide.
   ``If we had any important messages coming in we wouldn't have
been able to get them through,'' said David S. Iannucci, the
governor's lobbyist.
   Gov. William Donald Schaefer's office received 343 fax messages
after a California group, the National Fax Users Committee of
Mission Viejo, faxed hundreds of one-page protest fliers to
Maryland businesses.
   Businesses were urged to sign a protest message on the flyer,
tear the message off and fax it to the Statehouse. About one fifth
of the businesses receiving the message sent it on to the governor,
Ianucci said.
   Iannucci called Thursday's one-day campaign ``incredibly
counterproductive,'' saying it might help persuade Schaefer to sign
the bill.
   One executive sent his flier with an added message, asking
Schaefer to sign the bill into law and stop people ``from using my
fax machine as their printing press.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pollster sampling Minnesotans' perceptions
of Republican Sen. Rudy Boschwitz made one call straight into what
may become the enemy camp.
   One of the people who answered the phone was Walter Mondale, the
former Democratic vice president who is mentioned as a possible
opponent of Boschwitz in 1990. Numbers were picked at random from
some 1.5 million households.
   ``The odds against this happening are unbelievable,'' said Tom
Mason, Boschwitz's campaign director.
   Mondale was on an East Coast trip and not immediately available
for comment.
