<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-89 1604EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-BlindPassengers     05-16 0457</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Blind Passengers,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Committee Passes Bill for Blind Air Passengers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Senate committee approved legislation on
Tuesday that would bar airlines from refusing to seat blind
passengers in rows that have emergency exits.
   The measure, approved on a voice vote, goes against a proposed
Federal Aviation Administration regulation that would prohibit
blind and other disabled people from sitting next to emergency
doors.
   The ease with which the measure was approved by the Commerce
Committee _ debate lasted only several minutes _ might not be
indicative of its prospects for final enactment. Although only two
members of the committee spoke against the bill, congressional
sources said some public supporters have private doubts.
   The bill has been lobbied heavily on both sides, and at least
one member of the committee who supports the measure admits that
the issue has put him in an uncomfortable position.
   ``How would you like to be the guy who voted for this bill on
the one-in-a-billion chance that a blind person was sitting next to
an exit door when an incident occurred, and something happens?''
said the senator, speaking on condition he not be further
identified.
   One congressional source, also speaking only on condition of
anonymity, acknowledged the measure's 31 co-sponsors and the ease
with which it cleared the commerce panel, but said, ``A lot of
people did it anticipating it wasn't going to go anywhere.''
   Groups representing the blind have complained that some
airlines' policies of refusing to seat blind people near emergency
exits are discriminatory. Some advocates for the blind have been
removed from planes and arrested after refusing to leave exit seats
to which they had been assigned.
   The bill's sponsor, committee chairman Ernest Hollings, D-S.C.,
said the legislation would ``move to eliminate once and for all the
embarrassment and hassle given our blind passengers.''
   But lined up on the other side are the FAA, the airline industry
and many of its labor unions, who argue that if an emergency
occurred, the danger could be greater if the seat nearest the exit
were occupied by a blind traveler.
   In a letter to Hollings written last week, the Air Transport
Association _ which represents the nation's major airlines _ asked
for a study of the problem in place of the legislation.
   ``Until such time as there is good evidence that persons with
visual impairments will not impede an emergency evacuation, we
continue to believe that the prudent course of action is to put the
safety of all passengers and crew members ahead of the narrow
interests of a vocal advocacy group,'' the association wrote.
   A similar bill has been introduced in the House, but it has yet
to receive committee approval.
</TEXT>
