<FIRST>r i AM-SouthAfrica     05-16 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa,0408</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anti-Apartheid Politician Retiring After 36 Years In Parliament</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Helen Suzman, South Africa's
best-known white civil rights campaigner, said Tuesday she will
retire in September after 36 years at the forefront of
anti-apartheid opposition in Parliament.
   ``She will be missed as a courageous fighter who was ahead of
her time,'' said Con Botha, chief spokesman for the governing
National Party.
   Mrs. Suzman, 71, is the longest-serving member of Parliament,
having represented the same Johannesburg constituency since 1953.
   From 1961 until 1974, she was the only legislator representing
opponents of South Africa's legal policy of race discrimination.
Often, she cast the sole vote against discriminatory or repressive
laws.
   She said she would not seek re-election Sept. 6, when a general
election will be held for the white, Asian and mixed-race chambers
of Parliament. She has campaigned consistently to extend political
rights to the black majority, which has no representation in
Parliament.
   Allies and opponents joined in praising her.
   Andries Treurnicht, leader of the extreme-right Conservative
Party, said: ``I didn't agree with her political views, but she was
someone you could respect for the conviction with which she held
them.''
   One of her liberal colleagues, Colin Eglin, said her years in
politics ``were perhaps unequalled for sustained excellence by an
opposition politician in any parliament in the world.''
   ``Her departure will leave a huge vacuum,'' said The Argus, a
Cape Town newspaper.
   Mrs. Suzman told reporters it was time to let a younger
politician represent her district. She also said she would attempt
to write her memoirs.
   ``My most important task, the disappearance of apartheid, has
not been completed,'' she said. ``But a number of important laws
have been repealed, laws which I opposed when they were introduced,
and that's a source of considerable satisfaction for me.''
   Probably more so than any other white elected official, Mrs.
Suzman earned the trust and good will of black activists. She
attended funerals of slain militants, frequently visited black
townships and in 1987 finished ninth in a poll asking black
newspaper readers who they wanted as president.
   She met several times with imprisoned black leader Nelson
Mandela, who placed first in that newspaper poll, and she
repeatedly called for his release. Mandela's wife, Winnie, once
referred to Mrs. Suzman as ``the conscience of white South Africa.''
</TEXT>
