<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Korea-US     05-16 0158</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Korea-US,0162</SECOND>
<HEAD>South Korea Will Spend More on American Military</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government will bow to
Washington's demands and spend more to maintain U.S. troops in
South Korea, it was reported Tuesday.
   In a plan submitted to the National Assembly, the government
said the country will gradually pay more. But Washington should
consider Seoul's already heavy defense burden, which is equivalent
to 6 percent of the gross national product, according to the Yonhap
News Agency.
   Washington, citing the strong economy, has requested that Seoul
contribute more to the cost of maintaining U.S. troops in South
Korea.
   The United States keeps about 43,000 troops in South Korea under
a mutual defense pact to protect it from a possible invasion from
communist North Korea.
   Last year, Seoul spent $2.2 billion maintaining U.S. troops in
South Korea, including $105 million in direct financial aid and the
rest in indirect support such as providing facilities, Yonhap said.
