<FIRST>u a AM-Byrne-Sentencing     05-16 0439</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Byrne-Sentencing,0456</SECOND>
<HEAD>Copeland Gets Maximum in Byrne Slaying</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To thunderous applause from 150 police officers,
a judge Tuesday sentenced a drug dealer to 25 years to life in
prison _ the maximum _ for murdering a rookie policeman guarding
the home of a drug witness.
   ``This arrogant act assaults our society,'' Supreme Court
Justice Thomas A. Demakos told Philip Copeland, 23, who was
convicted along with two other men March 29 in the February 1988
slaying of Officer Edward Byrne.
   ``There is no doubt that, of the three, Copeland was the
worst,'' said Demakos, charging that Copeland arranged the murder
after getting an to ``ice a cop'' in a jailhouse telephone call
from alleged drug kingpin Howard ``Pappy'' Mason.
   Byrne was shot five times at close range as he sat alone in a
parked patrol car on a crack-infested street early on the morning.
He was guarding a house that had been firebombed after its owner
complained about drug dealers outside.
   The case was given national attention by President Bush, who
during the campaign for the White House called it a symbol of
drug-related crime.
   Demakos told Copeland he is ``unfit to be a member of our
society.'' The judge said that he would recommend no parole and
that when he retires, his last act would be to remind the parole
board of his recommendation.
   When Copeland's lawyer, Frank Hancock, told the judge Copeland
feared for his safety in prison, there was more applause from the
officers who packed the courtroom.
   Byrne's mother, Ann, wept as she heard the sentence. Her
husband, Matthew, a former police lieutenant, was stoic.
   The judge postponed until June 6 the sentencing of Copeland's
co-defendants.
   All three earlier rejected a request to name Mason as the
mastermind of the murder in exchange for leniency.
   ``This is a crime of monstrous proportions,'' said Assistant
District Attorney Eugene Kelly. ``This was a message to society.''
   Prosecutors alleged that Mason placed a ``hit'' order by
telephone to Copeland, who recruited the others and promised them
$8,000. Cobb, in a videotaped confession, said of the murder: ``We
lose one, they lose one.''
   Prosecutors said Cobb was the getaway car driver. David McClary,
21, identified by two defendants as the triggerman, goes on trial
Wednesday.
   Byrne's funeral drew 10,000 uniformed police officers from
around the country. The slain officer's father presented then-GOP
nominee Bush with his son's police shield during the presidential
campaign.
   Mason has denied involvement in the murder. He is in prison on a
weapons charge and face charges of drug-racketeering and killing a
parole officer.
</TEXT>
