<FIRST>r a AM-ExtortionIndictment     05-16 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Extortion Indictment,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Virginian Accused of Trying to Extort $2 Million from Coca-Cola Co.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal grand jury on Tuesday indicted
a Virginia man on charges that he tried to extort $2 million from
the Coca-Cola Co. and two of its top officials by threatening to
poison their products.
   The 14-count indictment charged Lester L. Hummer, about 47, with
extortion, interstate travel in aid of a racketeering enterprise,
attempting to tamper with consumer products and mailing threatening
communications.
   Hummer, of Berryville, Va., allegedly sent several extortion
letters to Coca-Cola President and Chief Operating Officer Donald
R. Keough and Chairman and Chief Executive Officer Roberto C.
Goizueta between Feb. 22 and April 16, when he was arrested.
   Hummer was arrested at a drop site near Washington-Dulles
International Airport where he was to be paid. He has been held
without bond since his arrest. Arraignment is scheduled Monday
before U.S. District Judge Albert V. Bryan Jr.
   U.S. Attorney Henry Hudson said there was no evidence that
Hummer or anyone else actually tampered with any products.
   ``Due to the cooperation of the Coca-Cola Co. and the
extraordinary investigative skills of the Federal Bureau of
Investigation, I am convinced that we have arrested the only
individual who was involved in these extortion attempts and have
done so prior to his carrying out any of the threats he has made in
this matter,'' Hudson said in a statement.
   Hummer faces a maximum prison term of 145 years and a fine of
$3.5 million if convicted on all counts.
   Coca-Cola spokesman Randy Donaldson declined to comment on the
case, other than to say the company had cooperated fully with
authorities.
</TEXT>
