<DOCNO> AP890516-0140 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-89 1658EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-BRF--CleanCampaigns     05-16 0152</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Clean Campaigns,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Danforth and Hollings Offer Bill to Curb Negative Campaign Ads</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislation to curb negative political
advertising and independent campaign expenditures was proposed
Tuesday by Sens. John Danforth, R-Mo., and Ernest Hollings, D-S.C.
   ``Increasingly the sentiment of the American people when they
look at American politics today is nausea,'' said Danforth, adding:
``Campaigns should be to inform the public not to nauseate the
public, not to make them feel like throwing up.''
   The bill would require broadcasters to provide free time to
presidential and congressional candidates to respond when:
   _Opponents broadcast ads that refer to them. This would not
apply if an opponent appears in the ad to personally make the
attack.
   _An independent committee or individual broadcasts any type of
political ad either supporting or opposing a candidate. The
senators said this is mainly directed at ads paid for by political
action committees, or PACs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
