<FIRST>r w AM-ArmsSales     05-16 0153</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Arms Sales,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Selling F-16s to Portugal, Netherlands</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Defense Department notified Congress on
Tuesday it had approved four arms transactions with NATO allies,
including sales of F-16 jet fighters to Portugal and the
Netherlands.
   Assuming there are no congressional objections, the Pentagon
said Portugal would be offered 20 F-16s and support equipment for
about $300 million. The Netherlands plans to purchase 10 F-16s,
less engines, for $116 million, the Pentagon added.
   The other two transactions involve the sale of five SH-2F LAMPS
submarine-hunting helicopters to Portugal for $99 million, and the
sale of 1,400 Seasparrow anti-aircraft missiles to a consortium of
seven NATO allies for $360 million.
   The consortium includes Belgium, Canada, Denmark, West Germany,
the Netherlands, Greece and Norway.
   The Navy will oversee the sale of the Seasparrows and the
helicopters, and the Air Force will oversee the sale of the F-16's,
the Pentagon statement said.
</TEXT>
