<FIRST>r w AM-Congress-TV     05-16 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-TV,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Industry Urges Steps to Speed HDTV</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Industry witnesses urged Congress Tuesday to
create a trust fund, increase tax credits and take other steps to
encourage research and development work on high-definition
television.
   ``Japanese and European governments have been investing in HDTV
technologies for years,'' Jerry K. Pearlman, chairman and president
of Zenith Electronics Corp., told a Senate subcommittee.
   ``Now is the time for ours to do the same,'' he said. Pearlman
told the subcommittee on science, technology and space.
   Pearlman, whose company is the sole domestic television
manufacturer, proposed setting up a trust fund, financed by a $5
per television excise tax, to pay for the federal portion of HDTV
research by U.S. companies.
   With television sales in the United States running about 20
million a year, such a trust fund could raise $100 million per year.
   Pearlman suggested that after three to four years the excise tax
on conventional televisions could be dropped and the program
financed through sales of high-definition sets.
   Meanwhile, Sen. Albert Gore, D-Tenn., introduced a bill that
would require the secretary of commerce to draft within 90 days a
plan of policies and procedures that would underlie development of
high-definition television production.
   Gore, who heads the Commerce subcommittee on technology, said
such production will ``consume more semi-conductors than the entire
U.S. personal computer industry.''
   High-definition TV promises far sharper pictures and clearer
sound than possible from conventional sets.
</TEXT>
