<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-89 1701EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Missiles     05-16 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Missiles,0364</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cabinet Dispute Over Bonn's Position on Missiles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The NATO dispute over deployment of
short-range missiles has widened a split within the government, a
newspaper reported Tuesday.
   Transport Minister Friedrich Zimmermann was quoted by the Bild
am Sonntag newspaper as accusing Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich
Genscher of covering up his true disarmament aims.
   ``If you look Genscher in the eyes, you know that he is lying,''
the newspaper quoted Zimmermann of the Conservative Socialist Union
as saying during a May 8 meeting of his party leadership.
   Zimmermann on Tuesday denied the report, but Bild am Sonntag
editor Michael Spreng immediately issued a statement saying the
newspaper stood by its article and that it was based on first-hand
reports.
   West Germany's wavering on the issue has triggered a crisis
within the Bonn leadership as well as within NATO. Kohl's coalition
government is composed of three divergent parties _ his own
Christian Democratic Union, the conservative Christian Socialist
Union of Bavaria and the liberal Free Democratic Party.
   Genscher has been at the forefront of West German resistance to
NATO's plan to upgrade short-range missiles deployed in West
Germany, urging the superpowers to try to negotiate down their
weapons stockpiles.
   He has denied he wants the complete elimination of short-range
rockets. But he is a member of the liberal Free Democratic Party
and a vocal supporter of improving relations with Eastern Europe,
and some Bonn officials charge Genscher is aiming for a
nuclear-free Europe.
   A May 29-30 NATO summit will examine the question of replacing
the Lance rockets, which have a range of about 75 miles, with
missiles of a range nearing 300 miles. The United States and
Britain want the rockets upgraded.
   Bonn has insisted that the decision be put off for at least two
years, partly to avoid angering voters before the next federal
elections in December 1990.
   Opinion polls show West Germans are against renewing the
missiles and Kohl's party has suffered serious defeats in recent
local elections, as well as a nationwide tumble in public opinion
polls.
</TEXT>
