<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-89 1653EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Argentina     05-16 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina,0541</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alfonsin Seeks Meeting with President-Elect; Rejects Cabinet Resignations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM H. HEATH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Raul Alfonsin rejected
the resignation of his eight-man Cabinet on Tuesday and sought a
meeting with President-elect Carlos Menem on an orderly transition
of government.
   Menem, a flamboyant provincial governor who led an opposition
Peronist resurgence in elections on Sunday, flew to Buenos Aires
from his northwestern province of La Rioja to meet with aides.
   Menem told a newspaper he was willing to meet ``as many times as
necessary'' with Alfonsin. ``All he has to do is call me,'' Menem
said.
   Alfonsin met for 2{ hours with his Cabinet, rejecting the
resignations that Labor Minister Ideler Tonelli said were offered
``because we thought it was opportune.''
   Presidential spokesman Jose Ignacio Lopez told reporters that
Alfonsin had ordered Interior Minister Enrique Nosiglia to contact
Menem ``immediately'' to arrange a meeting.
   The president, Lopez said, plans to ask Menem to appoint liaison
teams that would maintain close contact with each ministry ``in an
effort to make the transition viable until Dec. 10,'' the last day
of Alfonsin's six-year term.
   Alfonsin's decision seemed to reject a call to advance the
inauguration to reduce tension during the nearly seven months
remaining in his term.
   Argentina's economy is staggering under triple-digit inflation,
soaring interest rates, local currency devaluation, a budget
deficit and a $59 billion foreign debt on which no interest
payments have been made since last year.
   Leaders of the Peronist Party and Alfonsin's governing Radical
Civic Union have pledged to work together to ensure a smooth
changeover, but have acknowledged that it will not be easy.
   Alfonsin has tried to balance the budget by selling off state
businesses. Menem's preference is to make the companies more
efficient but keep them in state hands.
   The Peronists have demanded increases in both the minimum wage
and federal aid to the provinces. Alfonsin has tried to hold the
line on each.
   Menem defeated Eduardo Angeloz of the governing party by 7.8
million to 6.1 million votes, or 47.3 percent to 36.9 percent.
   The president of the Chamber of Deputies, Radical Leopoldo
Moreau, suggested Alfonsin consider ``moving up the delivery of
power.''
   ``Menem obtained a resounding, majority support of society,''
Moreau said. ``And if society believes that his proposals,
illusions and hopes are within reach, then let's put them to work
as soon as possible and let's look together for solutions to
existing problems.''
   The Peronist Party also won 67 seats in the Chamber of Deputies
to give it 127, or exactly one half; and one Senate seat to give it
23, also exactly a half. The party controls 17 of 22 provincial
governorships.
   Menem, in an interview published Tuesday by the leftist
newspaper Pagina 12, said he opposed any change in the inauguration
date. It will be Argentina's first transfer of power between freely
elected governments in 61 years.
   ``The constitution is clear, and President Alfonsin must
complete his six years of office,'' Menem was quoted as saying.
   Alfonsin has been widely praised for helping democracy return to
Argentina after the brutal 1976-83 military dictatorship.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
