<HEAD>Governor Calls Top Cop's Firing `Appropriate'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to ADD that Celeste was in Washington; PICKS
UP 4th graf pvs, `Walsh's first ...'; FIXES category code.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHERINE RIZZO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Ohio Highway Patrol superintendent used
bad judgment in accepting two free trips to South Africa and
deserved to be fired, Gov. Richard Celeste said Tuesday.
   Col. Jack Walsh was dismissed Monday after he refused to accept
a demotion to major.
   ``Here's a man who's leader of an elite law enforcement
organization in our state,'' said Celeste, interviewed after a
meeting with President Bush. ``He's going to be recruiting young
blacks to come into the Ohio Highway Patrol, right?''
   Walsh's first trip to racially segregated South Africa, in 1984,
was sponsored by the Johannesburg Safety Council. The second, this
month, was sponsored by the Johannesburg City Council.
   ``I think it was appropriate to say, `We can't have you in this
position of leadership,''' the governor said.
   Celeste said the situation might have been different if Walsh
had paid his own way or at least had warned the governor's strongly
anti-apartheid administration of his plans to make a second visit
to South Africa.
   The governor said he was led to believe, wrongly, that Walsh's
first visit was at the expense of the International Association of
Chiefs of Police.
   Walsh was not available for comment Tuesday. His telephone
number is not listed. But he told The Columbus Dispatch he is
opposed to racial discrimination and saw nothing wrong with the
trip.
   ``I really can't see there is any conflict with my job as a
police officer, as superintendent of the highway patrol,'' Walsh
said. ``I guess the next thing is you won't be able to go to a
library and read a book on South Africa.''
   Walsh, 53, was part of the Highway Patrol for 31 years and was
paid about $54,000 annually. He was appointed superintendent in
1979 by Gov. James A. Rhodes.
   Walsh also was chairman of the Highway Patrol pension fund,
which has interests in companies that do business in South Africa.
   He told the newspaper his trip included a tour of ``both the
slums and the millionaires' homes.''
   Walsh was joined on the most recent trip by Dennis J. Love,
mayor of Maple Heights, a predominantly white Cleveland suburb.
   Love said the purpose of the $18,000-per-person trip was to let
business, civic and political leaders ``see South Africa and
Johannesburg for themselves.''
   ``They want people to see what it's like over there firsthand.
There's no brainwashing,'' he said. ``They did not try to force
anything on us.''
</TEXT>
