<FIRST>r w AM-RivalUnions     05-16 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rival Unions,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Smaller Union Temporarily Halts Signing Up Social Security Workers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A union seeking to oust a larger rival as the
representative of more than 60,000 Social Security workers has
withdrawn its initial effort to sign up 12,000 of those federal
employees, union officials said Tuesday.
   The National Treasury Employees Union said its move was
temporary and necessitated by delays in a planned reorganization of
the Social Security Administration that when completed will place
the 12,000 workers under the jurisdiction of regional SSA
commissioners.
   The American Federation of Government Employees, which
represents the majority of Social Security workers and 700,000
federal workers in all, characterized the NTEU's withdrawal of its
effort as a face-saving move. ``Their petition never had merit,''
AFGE President John N. Sturdivant said.
   But NTEU President Robert N. Tobias said the petition was
withdrawn because a Federal Labor Relations Authority official last
week informed the union he could not determine if NTEU had
jurisdiction over the 12,000 workers because the reorganization has
not been completed.
   ``We'll have to wait until management gets its act together but
we intend to continue our effort,'' Tobias said in a statement.
   ``It's not a matter of winning or losing because it's not over
yet,'' NTEU spokesman George King said.
   Among the federal workers represented by NTEU are those at the
regional offices of the Department of Health and Human Services,
the parent agency of SSA. HHS in September announced plans to place
12,000 of the SSA workers under the control of the regional offices
and NTEU since then has asserted it should have jurisdiction over
them.
   NTEU, which has about 145,000 members, has been seeking a
foothold among Social Security workers so it can attempt to
organize the agency's entire work force, part of its larger effort
to chip away at AFGE's lead in representing federal workers.
</TEXT>
