<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Space 1stLd-Writethru a0696 05-16 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Space, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0696,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Honors Astronauts, School Children Who Helped Name New Shuttle</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 5th graf bgng: The crew ..., to restore dropped word ``million''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush made a small ceremony do double
duty Tuesday as he honored the most recent space fliers and two
groups of school children who picked the winning name for the
newest space shuttle.
   ``We are gathered here today to celebrate the continuity of our
space program and really of our country itself, of America
herself,'' the president said as he shared a White House stage with
five shuttle astronauts, nine fifth-graders and nine math students
from grades 8-12.
   ``In a sense today's setting reflects the continuity,'' he said.
``You are pioneers pushing back the boundaries of our technological
future.''
   To astronauts David Walker, Ronald Grabe, Norman Thagard, Mark
Lee and Mary Cleave, who returned on May 8 from a four-day shuttle
mission, the president said, ``You've reaffirmed your nation's
genius in science and technology and yet, I think we would all
agree, this really is only just the beginning.''
   The crew on the 29th shuttle flight launched a space probe that
will orbit Venus after an 800-million-mile, 15-month journey and
map the surface of Earth's fog-shrouded sister planet.
   The pupils, from Senatobia Middle School in Senatobia, Miss.,
and Tallulah Falls School in Tallulah Falls, Ga.,. each submitted
the name ``Endeavour,'' for the shuttle being built to replace the
ill-fated Challenger, which exploded after its launch in January
1986.
   ``My friends, choosing a name can be a thankless task,'' said
Bush. ``Consider the new father who was once reproached by Sam
Goldwyn. `You are going to call your son William,' he said. ``What
kind of a name is that? Every Tom, Dick and Harry is called
William.'''
   Endeavour will have the British spelling. It was the name of the
flagship used by James Cook, the 18th century English explorer and
it was chosn from several names by 31 of the 111 state-level
winners.
   Bush recalled that more than 6,100 teams formed by 71,650
students submitted research projects supporting the names they
selected. Panels from state education agencies picked state winners
in the two divisions and Bush made the final selection.
</TEXT>
