<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-89 1908EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Budget     05-16 0597</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Budget,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush, Budget Leaders Turn to 1991; Some Say New Taxes Likely</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With final approval near on the 1990 federal
budget, President Bush and congressional leaders on Tuesday began
laying groundwork for a fiscal 1991 package that some of the
lawmakers said must include new taxes.
   Bush did not comment on any options presented to him, including
the possibility that new taxes would be needed to meet budget
deficit goals.
   White House Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater said, ``The
president's attitude is that he does not want to raise taxes now or
any time, but you consider each budget year as it comes. We did not
raise taxes in 1990; obviously no one wants to do it in 1991.''
   Doing it would also go against Bush's ``Read my lips, no new
taxes'' campaign pledge of last year.
   Rep. Leon Panetta, D-Calif., chairman of the House Budget
Committee, said participants in the meeting made ``some good
progress'' toward discussions on the sticky subjects such as taxes
and spending cuts.
   ``The only specifics that we all discussed there was the fact
that everything is going to have to be on the table _ defense,
entitlements, taxes, all three are going to have to be part of that
kind of package,'' he said after the meeting with Bush.
   ``There weren't any violent reactions,'' said House Speaker Jim
Wright of Texas when reporters asked him how Bush had reacted to
suggestions of new taxes.
   Rep. Thomas Foley of Washington, the House majority leader, said
administration officials ``have not ruled out discussion of any
options'' but that the White House had sent no signals that it was
willing to look at new taxes.
   ``Next year's budget is going to be monumentally more difficult
than this year's,'' said Wright when he emerged from the meeting
that included Bush's budget team and several Democratic and
Republican lawmakers.
   Several of the members in the meeting told Bush there is no way
they can produce a budget meeting next year's $64 billion deficit
ceiling unless he agrees to new taxes, said those who were present.
   Sen. Pete Domenici of New Mexico, ranking Republican on the
Senate Budget Committee, said there was general discussion of
options on what must be done next year. He said the group agreed to
``continue the momentum of working together ... to continue serious
discussions about starting soon with a group representing the
leadership that would begin to look seriously at all the options
for the 1991 budget.''
   Wright said the 1990 budget that is expected to get
congressional ratification this week is ``a special case, it's
patchwork that was made possible by agreements that cannot be
duplicated next year.''
   Last month, Bush and congressional leaders agreed on a budget
outline for fiscal 1990, which begins Oct. 1. Congress has since
produced a budget resolution based on that pact.
   The House is scheduled to consider the compromise $1.2 trillion
budget on Wednesday, and final Senate action is expected late
Wednesday or Thursday.
   Some lawmakers even while signing on to the 1990 package
criticized it for using a ``smoke and mirrors'' approach to meet
the 1990 deficit ceiling of $100 billion.
   Critics say the package relied on unrealistic economic
assumptions that make the deficit seem smaller and on accounting
gimmicks that create little real saving.
   It also includes $5.3 billion in unspecified additional tax
receipts. Bush says $4.8 billion of that can come from cutting the
capital gains tax, but Democrats say his plan is a handout to the
wealthy and a money-loser.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
