<FIRST>r w AM-Governors-Bush     05-16 0608</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Governors-Bush,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governors Press State Concerns on Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bipartisan group of 13 governors met with
President Bush on Tuesday to press a list of state concerns and
said the president agreed to call a national summit meeting on
education later this year.
   Virginia Gov. Gerald Baliles said the governors expressed their
concerns on schools, the environment, roads, crime and welfare
reform in their half-hour private meeting in the Cabinet Room of
the White House.
   ``We told the president that we need a road map, a game plan, if
this country is going to maintain its momentum,'' Baliles, a
Democrat and chairman of the National Governors' Association, said
afterward.
   ``Governors are realistic. They know these issues are not going
to be resolved in 100 days,'' he said. ``But they're also eager for
results. We want to work with Washington, but we're not waiting on
Washington.''
   Iowa Gov. Terry Branstad, a Republican, said he had first
suggested a domestic summit meeting of governors and education
leaders when Bush met with the governors after his election in
November, and repeated that request Tuesday.
   He said Bush ``indicated he will host a summit conference on
education ... in September and will be working with the governors
in planing for that.'' He said the meeting would include governors,
state education chiefs and local educators who are trying
innovative approaches to improve learning.
   A recent report by Education Secretary Lauro Cavazos ranked the
states in education and concluded education is not improving
overall in the nation.
   Despite that, Branstad said, ``there are exciting and innovative
things happening in many of the states to deal with the education
problems of the nation, and this summit conference is going to give
us an opportunity to share them.''
   Vermont Gov. Madeleine Kunin said that she encouraged Bush to
support strenthening the clean air act and that ``delay is now not
acceptable'' on the issue. She said Bush ``seems to agree with that
fundamental message.''
   Branstad, who will become chairman of the nation's governors
this summer, said he urged more federal effort to help Midwestern
farmers deal with drought, and urged a relaxation of new federal
welfare regulations affecting the states, which he said ``don't fit
the spirit'' of the welfare reform act.
   Bush's meeting with the governors amounted to a make-up session,
since he was out of the country last winter when the National
Governors' Association held its annual Washington conference, which
traditionally includes meetings with the president and dinner at
the White House.
   The president will host the governors at a formal state dinner
Monday night.
   Earlier in the day, the governors' association released a report
by its task force on research and technology, which said states and
the federal government should take steps to promote commercial
appliciations of technological advances that are necessary to make
the United States competitive with other countries.
   It recommended a revision of federal antitrust laws to promote
joint research and development projects by businesses, and renewal
of the federal tax credit for research and development.
   The report said that the nation has spent a declining share of
its gross national product on commercially applicable research and
development in the 1980s, and that federal spending on research has
gone increasingly toward specialized military needs.
   Governors meeting with Bush were Democrats Baliles, Kunin, Mike
Sullivan of Wyoming, Booth Gardner of Washington, Richard Celeste
of Ohio, and Republicans Branstad, Michael Castle of Delaware, John
Ashcroft of Missouri, Norman Bangerter of Utah, Carroll Campbell of
South Carolina, Edward DiPrete of Rhode Island, Thomas Kean of New
Jersey and John McKernan of Maine.
</TEXT>
