<FIRST>r a AM-Dukakis-Pollution     05-16 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dukakis-Pollution,0448</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dukakis Cracks Down on Polluters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drawing personnel from across state government,
Gov. Michael S. Dukakis on Tuesday launched an environmental strike
force of 33 lawyers, scientists and law officers to bring criminal
charges against polluters.
   State officials plan to use an array of crime-fighting
techniques _ undercover agents, aerial surveillance and search
warrants _ in the pollution crackdown, which they say is the most
sweeping in the nation.
   ``These are violent crimes. They do violence against others,
against houses, against neighborhoods and against the water we
drink and the air we breathe,'' Dukakis said.
   Escorted by dozens of officers, Dukakis stood between the shore
of the Charles River and a new jail to emphasize Massachusetts'
resolve to go after polluters.
   Dukakis aides said the strike force should not be expected to
generate headlines soon because the goal is major investigations
that may take months. But their hope is that a few high-profile
prosecutions will deter polluters.
   Environmental Affairs Secretary John DeVillars, who initiated
the program after being appointed six months ago, said
investigators will concentrate on cases that involve the greatest
costs in terms of cleanup and human health.
   Dukakis aides said they plan to work with the Environmental
Protection Agency and the U.S. attorney.
   ``The state is thinking big and thinking properly,'' said Elissa
Parker, policy director at the Environmental Law Institute, a
nonprofit research group in Washington.
   She said Maryland, Ohio and Pennsylvania have strike forces that
concentrate on toxic dumping and water pollution, while
Massachusetts will also include the protection of wetlands and
other habitats.
   Except for those three states, ``there aren't any statewide
initiatives that even come close to what Massachusetts is doing,''
she said.
   Daniel Greenbaum, who heads the state Department of
Environmental Quality Engineering, said up to half the people
discharging pollutants into sewers or the air do not have permits.
Many who have permits violate their limits, he said.
   DeVillars said polluters have ruined 103 water supplies in
Massachusetts, created more than 1,000 toxic dumps and cost the
state $90 million a year in losses from contaminated shellfish beds.
   Joseph Duggan of the Greater Boston Chamber of Commerce
criticized the strike force as ``all stick and no carrot.''
   ``People who are intentionally disobeying the law, fouling the
land and atmosphere, should be cracked down on and made to pay,''
Duggan said. But others find out after buying property that it was
contaminated and are ordered to clean it up.
   ``We are objecting to that. We don't think it's the right
approach,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
