<FIRST>r w AM-NASAJob     05-16 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NASA Job,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>New NASA Head Says He'll Fight for Space Station</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new acting head of NASA moved quickly
Tuesday to fill a key vacancy and told space agency employees he'll
fight against ``potential cuts that could delay, trim down or even
kill'' the proposed space station.
   Richard Truly, who took over as administrator on Monday, named
Samuel W. Keller to be associate deputy administrator, the No. 3
job at the space agency. J.R. Thompson was nominated by President
Bush earlier to be deputy administrator.
   ``I will be filling other top jobs as quickly as I can,'' said
Truly, whose own confirmation hearings are to begin soon. ``I
intend to do all that I can to ensure that NASA continues to
maintain and attract a team dedicated to excellence.''
   Keller has served as deputy associate administrator for space
science and applications since December 1977. He succeeds Dr. Noel
W. Hinners who was one of several NASA officials who resigned
recently because of new post-employment laws and the failure of a
pay raise to pass Congress.
   Truly, in a televised address to all NASA centers, said the
battle over construction of the space station will be especially
difficult.
   ``We can't afford to short-change Space Station Freedom or any
other major program,'' he said. ``To do so would be to deny our own
future as a nation. And I don't believe that President Bush or the
American people want that to happen.''
</TEXT>
