<FIRST>r w AM-US-Soviet-Health     05-16 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Soviet-Health,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Formed to Make Medical Goods for Soviet Union</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six American health care companies have formed
a consortium with the Soviet government to produce badly needed
medical goods for the Soviet Union, the group announced Tuesday.
   ``This is more than an experiment in sharing knowledge and
experience,'' said Dennis Sokol, who is president of the consortium
and chairman of MedServ International Inc., of Stamford, Conn., one
of the American companies.
   The other American companies are Abbott Laboratories Inc.,
Pfizer International Inc., Hewlett Packard Inc., HCA International
Co. and the Colgate-Palmolive Co.
   On the Soviet side are the Soviet ministries of Health, the
Medical and Microbiological Industry and Instrument-making Means of
Automation and Control Systems, the group said in statement.
   Sokol anticipated ``a substantial two-way flow of business for
the first time in this field,'' but said it was too early to
speculate on the volume.
   Although the Soviets claimed for years to have one of the most
advanced health care systems in the world, serious shortcomings
have been revealed under glasnost, including high rates of
alcoholism and infant mortality and a falling life expectancy for
men.
   Consortium members said the group could play a role in the
expansion of medical facilities in the Soviet Union, and quoted
Soviet Health Minister Yevgeny Chazov as saying he expects his
nation to triple health care expenditures by the year 2000.
   Barry MacTaggart, chairman of the consortium and president of
Pfizer, ancitipated that the group would market Soviet health
technologies in the West, but did not explain explain what those
might be.
   ``We expect to get the benefit here in the United States from
the technological developments that have been made in the Soviet
Union in a variety of medical and scientific areas,'' MacTaggart
said in a statement.
   Consortium members did not explain how the American participants
could profit from helping expand medical care in the Soviet Union.
The ruble cannot be converted profitably into western currencies,
and previous U.S. ventures in the Soviet Union have been hampered
by tight Kremlin rules governing how foreign firms can repatriate
their profits.
   The consortium was intended to facilitate the formation of joint
ventures involving U.S. and Soviet participants, and stemmed from
discussions that took place within the U.S.-U.S.S.R. Joint Trade
and Economic Council, a binational group aimed at promoting
commerce between the superpowers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
