<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0669 05-16 0811</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0669,0836</SECOND>
<HEAD>Car Bomb Kills Leading Moslem Cleric</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos BEI5,7</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to ADD Christian period of mourning; picks
up 6th `Rescuers had...'; DELETES grafs 12-15 `Police in...last year' which
covered in separate, and SUBS 28th, `Hoss declared...' to conform</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car bomb exploded by remote control as
the spiritual leader of Lebanon's Sunni Moslems drove past on his
way home to lunch Tuesday, killing him and 21 other people and
wounding 75, police reported.
   The explosion in Moslem west Beirut, which Syrian troops patrol,
occurred as Arab League mediators were trying to consolidate a
6-day-old truce in the latest round of fighting.
   Sheik Hassan Khaled, Lebanon's Grand Mufti and the Sunni
spiritual leader, was a leading voice for moderation in a country
devastated by 14 years of factionalism and sectarian civil war.
   Both Christian and Moslem leaders denounced the assassination,
for which there was no claim of responsibility, and declared
periods of mourning.
   Police said Khaled was being driven home from his office at 1
p.m. when the bomb went off in the crowded Aishe Bakkar district.
   Rescuers had to break the doors of Khaled's smashed black
Cadillac to pull out his mutilated body and those of his driver,
his brother-in-law Hussein Bashasheh and an unidentified companion.
   ``Our beloved Mufti is murdered!'' a policeman screamed through
tears as he took Khaled's blood-stained white turban from the
crumpled limousine.
   Firemen doused dozens of smoldering cars. Pools of blood
glistened on the street. The explosion tore the facade of an
adjacent apartment building.
   Among others killed were four bodyguards from the crack Squad 16
riot police who were burned beyond recognition in their charred
jeep, a policeman said.
   ``The assassin, or assassins, used a remote control device to
detonate the car bomb, which was rigged with more than 150
kilograms (330 pounds) of TNT,'' a police spokesman said.
   In Washington, State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said
the United States was ``revolted by the cold-blooded killing'' and
described Khaled as ``a selfless leader.''
   Khaled, 68, was spiritual leader of Lebanon's 900,000 Sunni
Moslems and was elected Grand Mufti of Lebanon 23 years ago, making
him the nation's highest- ranking Moslem cleric.
   He guided the economically powerful Sunni sect into advocating
coexistence with Christians and shunning a fighting role in the
sectarian war.
   Lebanon has more Shiite Moslems than Sunnis. Shiites loyal to
Iran are believed to hold most of the 15 foreigners missing in
Lebanon, who include nine Americans, but Sunnis are not believed to
be involved in hostage-taking.
   In the latest battle between Christians and Moslems, which began
March 8, Khaled made several calls for restraint and supported Arab
League efforts for a truce.
   Salim Hoss, acting premier in the Moslem cabinet of Lebanon's
dual goernment, said ``We shall never deviate from the course of
moderation our martyred grand mufti has charted.''
   Hoss, a Sunni, spoke after meeting with senior Sunni politicians
at Khaled's headquaters.
   In September 1984, Khaled and Hoss escaped death by car bomb as
they set out together in a motorocade for prayers marking the
Moslem feast of Al-Adha. Hoss suffered scratches and Khaled was
unscathed.
   Tuesday's bomb exploded only 100 yards from the Hoss residence.
A policeman guarding his home was among the dead.
   Syria's Moslem allies blamed the assassination on Gen. Michel
Aoun, who leads Christian army units in the artillery battle that
began 10 weeks ago with an alliance of Syrian soldiers and Druse
militiamen.
   The general also heads a Christian cabinet that competes for
authority with the Hoss government.
   He blamed Syria, but did not mention it by name in a statement
saying:
   ``This ugly crime confirms that the hand of terror and
oppression does not refrain from targeting the highest symbols of
moderation that advocate the unity of the nation against the plots
of partition and dismemberment.''
   Aoun called Khaled was ``a great, bold leader'' whose death
should cause Lebanese to ``take a unified stand against the
occupiers of our land.'' Aoun has pledged to continue fighting
until Syria leaves Lebanon, where it has 40,000 soldiers under a
1976 peacekeeping mandate from the Arab League.
   President Hafez Assad of Syria sent a condolence telegram
saying: ``This crime was aimed at liquidating this leader because
he fought for the unity and sovereignty of Lebanon and national
understanding.''
   Hoss declared seven days of official mourning for Khaled, who is
survived by his wife, six sons and three daughters. Political and
religious leaders in Christian east Beirut declared a day of
mourning.
   Christian and Moslem radio stations joined in the mourning.
Moslem radios broadcast verses from the Koran, Islam's holy book,
and the Christians played somber music.
   The car bombing was the sixth and worst of the year. By police
count, the previous explosions killed 28 people and wounded 218.
</TEXT>
