<FIRST>u i AM-Obit-Khaled     05-16 0546</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Khaled,0568</SECOND>
<HEAD>Slaying Silences One of Few Prominent Moderates in Lebanon</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Lebanon, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY13</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIAD KAHWAJI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The assassination of Grand Mufti Hassan
Khaled, spiritual head of Lebanon's Sunni Moslem sect, silenced one
of the few remaining voices of moderation after 14 years of civil
war.
   A spellbinding orator, the 68-year-old Khaled was an unbending
champion of ``dialogue, not the gun'' to re-establish peaceful
coexistence between Moslems and Christians.
   During his 23-year reign as grand mufti, the nation's highest
Moslem religious post, Khaled urged the 900,000 economically
powerful Sunnis to shun any military role in the civil war.
   When the only Sunni militia _ the Mourabitoun, or ambushers _
was disbanded in 1985, Khaled used the powers of his office to
block the emergence of any other Sunni paramilitary faction.
   He was killed on Tuesday when a car bomb exploded in Beirut as
his car drove by. The explosion killed 21 others and injured 75,
police said.
   Khaled was born in 1921 to a middle-class Beirut family. He
finished his high school education at Beirut's College of Islamic
Theology and graduated in 1946 from Al-Azhar University in Cairo,
Egypt, the world's most prestigious Islamic institute.
   Khaled started his career as a teacher of logic at the College
of Islamic Theology in Beirut.
   In 1957, he was appointed an Islamic law judge in Lebanon's
northern province of Akkar and was transfered to a similar position
in central Lebanon.
   On December 1966, he was elected grand mufti. Khaled also headed
the Islamic bloc, a coalition of senior Sunni politicians,
including prime ministers and parliament members.
   Khaled was awarded a honorary doctorate from Al-Azhar University
and the Chinese Gen-Ge University in 1967.
   He wrote seven books and was a member of many regional and
international Islamic institutes.
   He is survived by his wife, six sons and three daughters.
   Khaled escaped a previous assassination attempt when a car bomb
exploded Sept. 5, 1984 as he prepared to drive with Sunni Prime
Minister Salim Hoss for prayers to mark the Adha feast, Islam's
holiest holiday.
   Condolence messages for Khaled poured in.
   In Washington, State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said
the United States was ``revolted by the cold-blooded killing.''
   In Kuwait, Foreign Minister Sheik Sabah Ahmed, head of the Arab
League committee on Lebanon, condemned it as ``an ugly crime
designed to deepen dissension inside'' Lebanon.
   In a statement distributed by the Kuwait News Agency, Sabah
described Khaled as ``a man of tolerance and justice who was deeply
concerned over the sufferings of the entire Lebanese people.''
   Saudi Arabia issued a statement expressing ``the king's,
government's and nation's extreme sorrow and pain at the tragic
loss.''
   His death made him the fourth Sunni figure to be assassinated in
three years.
   Sheikh Subhi Saleh, 60, a ranking Sunni cleric and staunch
advocate of Moslem-Christian coexistence, was gunned down at west
Beirut's Sakiet el-Janzir neighborhood on October 7, 1986 by masked
assassins riding a motorbike.
   Prime Minister Rashid Karami, 64, was killed in June 1987, when
a bomb exploded aboard the army helicopter that was flying him from
north Lebanon to Beirut.
   Mohammed Shokair, 70, political adviser to former President Amin
Gemayel, was killed by gunmen who stormed his home on Aug. 20, 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
