<DOCNO> AP890516-0162 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-89 1741EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-LadleDeaths     05-16 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ladle Deaths,0368</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Charged With Killing Sons In Foundry Ladle Found Guilty But Mentally
Ill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MUSKEGON, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man was found guilty of murder but
mentally ill Tuesday for killing his two sons in a 1,300-degree
foundry ladle.
   A jury deliberated nearly two hours before returning the verdict
against Bartley James Dobben, 28, in the Thanksgiving 1987 deaths
of 2-year-old Bartley Joel and 15-month-old Peter David at the
foundry where Dobben worked.
   Sentencing was set for June 16.
   The defense contended Dobben, diagnosed a paranoid
schizophrenic, was insane at the time of the slayings. Brett
Gardner, an assistant prosecutor, said Dobben killed his sons
because his marriage of four years was failing.
   According to testimony, Dobben loaded his wife and children in
the car for Thanksgiving dinner at his parents' home but told his
wife he had to get a Bible from his locker at the Cannon-Muskegon
Corp. and show the boys where he worked.
   As Dobben's pregnant wife, Susan, waited outside, Dobben put the
boys in a furnace used to hold molten metal and turned the gas jets
up until the ladle glowed red, authorities said. Autopsies showed
the boys quickly suffocated and burned.
   A jail guard, Deputy Joy Knapp, testified Dobben told her that
``by killing the kids that they would go to heaven.''
   ``Bartley felt it was a spiritual rite he was doing by killing
the kids,''' she said. ``He didn't want his kids to face the trial
and tribulations of today's society.''
   Family and friends portrayed Dobben as a loving, attentive
father who was obsessed with religion, believed the end of the
world was near and was instructed by a self-ordained minister to
stop taking drugs that controlled his behavior.
   Bizarre behavior and suspicions that his wife was unfaithful and
his family in danger resulted in a 60-day, court-ordered stay at a
psychiatric hospital in 1985, according to testimony.
   Mrs. Dobben testified she forgave her husband a day after the
slayings and wants him back home with her. The couple's third son
will be a year old in June. ``He would have given his life for
those kids,'' she testified.
</TEXT>
