<FIRST>r w AM-Osprey     05-16 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Osprey,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cheney Still Plans to Kill Osprey Aircraft Project</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney met privately
Tuesday with six congressional supporters of the V-22 Osprey
aircraft project, but they failed to sway his decision to shut down
the program, Pentagon officials said.
   The officials, speaking only on condition of anonymity, said
Cheney met with both of Pennsylvania's senators and four of its
congressmen for about 30 minutes to discuss the embattled project.
   Pennsylvania is the home state for one of the two contracting
partners developing the plane _ the Boeing Helicopter Co. The other
prime contractor is Bell Helicopter Textron Inc.
   Cheney, in overseeing cuts in the fiscal 1990 Pentagon budget
promised by President Bush, announced last month he was scuttling
the V-22 program as too expensive. Despite intense pressure ever
since, including threats by the contractors to begin immediate
layoffs, Cheney has held firm to that position.
   On Tuesday, Cheney made clear to the lawmakers that he
understood their concerns, ``but nothing has changed; there won't
be any more money for the program,'' one official said.
   The six Pennsylvania legislators were Republican Sens. John
Heinz and Arlen Specter, Republican Reps. Curt Weldon, William F.
Goodling and Don Ritter and Democratic Rep. Thomas Foglietta.
   The V-22 Osprey, described by the Marine Corps as its most
important weapons program, is a revolutionary aircraft designed to
take off like a helicopter and fly like an airplane. To do this, it
utilizes special propellers at the tip of each wing that can swivel
upward and back.
   The Marine Corps wants to use the planes to improve its ability
to conduct surprise, long-range amphibious assaults. The first of
the planes recently began flight tests in Texas.
   In fashioning the fiscal 1990 budget, Cheney concluded the
Pentagon couldn't afford the plane and the Marine Corps could do
just as well by ordering additional helicopters.
   The Pentagon had earlier planned to spend $25.9 billion on 663
Ospreys, including $1.3 billion in 1990. The department has already
invested $2 billion in the program over a nine-year period.
   Of all of Cheney's budget decisions, the cancellation of the
Osprey has attracted the most intense opposition on Capitol Hill.
The plane is built in the district of House Speaker Jim Wright,
D-Texas, and also enjoys widespread support among Republicans.
</TEXT>
