<FIRST>u w AM-CowboyConnection     05-16 0738</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cowboy Connection,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Daughter of Dallas Team Owner Fares Well on Hill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Less than a year out of Stanford, the
22-year-old daughter of new Dallas Cowboys owner Jerry Jones is
making $60,000 a year as an aide to a congressman who reports owing
at least $100,000 to Jones.
   Charlotte Jones, who holds three titles on the staff or Rep.
Tommy Robinson, D-Ark., said Tuesday ``there is absolutely no
connection'' between her meteoric rise in position and pay on
Robinson's staff and the debt the congressman owes her father.
   Members of Congress involved in current ethics probes said they
also saw nothing that would constitute a violation of House rules.
   ``If she comes to work and does the work, it's not a problem,''
said House GOP Whip Newt Gingrich of Georgia, who brought the
initial allegations of ethics violations that House Speaker Jim
Wright of Texas faces in a separate matter.
   Rep. John T. Myers, the ranking Republican on the ethics
committee now investigating the allegations against Wright, said
``there is no de facto rule'' against hiring a relative of a
campaign contributor or business partner.
   ``There is no problem if she actually does work,'' Myers said.
   Robinson, 47, and Jones, 46, have been friends since the they
attended high school together in North Little Rock. While Jones
took over his father's insurance business and became a
multimillionaire through oil and gas ventures, Robinson turned to
politics with financial backing from Jones.
   In February, Jones purchased the Dallas Cowboys football
franchise for an estimated $140 million.
   The two men own a farm together in Arkansas under the name J.R.
Agricultural Enterprises Inc., of which Robinson is president. And
Robinson listed among his liabilities in his 1987-88 financial
disclosure form a personal loan from Jones of between $100,000 and
$250,000.
   ``I don't know the details of that loan,'' Jones' daughter said
Tuesday. ``But as far as I know, monthly payments on it are being
made.''
   She conceded in an interview that her father's relationship with
Robinson was instrumental in getting her a job on the congressman's
staff as a $31,000 constituent caseworker after graduating from
Stanford last June with a degree in human biology.
   ``I cannot deny that I'm here because of my father,'' she said.
``But it's not the money, it's the motivation that he encouraged in
me. I see no ethical conflict, none whatsoever.''
   She said she has had a close friendship with Robinson back to
when she was in high school and he was a county sheriff and she
interviewed him for a class paper on politics.
   ``I have a different kind of access to him that makes it easier
for me to interrupt him or intervene with him on behalf of somebody
else,'' she said. ``I think he feels secure with me being here.
   Ms. Jones now holds three titles in Robinson's office _
administrative assistant, office manager and press secretary _ as
more of her own doing.
   The average salaries in 1987 _ there have been raises since _
for respective positions were $55,140, $25,900 and $29,000,
according to the Congressional Management Foundation, a non-profit
group that monitors congressional staff pay and provides management
services to Congress.
   However, most congressional employees with a college degree and
under 25 hold jobs such as legislative assistants with an average
pay of $23,800, or legislative correspondent involved with handling
constituent mail and services at an average pay of $18,000,
according to the foundation.
   Robinson could not be reached Monday or Tuesday. But he has
defended earlier her Ms. Jones rapid elevation on his staff, saying
she has performed her tasks ``in an exemplary way'' and adding,
``You don't really expect me to hire one of my enemies, do you?''
   ``I like people with no experience because they're not
opinionated and you can train them the way you want them to be
trained,'' he told The Arkansas Gazette, which first disclosed Ms.
Jones' salary.
   Ms. Jones said she had attempted to discourage Robinson from
boosting her pay from $51,300 to $60,000 in March after raising it
from $31,000 just two months earlier.
   ``I knew how it was going to come out in the media and cause him
political damage, and I didn't think it was worth it,'' she said.
``So I held it back for three weeks until he bantered he'd fire me
if I didn't put it through.''
</TEXT>
