<FIRST>r w AM-Moths-Abby 1stLd-Writethru   05-16 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Moths-Abby, 1st Ld-Writethru,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>EDS: Subs penultimate graf to change year to 1869, sted 1969</HEAD>
<HEAD>Virus `Abby' May Be Effective Against Gypsy Moths</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A virus called Abby shows promise of being an
effective killer of foliage-eating gypsy moths, the Agriculture
Department said Tuesday.
   Once the virus is applied, it is transmitted to each new
generation of moths, said entomologist Martin Shapiro of the
department's Agricultural Research Service.
   The agency and the Forest Service plan to field test the Abby
virus this summer in western Maryland. Scientists will count the
number of dead moth larvae and measure the amount of foliage that
was protected.
   Shapiro said if Abby passes the tests, the virus could become an
alternative to either Bacillus thuringiensis bacteria or
diflubenzuron, a chemical, presently used against the moths by
keeping them from reaching adulthood.
   Shapiro, who has worked on the virus strain for about seven
years at the agency's insect patholoy laboratory in Beltsville,
Md., named the new virus Abby after the town where it was found,
Abington, Mass.
   The Abby virus showed up early in the studies as one of the most
effective of 19 different strains of nuclear polyhdrosis virus, or
NPV, around the world. The NPV strains infect gypsy caterpillars
but may not always prevent them from defoliating trees.
   But Shapiro said the Abby virus demonstrated in laboratory tests
that it can kill more caterpillars 10 times faster than the
standard NPV, which has been used for two years by the National
Park Service in selected areas of Rock Creek Park in Washington,
D.C.
   Park officials said that wherever NPV was sprayed there was
``little or no defoliation'' to the trees. Shapiro said: ``And that
was the natural strain, not Abby.''
   Gypsy moths in the caterpillar or larvae stage are voracious
eaters of foliage. They have gradually spread from Massachusetts,
where they were imported in 1869 by a French biologist to breed
with native American silkworms.
   But the moths escaped from the laboratory and started eating
foliage. The scientist, Louis Trouvellot, returned to France and
pursued a career in astronomy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
