<DOCNO> AP890516-0169 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-89 1759EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-EthicsDelay     05-16 0248</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ethics Delay,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Signs Bill to Delay Ethics Rules</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New federal ethics rules placing strict
restrictions on post-government employment will be held up for 60
days under a delay signed by President Bush on Tuesday.
   The new regulations, which some officials have blamed for a
spate of resignations in various government agencies, including the
National Aeronautics and Space Administration and the Pentagon,
were to have taken effect Tuesday.
   But Bush signed legislation to postpone the measures until July
16 after both the House and Senate approved that request by the
Pentagon and the Office of Management and Budget.
   The new rules would ban federal contractors from hiring
government officials who have supervised their competitors'
projects, subject to maximum fines of $1 million and imprisonment
of up to five years.
   Rep. John Conyers Jr., D-Mich., chairman of the House Committee
on Government Operations, said the purpose for the delay was to
give government and industry officials ``an opportunity to train
their personnel regarding the new regulations.''
   He said the administration and industry representatives assured
his committee that they would not use the extension period ``to
seek legislative repeal or modification'' of the new ethics law.
   Thomas L. Moser, acting chief of NASA's space station program,
blamed the new ethics regulations for being too restrictive when he
tendered his recent resignation.
   The new rules are the result of legislation passed by Congress
last year. However, the administration did not issue final
regulations until last Thursday.
</TEXT>
