<FIRST>u w AM-Scotus-Wealth     05-16 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Wealth,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>O'Connor Still Richest Justice</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sandra Day O'Connor remains the Supreme
Court's only millionaire, a distinction she's held since 1987,
according to financial disclosure forms released Tuesday.
   But the court's newest justice, Anthony M. Kennedy, may have
edged closer to millionaire status within the last year.
   O'Connor is still the wealthiest justice by far. The total
wealth listed for O'Connor and her husband, a lawyer, was from $1.3
million to $2.6 million and up.
   The Ethics in Government Act, under which the statements are
filed each year, requires only broad ranges of value for the
reporting of investments and other assets. It does not require that
any asset worth less than $1,000 be listed, nor the value of
personal property items and the official's residence.
   The statement filed for O'Connor last year listed assets of $1.3
million to $2.3 million or more.
   Kennedy, who joined the court in February 1988, listed assets
for himself and his wife, a former teacher, of $348,000 to
$929,000. The report he submitted last year for 1987 listed assets
of $348,000 to $920,000.
   Kennedy, who taught at the McGeorge School of Law in Sacramento,
Calif., while a member of the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals,
reported receiving $31,900 from the school in 1988.
   He said he received $24,900 in salary, $5,000 in sabbatical pay
and a $2,000 honorarium for delivering a commencement speech.
   Kennedy also received one of the more unusual gifts reported by
any justice _ a golf bag and clubs from Sacramento residents Tom
LoPresti and Ken Morton. He estimated that the gift was worth $400.
   Among some of the other noteworthy information included in this
year's disclosure forms:
   _Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist earned $9,000 in honoraria
for three law school speeches. He donated $3,000 of that money to
various charities.
   _Justice Antonin Scalia ranked No. 1 in honoraria for 1988,
receiving $23,000 for 10 speaking or teaching engagements. No
charitable donations were listed.
   _Justice Thurgood Marshall, who over the years has listed his
only asset as a savings account worth less than $50,000, pegged the
account's worth in 1988 at $50,000 to $100,000.
   The court's eight associate justices are paid $110,000 a year.
The chief justice's annual salary is $115,000.
   Here are the listed 1988 assets of the justices:
   _Rehnquist, $186,000 to $480,000, up from the $136,000 to
$380,000 listed for 1987.
   _O'Connor, $1.3 million to $2.6 million or more, about the same
as the $1.3 million to $2.3 million or more listed for 1987.
   _Kennedy, $348,000 to $929,000, up from $348,000 to $920,000.
   _Scalia, $315,000 to $400,000, up from $165,000 to $400,000.
   _Marshall, $50,000 to $100,000, up from $15,000 to $50,000.
   _Justice Harry A. Blackmun, $195,000 to $580,000, down from
$225,000 to $680,000.
   _Justice John Paul Stevens, $183,500 to $405,000, up from
$177,000 to 385,000.
   _Justice William J. Brennan, $145,000 to $476,000, about the
same as his $141,000 to $485,000 listing for 1987.
   _Justice Byron R. White, $145,000 to $400,000. For 1987, White
had listed assets from $145,000 to $250,000 or more.
</TEXT>
