<FIRST>r w AM-AutoSafety     05-16 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auto Safety,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>New NHTSA Probes Involve More Than 4 Million Cars, Trucks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal engineers have opened investigations
into reports of safety defects in potentially 4 million cars and
trucks made in the United States and abroad, the National Highway
Traffic Safety Administration said Tuesday.
   The 10 new investigations were preliminary evaluations, the
lowest level of probe, of alleged problems in vehicles made by
major automakers.
   NHTSA said it was looking into seven complaints of engine
problems that reportedly caused fires in the 1986-88 Yugo GV, an
import from Yugoslavia.
   The unconfirmed complaints suggested the possibility of a
problem with the carburetor or fuel system, NHTSA said. There were
110,000 vehicles involved in the investigation, the agency said.
   Also, the 1985-89 Yugo GV was among nearly 2 million cars and
trucks that were the subject of new investigations into
malfunctioning brakes, NHTSA said.
   The agency said it had received two complaints, one involving an
accident, in which a front brake pad fell out, becoming stuck in
the assembly and affecting the car's ability to brake. About
100,000 vehicles were involved, NHTSA said.
   The other brake investigations involved vehicles made by General
Motors Corp.
   NHTSA said it was investigating 26 reports that the brakes in
1.5 million GM light trucks tend to pull to the left or right. The
models involved are the 1984-86 C123, K1 and K2; the 1987-88 R123,
V1 and V2; and the 1984-88 G123 pickup trucks.
   The 75,000 1988 Pontiac Lemans, according to six complaints, is
prone to weak braking. The complaints included one accident with
four injuries.
   The agency also opened preliminary evaluations into alleged
problems with the brake lamp switch on 100,000 GM 1988-89 C- and
K-series trucks and on 200,000 1989 Chevrolet Celebrity cars, based
on service bulletins issued by the company.
   Other preliminary evaluationswere into unconfirmed reports that:
   _The fuel-tank strap tends to break on 1.4 million 1981-89 Dodge
pickup trucks. The agency received 2 complaints.
   _The speed control is slow to disengage in cold weather on the
1985 Ford Mustang, Capri, Tempo and Topaz. The agency had nine
complaints.
   _The horn won't work properly on 530,000 1985-89 GM Minivan,
Astro and Safari vehicles. There were four complaints.
   The agency also opened an investigation to determine why Volvo
had changed the fuel tank and driveshaft design in its 700 series.
The investigation covers 175,000 1988-89 vehicles.
