<FIRST>r w AM-PanAm     05-16 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pan Am,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pan Am Has Lost $60 Million in Revenue Because of Flight 103 Bombing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pan Am has lost more than $60 million in
revenue because of the bombing of Flight 103 over Scotland last
December, the company's chairman said Tuesday.
   Thomas G. Plaskett said the worst losses appear to be over but
that the threat of terrorism against U.S. and other government
policies continues and governments should begin paying for a
greater share of aviation security.
   The U.S. government, Plaskett said in a speech to an aviation
industry group, should ``stop putting the financial burden on the
backs of either the industry or the traveling public.''
   The Bush administration has ordered airlines to pay the expected
$100 million cost of installing devices to detect plastic
explosives at high-risk airports around the world. But a bill is
pending in Congress to use federal funds for the units.
   The Dec. 21 bombing of Flight 103, which killed all 259 people
aboard the plane and 11 on the ground in Lockerbie, Scotland, has
been traced to a plastic bomb concealed in a checked-in
radio-cassette player.
   Plaskett said Pan Am lost $60 million in the first quarter of
1989 and more in April after some U.S. companies advised employees
not to fly on U.S. carriers in Europe because of the threat of
terrorist attacks.
   Plaskett said 12 of the last 14 terrorist incidents against
civil aviation involved non-U.S. carriers.
   He said Pan Am spends close to $45 million a year on security,
compared with an average of $10 million for foreign carriers whose
governments usually share the expense. All U.S. airlines, he said,
spend about a half-billion dollars a year on security.
   He said U.S. airlines X-ray or hand-search all checked baggage,
deny passengers access to checked baggage, carry only bags that can
be matched to passengers aboard the aircraft and give additional
screening to passengers who fit a risk profile.
</TEXT>
