<SECOND>AM-BRF--Drug Arrests, 2nd Ld-Writethru,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>EDS: Subs 2nd graf to add dollar amount.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Federal Authorities Bust Bi-Coastal Drug Ring</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal authorities arrested at least 26
people, including two Panamanian nationals, during a crackdown
Tuesday on a major drug ring that operated here and in Los Angeles
and New York, authorities said.
   U.S. Attorney Jay B. Stephens estimated the organization
distributed up to 50 kilograms of 98 percent pure cocaine and crack
every month. The FBI estimated the drugs' value at $6 million
monthly.
   The action came four days after a grand jury handed up a
112-count indictment charging 32 persons with narcotics trafficking
and conspiracy.
   Stephens said authorities on Tuesday seized four kilograms of
cocaine, thousands of dollars in cash, five cars, three houses and
several guns.
   The organization's alleged kingpins were Panamanian nationals
Marcos Loinas Anderson and Gabriel Davis-Munoz, Stephens said. He
would not dismiss a possible connection between the two and
Panamanian military strongman Manuel Antonio Noriega, but said it
would be ``speculation.''
   Officials suspect the drugs originated in Colombia and were
transported through Panama on commercial air lines to Los Angeles
and New York, using Panamanian and Jamaican immigrants as couriers.
   From there, the narcotics were moved by car to the Washington
area and in lesser degrees to Colorado Springs, Colo., and Killeen,
Texas, said FBI agent W. Douglas Gow.
   All of the suspects were charged with conspiracy and face a
maximum sentence of life imprisonment and $4 million in fines,
Stephens said.
