<FIRST>r w AM-ACLU-Meese 1stLd-Writethru a0693 05-16 0725</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-ACLU-Meese, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0693,720</SECOND>
<HEAD>Meese, Civil Liberties Group Back Collegiate Freedom of Expression</HEAD>
<BYLINE>EDS: SUBS 6th graf, Meese, who...,with two grafs to include background
on Meese and Berkeley free speech movement; SUBS 9th pvs, ``The university...,
to CORRECT spelling of citadel. ^By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Attorney General Edwin Meese III and
the American Civil Liberties Union, bitter foes in the past, joined
forces Tuesday to endorse freedom of expression on American college
campuses.
   The unlikely alliance was prompted by the settlement of a
lawsuit pitting California State University at Northridge against
James Taranto, a conservative former editor of the university's
student newspaper.
   Taranto was suspended from the news editor's job at the Daily
Sundial in 1987 after he wrote an opinion piece criticizing UCLA
officials for their handling of a controversy over affirmative
action.
   Taranto also reprinted a cartoon from the UCLA student newspaper
that satirized affirmative action.
   Meese once called the ACLU a ``criminals lobby'' and as a deputy
district attorney in 1964 had supervised the arrest of more 700
student demonstrators on the University of California's Berkeley
campus during the ``Free Speech Movement.''
   On Monday, he attended a news conference at the ACLU's
headquarters in Washington with Taranto and ACLU Director Morton
Halperin.
   ``I disagree with the ACLU on many of their policies,'' Meese
said. ``But I have never said they should not be free to espouse
them. I don't see anything inconsistent with encouraging them when
they do what is right.''
   The university should be ``a citadel of free speech,'' Meese
said, regardless of whether the views expressed are liberal or
conservative.
   Halperin said, ``We're happy to have any allies we can get on
any issue. We're delighted to have (Meese) come and express support
for First Amendment rights on campuses.''
   He added that he was particularly pleased that Meese gave his
support to the ACLU's approach to dealing with controversial
subjects. ``The remedy here is more speech, not to suppress
speech,'' Halperin said.
   The ACLU continues to believe university officials ``should
speak out'' against racist or anti-minority views when they are
expressed in student publications, Halperin said. But ``they should
not use the coercive powers of the university to censor'' those
views, he said.
   Taranto is now a public relations assistant at the conservative
Heritage Foundation here, where Meese also is employed. Taranto
said he invited Meese to attend Tuesday's news conference and the
former attorney general ``readily agreed.''
   Taranto's article in the Daily Sundial in March 1987 said UCLA
officials had helped ``stifle dissent about the issue of
affirmative action.''
   The cartoon first printed in the UCLA newpspaer, the Daily
Bruin, and reprinted to accompany Taranto's article depicted a
rooster saying he was admitted to UCLA under its affirmative action
program to help minorities.
   Taranto was suspended as editor by Cynthia Rawitch, the faculty
adviser to the student newspaper at California State. She said he
had violated a school policy requiring consultation with the
faculty adviser before running controversial articles.
   Taranto said he had been punished for his conservative views
and, with the help of the ACLU, sued the university on grounds his
free-speech rights had been violated.
   ``Campus leftists are attempting to silence conservative
students through censorship and intimidation,'' Taranto said.
   Under the settlement to the suit announced Tuesday, the
university agreed to give Taranto $93 in back pay for the two-week
suspension and remove the reference to his suspension from his
university records.
   The university also amended its policy on publication of
controversial articles in the Daily Sundial. It agreed to declare
the newspaper a ``public forum'' and permit publication of
controversial material without the faculty adviser's permission
unless the material could be obscene, libelous or invade someone's
privacy.
   Michael Emery, head of the university's journalism department,
said in a telephone interview he considers the settlement fair for
both sides.
   ``Everybody now knows exactly where they stand,'' he said. Emery
described the incident involving Taranto's article as ``a real
quirky deal'' and said the university always has stood for freedom
of expression.
   The cartoon caused ``holy hell'' when it was printed in the UCLA
newspaper, he said. ``There could have been a similar explosion at
our school.''
   But Emery said in the future the student-run newspaper would be
free to run such material without consulting with the faculty
adviser.
</TEXT>
