<FIRST>r a AM-LATeachers     05-16 0571</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-LA Teachers,0590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Students March, Scatter or Loaf as Teacher Strike Continues</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos LA4,5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE V. BIGELOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The half million students affected by a
strike in the nation's second-largest school district held raucous
demonstrations, played hooky or dawdled through a second day of
classes Tuesday with too few teachers.
   ``To even pretend any teaching was going on would be short of
ridiculous,'' said Don Schrack, a spokesman for United Teachers-Los
Angeles, which represents about 22,000 teachers, counselors, nurses
and librarians.
   Informal talks were continuing, but negotiators appeared to be
awaiting a report due Wednesday from a state fact-finder, who began
investigating the claims of both sides last March when negotiations
reached an impasse in the 16-month contract dispute.
   Hundreds of boisterous students marched out of Benjamin Franklin
High School in Highland Park and faced off briefly with police
after a patrol car was pelted with rocks.
   Students left Belmont High School to picket the school
district's downtown headquarters.
   ``My father's a teacher, he works overtime constantly and I
don't think he gets paid enough,'' said Mercedes Chavez, 18, whose
father, Rudy, teaches English at Belmont. She had been marching at
the district headquarters for three hours with her 15-month-old
daughter, Dominique.
   Among those carrying a picket sign Tuesday was Garfield High
School calculus teacher Jaime Escalante, whose portrayal in the
film ``Stand And Deliver'' has made him probably the city's
best-known instructor.
   ``I have to support them 100 percent, because I feel that we
deserve better pay and professional pay if we look for quality
education,'' said Escalante.
   ``Without additional teachers it's going to be very, very
difficult'' to finish the final weeks of the semester and grade
students fairly, said Gabriel Cortina, a Los Angeles Unified School
District associate superintendent.
   He made a plea for more substitutes, which the district hopes to
lure with higher than usual pay, $167 instead of $137 a day.
   The higher pay outraged picketing teachers.
   ``It's demeaning to be treated like that,'' said Dale Tropp, a
teacher at an elementary school.
   ``I make about half what the substitutes are making today,''
said Susan Perry, a third-grade teacher.
   On Monday, substitute teacher Randy Kiyabu arrived at Narbonne
High School in a white, chauffeured limousine as a way of outraging
strikers.
   Students at San Fernando High School took up a collection of $95
for one substitute who said he only took the job because he needed
the money. The unidentified teacher left after he was handed the
cash.
   There were no immediate figures Tuesday on attendance by the
district's nearly 540,000 students or on the number of teachers who
crossed picket lines.
   Schools spokeswoman Diana Munatones told reporters, ``We do have
a trend established that a lot of teachers are returning to the
classroom.''
   ``Our estimates are that 73 to 83 percent of the teachers are
out,'' said union spokeswoman Catherine Carey, adding, ``We don't
see any significant attrition.''
   The teachers are demanding a 21 percent pay increase in two
years. They also want relief from unpaid duties such as playground
patrol, and greater control in choosing curricula.
   The district most recently offered a 21.5 percent pay increase
over three years and has promised to set up teachers' councils at
individual schools on curricula.
   Teachers in the district earn from $23,440 in beginning salary
to $43,319 for those with doctorates, 98 extra course units and 19
years' experience.
