<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-89 2005EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-SpendingBill     05-16 0457</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spending Bill,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Raises Pressure for More Veterans' Spending</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration pressured House
Democrats on Tuesday to quickly provide $340 million for veterans'
health programs and warned lawmakers that adding extra spending to
the measure would prompt a presidential veto.
   The money is in a multibillion-dollar domestic spending bill for
this year that continued to be snarled because of differences over
hundreds of millions of dollars it contains for anti-drug programs.
   In a letter to House Appropriations Committee Chairman Jamie
Whitten, D-Miss., Veterans Affairs Secretary Edward J. Derwinski
said that failure to provide the money soon would result in delayed
purchases of medical equipment and a gradual reduction in the
department's work force.
   ``Each day that supplemental funding is not forthcoming, the
level of service provided by the VA's medical system is
diminished,'' he wrote.
   Letters were also directed to Whitten and House leaders by the
Veterans of Foreign Wars, the American Legion and the Paralyzed
Veterans of America, each of which urged quick passage of the
legislation.
   ``To be blunt, veterans are being placed in life-threatening
situations,'' the Veterans of Foreign Wars said.
   Agency officials have previously warned that veterans' hospitals
will begin running out of money in late May.
   The money is for the 1989 fiscal year, which ends Sept. 30. With
Congress' Memorial Day recess coming up, lawmakers are reluctant to
leave town without having provided the veterans' money.
   But the hangup continued to be $822 million for new prisons,
extra law officers and other anti-drug initiatives, which the
administration has argued can wait until next year.
   Rep. Neal Smith, D-Iowa, chairman of the Appropriations justice
subcommittee, has said the money is needed and argued that
Republicans should be forced to demonstrate how resolutely they
support President Bush's efforts against drugs.
   He has proposed paying for much of the spending with parts of
the $650 million the government expects to collect in fines from
the Wall Street firm of Drexel Burnham Lambert.
   In a policy statement it issued Tuesday, the administration said
it believed Smith's financing plan ``is not valid'' because it
would still add to the deficit.
   Leading members of the Appropriations Committee met among
themselves and with the Democratic House leadership for much of the
day, but were unable to work out a solution to the problem.
   ``Everybody keeps working on all kinds of alternatives,'' Smith
said.
   A $4.7 billion version of the bill was pulled off the House
floor last month after objections were raised over its cost.
   The leadership of the Appropriations Committee has reduced the
measure's price tag to about $3.2 billion, excluding the drug
spending, according to one government source who asked to not be
identified.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
