<DOCNO> AP890516-0181 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-89 2005EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-YouthViolence     05-16 0627</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Youth Violence,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Experts Recommend Government Shift Focus to Crime's Effect on Children</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Experts on violence involving children urged a
House panel Tuesday to shift its focus from stiffening penalties
for criminals to minimizing the effect on children of witnessing
violent crime.
   But legislators were not receptive to that message, which came
one day after President Bush unveiled an extensive anti-crime
package.
   The experts told the House Select Committee on Children, Youth
and Families that federal efforts to reduce violence by and against
children should work to dispel myths about crime, especially in
inner-city black communities.
   The government also should restructure the education system to
emphazize values and offer viable employment and recreational
options to youth, the experts testified.
   The experts received little encouragement from federal lawmakers.
   ``Your recommendations are really out of kilter with where
politicians are headed,'' said Rep. George Miller, chairman of the
panel.
   The California Democrat said most of his fellow congressmen are
``getting on the bandwagon heading down the road of stiffer and
stiffer penalties.''
   Dr. Carl C. Bell, a Chicago psychiatrist, warned that many
children who regularly witness extreme violence don't get the
counseling they need to lessen their risk of becoming victims or
perpretrators of crime.
   ``What we need to consider is that a lot of the educational
problems and behavioral disturbances that I see among young black
children ... may very well be due to the fact that they've
witnessed violence and are suffering from post-traumatic stress
disorder similar to what Vietnam Veterans suffered,'' said Bell.
   He warned that myths and misconceptions about homicides in the
black community are being heightened by media focus on sensational
incidents.
   ``Many blacks think it's white policemen who have killed the
majority of blacks,'' he said, but ``black-on-black murder is the
leading cause of death in black males 15 to 44 and the leading
cause of death in black females 15 to 34.''
   But Bell said policymakers cannot be excused for demonstrating
``a selective inattention to black homicide'' because many whites
harbor the fear expressed by one of his colleagues: ``If black
people stop killing black people, they will start killing white
people.''
   Dr. Howard Spivak, deputy health commissioner of Massachusetts,
said the typical homicide occurs when two young men of the same
race who know each other have been drinking or using drugs and get
into an argument that escalates into a fatal act of violence.
   Punitive measures like those being touted nationally would have
no effect, said Spivak.
   But District of Columbia Superior Court Associate Judge Reginald
Walton, who has been nominated to be the No. 3 man in the Office of
National Drug Control Policy, said many young men who end up before
him have no idea ``what the appropriate role of a male or father is
in this society.''
   Walton complained that policy makers have ignored earlier
recommendations for dealing with the effect of crime on children.
   He said no action was taken when a task force for Washington,
D.C., schools on which he served proposed improving school athletic
programs. Consequently, the judge said, he learned that drug
dealers are financing an underground basketball league used to
recruit young people.
   Bell and Spivak also criticized television for presenting
unrealistic heroes, male role models and situations that emphasize
violent solutions to problems.
   ``One young man being treated in an emergency room for a gunshot
wouund told me that he was surprised that the injury hurt; his
perception from television was that such injuries were neither
painful nor incapacitating,'' said Spivak.
   ``We've simply got to stop peddling violence to the children of
this country,'' added Gregory Loken, executive director of Covenant
House, a runaway youth program based in New York City.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
