<SECOND>AM-Bush-Tennis,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Sons Play Pros Evert and Shriver in Tennis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House came to a temporary halt
Tuesday for what President Bush described as a ``dog eat dog''
tennis match featuring pros Chris Evert and Pam Shriver against two
of Bush's sons.
   The two women were supposed to have played against Marvin and
Jeb Bush last year in Florida in a fund-raising game during Bush's
presidential race. However, the game was rained out.
   It was finally rescheduled for Tuesday on the White House courts
but was rained out there, as well. So they moved the game to an
indoor court usually reserved for senators on the fifth floor of
the Hart Senate Office Building.
   Watching from the sidelines were Commerce Secretary Robert
Mosbacher, CIA chief William Webster, Michael J. Boskin, chairman
of the Council of Economic Advisers, a sprinkling of members of
Congress and other guests.
   ``This is just a happy family match, dog eat dog,'' Bush said.
   The press was excluded from most of the match but it was clear
during a brief photo-taking session that the teams were evenly
matched.
   On the return to the White House, reporters shouted to ask who
had won.
   Jeb Bush was about to answer, but Pam Shriver clamped her hand
over his mouth.
   It was learned from reliable sources that the men won, two out
of three sets.
