<FIRST>r i AM-MuhammadAli     05-16 0420</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Muhammad Ali,0435</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Champ Testifies For Doctor Who Helped Him</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY CZUCZKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Muhammad Ali, diagnosed as having Parkinson's
syndrome, testified Tuesday for a Yugoslav-born doctor whose
treatment the former heavyweight boxing champion credits with
improving his life.
   Ali, 47, walked stiffly and could barely be heard giving
testimony at the trial of Dr. Rajko Medenica, a cancer specialist
charged with fraud by Swiss authorities. Medenica practices in
South Carolina.
   Former Gov. John West of South Carolina, who credits Medenica
with successfully treating his daughter-in-law's throat cancer, and
Richard Walker, a former U.S. ambassador to South Korea, also
appeared Tuesday as character witnesses.
   Yolanda, Ali's third wife, often spoke for him during the
10-minute courtroom appearance.
   ``Muhammad had a low image of himself,'' said Mrs. Ali, 32.
``After this treatment he was full of life.''
   ``He improved my physical condition,'' Ali said, and credited
the doctor with stopping the trembling in his hands.
   At a news conference, Ali seemed alert and in good spirits,
joking with reporters despite partly slurred speech and a gaze that
sometimes was distant.
   Asked how he felt, he answered: ``Good. I never felt better.''
   ``I talk when I feel like it,'' he said, adding that his speech
has improved in the past few years. When a reporter reminded him of
being ``The Greatest,'' Ali responded: ``Used to be.''
   Parkinson's syndrome is a treatable form of the incurable,
debilitating Parkinson's disease.
   Mrs. Ali said Medenica, whom they first consulted a year ago,
found evidence of pesticide poisoning and devised a treatment that
includes the drug interferon, as does his cancer therapy, and a
regenerative process known as blood cleaning.
   Ali retired from boxing in 1981 and dedicated himself to
promoting Islam. He lives much of the time on a farm in Geneva.
   The trial, which began April 17, is being held without Medenica.
A U.S. district judge withdrew the doctor's passport on grounds his
American patients depend on his treatment.
   Medenica, 49, is accused of writing $2.6 million in fake bills
while treating patients, including many Yugoslavs, at a Geneva
hospital in 1973-81.
   A Yugoslav court, in the same case, sentenced Medenica to 20
years in prison in 1983 for defrauding the government social
security system.
   He was released from 15 months of Swiss investigative custody in
1984 when West got a Geneva judge to allow bond and helped raise
much of the required $300,000. Medenica set up practice in Hilton
Head, S.C., and became a U.S. citizen.
</TEXT>
