<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-89 2009EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-India-DoctorStrike     05-16 0180</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Doctor Strike,0184</SECOND>
<HEAD>Doctors Strike in 5 Indian Cities</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 5,000 doctors at government
hospitals in New Delhi and four other cities went on strike Tuesday
after salary negotiations failed.
   Talks with a 17-member government team in the capital broke down
late Monday and ``there is a complete deadlock,'' said Dr. Anil
Gurtoo, who represented New Delhi's 3,500 junior doctors in the
negotiations.
   The striking doctors are junior hospital staff members, nearly
all of them residents. Senior doctors have handled emergency cases
since the strike began.
   Strikers want an increase of $53 in monthly pay that now ranges
from $200 to $270. They also seek an increase in the compensation
for not maintaining private practice from $16 to $40 and firm
schedules for promotion.
   Gurtoo told reporters medical care was crippled in New Delhi's
10 government hospitals. He said they treated only about 10,000
patients during the day, fewer than half the usual number.
   Strikes also were called by about 1,500 doctors at government
hospitals in Chandigarh, Pondicherry, Banaras and Aligarh, Gurtoo
said.
</TEXT>
