<FIRST>r i AM-Irish-Bomb 1stLd-Writethru a0614 05-16 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Irish-Bomb, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0614,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Six Hurt By Belfast Bomb</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout, UPDATING with new details of attack, Protestant
group claims responsibility for shooting death, rocket attack. No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb attached to a telephone
pole exploded Tuesday as a joint army and police patrol was
passing, injuring six people, including a soldier and a police
officer, the city police said.
   None of the injured was hurt seriously, according to first
reports. Police blamed the bomb on the outlawed Irish Republican
Army.
   Police also said they arrested two men in the Protestant Crumlin
Road during a search that uncovered 500 rounds of ammunition and a
submachine gun.
   The police were believed to be searching for the Soviet-made
RPG-7 rocket launcher used Monday in a rocket and gunfire attack on
a Sinn Fein office center in the Ardoyne district.
   Four people in the office during the attack escaped injury,
though the office was hit by a rocket and several bullets, police
said.
   Sinn Fein is the legal political arm of the IRA, which is
fighting to end British rule in the mainly Protestant province and
unite it with the overwhelmingly Catholic Irish Republic in the
south.
   The Ulster Volunteer Force, an outlawed Protestant paramilitary
group, claimed responsibility Tuesday night for the shooting death
of a Roman Catholic workman and the attack on the Sinn Fein office.
   It contended in messages to Belfast media that the slain
building worker was an IRA member and that the office was an IRA
meeting place.
   The workman was unloading a car at a job site in a Protestant
neighborhood Monday when shot by a man who fired about a dozen
rounds from a stolen van.
   It was the 25th death attributed to Protestant-Catholic violence
in Northern Ireland this year.
</TEXT>
