<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-89 2013EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-FireArtists     05-16 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fire Artists,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>Expo Puts Spotlight on Efforts to Rebuild After Devastating Blaze</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The eclectic colors and textures of this year's
annual art exposition mask a story of resolve by many artists and
dealers who were nearly wiped out by a devastating fire last month.
   Many raced to assemble displays for the 10th annual Chicago
International Art Exposition, one of the world's premier art fairs,
amid ``a new spirit to rebuild, to get on with our work,'' said
painter Steven Heyman. He was one of the lucky ones who did not
lose everything in the April 15 blaze.
   Brick rubble is all that remains of the six-story block-sized
building that housed nine galleries in the heart of the city's
River North art district. Most of Heyman's paintings were in his
studio; only five were in a gallery ravaged by the fire that
destroyed an estimated $10 million worth of artwork.
   Others who weren't as fortunate talked Tuesday about their
struggle to recoup.
   ``We lost over 9,000 pieces of art,'' said gallery owner William
van Straaten, whose establishment was destroyed with ``all our
historical records ... all our research data, customer account
files dating back 20 years.''
   In the weeks since the blaze, the cause of which remains
undetermined, van Straaten and three other dealers who lost
galleries in the fire managed to put together exhibits for the
exposition, which opened May 11 and closed Tuesday.
   The fair, this year involving displays by more 200 galleries
from 20 countries, is a showplace for contemporary art that
attracts dealers, collectors and art lovers from around the world.
   ``We had a few things that were framed before the fair ... a few
things suppliers air-freighted to us on an emergency basis,'' van
Straaten said. ``But (the exhibit) is just not what it was'' in
previous years.
   Still, such efforts did not go unnoticed.
   ``I think it's extraordinary how dealers involved were able to
jump back ... they have all my admiration,'' said Margaret Failoni,
owner of Galleria Il Ponte in Rome.
   Ms. Failoni, who had a booth at the expo, said word of the blaze
traveled quickly in the tightly knit world art community.
   ``This is just not your local store down the street ... it's a
tragedy'' felt by artists and dealers worldwide, she said.
   ``If anything good has come of this I think it's the incredible
solidarity among dealers and everybody'' touched by the loss, she
said. ``Obviously we're all trying to help in any way we can.''
   ``It's a very resilient community here in Chicago that we
have,'' said Heyman, 36, who had several works displayed at the
fair and is already working on paintings for another show.
   ``People are looking forward,'' he said. ``It's a devastating
blow but it's not a fatal blow.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
