<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon-Kidnap 1stLd-Writethru   05-16 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-Kidnap, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0723,0453</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Say 3 West Germans Kidnapped, 1 Freed</HEAD>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0790 to fix writethru designation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf, `Reporters were ...' with three grafs to UPDATE
with Ms. Schnitzler returned to camp. Pickup 9th pvs, `Police said ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Lebanon, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SIDON, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three West German relief workers were
abducted Tuesday, and one was freed later by militiamen who
intercepted the kidnap car in the belief it contained escaping
thieves, police reported.
   A spokesman for the Islamic Grouping militia said Petra
Schnitzler, 26, was freed after two militia members heard her
banging on the inside of the trunk.
   She had been kidnapped along with Heinrich Struebig, 48, and a
colleague tentatively identified as Thomas when gunmen stopped
them, police said. It was the third time Ms. Schnitzler and
Struebig had been reported abducted since last year and the second
in 12 days.
   All three work for the private West German relief group
ASME-Humanitas.
   A police spokesman said the white Mercedes carrying Ms.
Schnitzler in the trunk was intercepted after it sped into an alley
on the northern edge of Sidon.
   ``The two gunmen shot in the air to stop the white Mercedes,''
the police spokesman said of the accidental rescue. ``The driver of
the Mercedes and another passenger abandoned their car and ran
away.''
   Ali Sheik Ammar, head of the Islamic Grouping in Sidon and south
Lebanon, said Ms. Schnitzler was in good condition. His group is
one of the rare Sunni Moslem factions allied with Iran, which is
predominantly Shiite.
   After she was freed, she was taken to the Palestinian refugee
camp at Mieh Mieh.
   Reporters were allowed to see her later but she shouted. ``Go
away! I don't want to see anyone! I'm tired!''
   There was no word on the whereabouts of the other two relief
workers.
   Police said they still were not sure exactly what had happened.
   ``God knows what's going on between the crazy militias and the
crazier Germans,'' the spokesman said. ``We're completely baffled.''
   He said eight gunmen in three Mercedes cars intercepted the
relief workers at 7:30 p.m. on their way from the Mieh Mieh refugee
camp to their base at Aaqbiyeh. The spokesmen said the relief
workers were in two cars.
   On May 4, police reported that Struebig, Ms. Schnitzler and
colleague Markus Quint, 21, were abducted by five gunmen on Sidon's
southern edge. Struebig and Ms. Schnitzler, who also disappeared
overnight last year, were freed 10 hours later and Quint was
released in 10 days.
   Besides the two West Germans, 15 foreigners are missing in
Lebanon. Most are believed held by Shiite abductors loyal to Iran.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890516-0191 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-89 2040EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Panama 1stLd-Writethru a0706 05-16 0801</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0706,0826</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Prepares for Strike</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 14 grafs to UPDATE with American evacuees leaving,
Bush phoning Endara. Pickup 6th pvs, `Influential legislator...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Air Force plane evacuated the
first group of U.S. military dependents Tuesday on the eve of a
general strike that the Panamanian government has called illegal.
   The opposition vowed to go ahead with the one-day strike, which
coincides with the opening Wednesday in Washington of a conference
of the Organization of American States on Panama's nullified
election.
   President Bush telephoned Guillermo Endara, the opposition's
presidential candidate in the May 7 election who was severely
beaten a week ago by street gangs from the pro-government ``Dignity
Battalions.''
   Endara was released from a hospital Tuesday. An aide said Bush
spoke with Endara for about seven minutes and told him U.S. actions
were aimed at Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, commander of the
nation's Defense Forces, and not the Panamanian people.
   White House spokesman Roman Popadiuk said in Washington that
Bush called Endara ``to express sympathy over the assault which Mr.
Endara and his fellow leaders of the democratic forces in Panama
suffered at the hands of the Noriega regime.''
   ``The president noted the wave of outrage which has swept the
hemisphere in the wake of Noriega's effort to steal the election by
force and fraud.''
   At the U.S. Howard Air Force Base, 238 Americans boarded a
chartered Air Force plane _ the first of hundreds of dependents to
be evacuated in the next few weeks.
   Air Force Maj. Joan Ferguson said the group had 164 military
dependents, 71 active-duty personnel and three dependents of an
armed forces civilian employee.
   She said some of the active-duty personnel had fewer than three
months left on their tours in Panama and were vacating base housing
to make room for those who had been living off the base. She said
others were going on home leave and were taking advantage of the
special flight.
   While some Americans were being evacuated, the Bush
administration was sending 1,900 military personnel into Panama to
reinforce the more than 10,000 troopers stationed here.
   The Noriega-controlled government said Wednesday's strike is
motivated by political goals, not economic issues, and is an
attempt to stain Panama's image at the OAS meeting.
   Both the government and opposition say they will have
representatives at the conference.
   Benjamin Colamarco, the head of the ``Dignity Battalions,'' said
the paramilitary groups had no plans for the general strike and
were poised only to repel a U.S. invasion. Members of the groups
have frequently attacked opposition rallies.
   Endara, after leaving the hospital, said Wednesday would be ``a
very important day'' and threats would not stop the opposition.
   Influential legislator Rigoberto Paredes said on state-owned
Radio Nacional the strike is ``intended to create disorder in the
streets to a degree that the United States can use it to justify
direct physical intervention in Panama.''
   He said Noriega's departure from power is not negotiable.
   The opposition has said any solution to the Panamanian crisis
must involve talks with the military leading to Noriega's dismissal
or resignation.
   The troop presence on the streets has been low since May 11,
with the government frequently broadcasting declarations that the
nation is calm.
   The opposition wants the OAS to impose sanctions that would
amount to a political and diplomatic quarantine of Panama if the
government refuses to respect the results of the May 7 presidential
elections.
   Opposition leaders says they won by a 3-1 margin. The government
contends its candidates were ahead 2-1 when it stopped the vote
count and nullified the elections.
   Washington is urging Latin American nations to remove their
ambassadors from Panama.
   U.S. Ambassador Arthur Davis, recalled for consultations by
Bush, left for Washington Monday. Mexico and Venezuela also have
recalled their envoys.
   Endara, smiling but with a bandaged head, walked from the
hospital and was cheered by a small group of hospital workers and
other supporters.
   He repeated the opposition contention that their candidates won
and that nothing short of being sworn into office will satisfy them.
   Endara rejected the idea of a junta ruling after acting
President Manuel Solis Palma's term runs out Sept. 1.
   ``The Panamanian people expressed their will on May 7. We
consider it the will of God and will not compromise,'' he said.
   A communique from the Labor Ministry published in newspapers
Tuesday said, ``Businesses may not close their doors and their
first obligation is to give work to all of their workers.''
   It urged businesses to open and employees to report for work,
but did not say what would happen if they did not.
   The opposition is urging Panamanians to stay in their houses
Wednesday except for ``protests at noon by any imaginable means.''
</TEXT>
