<FIRST>u i AM-Panama-Americans 1stLd-Writethru a0677 05-16 0717</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama-Americans, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0677,0742</SECOND>
<HEAD>Family Says it Doesn't Fear Panama City</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS graf after 3rd, `The Kirbergs...' to UPDATE with first
group leaving. Pickup 4th pvs, `The Kirbergs...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT CLAYTON, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five days after U.S. military
dependents were ordered out of their homes and onto U.S. bases, the
Kirberg family has accepted the situation without entirely
understanding the need.
   ``I still don't have any fear about going into Panama City,''
said Judy Boyle, who moved in with Leo and Pat LeBlanc with her
husband, Emil Kirberg, and their son, Blake.
   The Kirbergs said they were safer inside Fort Clayton, but they
have no plans to make an early departure from Panama, as others
started doing Tuesday.
   The first group of Americans to be evacuated boarded an Air
Force chartered plane at the Howard Air Force Base for a flight
back to the United States. Air Force Maj. Joan Ferguson said that
in the group were 164 dependents of military personnel, 71
active-duty personnel and three dependents of an armed forces
civilian employee. She said the active-duty troopers were departing
because their scheduled tours in Panama were nearing an end or they
were going on home leave.
   The Kirbergs were living in Panama City when President Bush
ordered U.S. dependents into military bases following the beating
of opposition presidential candidates in the streets of Panama.
   They packed up a few suitcases and descended on the LeBlancs.
Leo LeBlanc is Kirberg's boss and designated sponsor.
   Now, five days later, the Kirbergs are resigned to living with
the LeBlancs. Under evacuation rules, they said, they have until
July 1 to find onbase housing or Blake and his mother will have to
leave.
   Kirberg's two-year tour as an Army contract employee ends in
July anyway.
   They are planning a trip to their 10th-floor apartment
overlooking the city and the bay to bring back ``anything that
could be stolen.'' That includes three TV sets and a VCR. They'll
also check on the dog, Sissy, boarding with a foster family.
   For them, it's the little things that are the biggest problems.
   Four-year-old Blake misses his dog, but has found a new playmate
in the LeBlancs' 9-week-old toy poodle, Prince.
   Emil Kirberg misses Sissy too. The 20-pound mutt used to pull
guard duty in Blake's bedroom, and now Blake insists on sleeping in
the Kirbergs' bed.
   ``He's like an octopus. He's got eight arms and he swims,'' said
Kirberg.
   Blake will be out of school as of Friday; the base is cutting
short the school year so those who want to leave soon can receive
credit and-or graduate.
   The LeBlancs, with two daughters in college in Texas, originally
took in a second family too, but that crowded the house.
   ``They're the kind that only need five hours of sleep while the
rest of us need eight,'' said Boyle, ``so they were lying in bed at
5 a.m. afraid they'd wake us up if they moved around.''
   That family moved out Sunday, returning to their house in Panama
City.
   ``His mother-in-law really wanted to go home and they didn't see
any security problem,'' said Kirberg. ``She was 78 and it was all
too much for her.''
   Indeed, the reasons for the evacuation escape even some
hard-bitten veterans.
   One retired master sergeant who still works at Fort Clayton said
he got together with some of his on-duty comrades Monday night to
``complain about the management.''
   ``This is not being handled well,'' he grumbled. ``There just
isn't any crisis.''
   Other drawbacks, ``aside from not sleeping in your own bed,'' as
Boyle said, are minor.
   Leo LeBlanc doesn't like Blake fooling with his stereo hookup.
There's only one shower. The LeBlancs won't accept money for food,
so the Kirbergs try to figure out the menu and buy for it.
   There are also some positive features. The LeBlanc house is only
two minutes from the Kirbergs' offices, instead of half an hour.
   And Pat LeBlanc is a great cook, which the Kirbergs admit has
not been a strong point for either of them.
   ``I want to stay forever,'' said Blake.
   ``Fine, we'll draw up the adoption papers,'' said Leo LeBlanc.
   But Pat LeBlanc shook her head.
   ``I haven't forgotten what it's like to have little kids,'' she
said.
</TEXT>
