<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-TVChief     05-16 0179</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-TV Chief,0184</SECOND>
<HEAD>Television Chief Changed After Controversy Over Burying Lenin</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Presidium retired the government television
chief Tuesday, three weeks after he apologized for the suggestion
on a live broadcast that Vladimir Lenin should be removed from
public view and buried.
   Alexander Aksyonov, head of the state committee for television
and radio, called Gostelradio, apologized at a Communist Party
plenum in April after the remark by Mark Zakharov, director of
Moscow's Leninsky Komsomol Theater.
   Zakharov said Lenin's body should be removed from its glass case
in a mausoleum on Red Square.
   Lenin, the founder of the Soviet Union, is treated with
religious reverence.
   The official news agency Tass said Tuesday that Aksyonov was
relieved of his duties in connection with his retirement and
replaced by Mikhail Nenashev, head of the state book publishing
committee.
   Kremlin ideology chief Vadim Medvedev visited Gostelradio last
week and raised staff salaries. Journalists reportedly were pleased
with Medvedev's comments on their work, and the host of
``Vzglyad,'' where the controversial suggestion was made, continues
to appear on the air.
