<FIRST>r i AM-Angola 1stLd-Writethru   05-16 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Angola, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0658,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>African Leaders Endorse Angolan Peace Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with summit over, leaders signing
peace plan. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leaders of eight African nations on
Tuesday signed an Angolan government peace plan aimed at ending the
country's 14-year civil war, the news agency Lusa reported.
   After a one-day summit in Luanda, Angola's capital, the leaders
supported the peace plan by President Jose Eduardo dos Santos, the
Portuguese agency said.
   Dos Santos did not disclose details of the plan other than to
say it includes a ``peace zone'' along the Benguela railroad, Lusa
reported.
   The railroad running through central Angola is an important
route to the Atlantic Ocean for landlocked Zaire, Zambia and
Zimbabwe, but rebel attacks have paralyzed much of the track.
   Dos Santos was joined in support for his plan by the presidents
of Congo, Gabon, Mozambique, Sao Tome e Principe, Zaire, Zambia and
Zimbabwe.
   ``It's not about obtaining peace at any price,'' the Angolan
news agency ANGOP quoted dos Santos as saying earlier Tuesday,
``but to consider the means, and to create the conditions for
launching a just and lasting peace.''
   ANGOP said most of the African leaders support an ``African
solution'' proposed by the Angolan government that would allow
rebels to integrate into society through a government amnesty.
   Dos Santos has refused to negotiate with Jonas Savimbi's rebel
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola and says any
solution must accept one-party rule by his Popular Movement for the
Liberation of Angola, a Marxist party.
   The rebels have rejected the amnesty and demand negotiations
leading to power-sharing in the former Portuguese colony.
   Savimbi was excluded from U.S.-sponsored peace talks that led to
a December agreement by which South Africa pledged to halt aid to
the rebels and grant independence to Angola's southern neighbor,
Namibia.
   In exchange, 50,000 Cuban troops backing the Angolan government
in the war have begun leaving Angola.
   The Luanda summit follows a series of meetings between dos
Santos and other African leaders since last October, when the
Angolan president committed himself to look for a solution
``inspired by the experience of other African countries that have
lived through similar situations.''
   Earlier Tuesday, African leaders criticized U.S. support for the
right-wing Angolan rebels, who have waged a bush war since 1974.
   Dos Santos attacked what he called the United States' ``publicly
declared intention to continue to destabilize Angola,'' the ANGOP
news agency said in a report monitored in Lisbon.
   Zambian President Kenneth Kaunda praised the Reagan and Bush
administrations for mediating in the Angolan dispute, but said the
U.S. supply of arms to the rebels contradicted this and was
``killing the Angolan people.''

</TEXT>
</DOC>
