<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Hall     05-16 0284</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Hall,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>AIDS-Infected Prostitute Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crystal Hall, who kept working as a
prostitute after learning she had AIDS until jail persuaded her to
straighten out her life, has died, Rhode Island Hospital announced
Tuesday.
   Hall, 25, died Monday evening after a 19-day stay, hospital
spokesman Rick Piester said Tuesday. He declined to give the cause
of death.
   Hall, a drug addict with a record of 34 prostitution arrests,
made headlines when District Court Judge Albert E. DeRobbio
threatened to charge her with attempted murder if she continued to
work the streets.
   DeRobbio later sentenced Hall to 13 months in jail. He said that
for her customers, having sex amounted to a death sentence.
   Behind bars, Hall got off heroin, came close to earning a high
school diploma and responded well to treatment for acquired immune
deficiency syndrome. She began talking about trying to steer
youngsters away from drugs and crime after her release.
   In February, DeRobbio and public defender Lauren Wilkins agreed
on a plan for Hall to spread her reform message. On her release,
she began working for Channel One, a Warwick drug program that
planned a documentary on her life.
   Hall was charged with violating the terms of her probation after
she was arrested behind the wheel of a stolen car.
   The charge was dropped shortly before she entered the hospital
for the last time, said state Corrections Department spokesman
Joseph A. DiNitto.
   AIDS, or human immunodeficiency virus, damages the body's immune
system, leaving it susceptible to infections and cancer. AIDS is
spread most often through sexual contact, needles or syringes
shared by drug abusers, infected blood or blood products, and from
pregnant women to their offspring.
</TEXT>
