<FIRST>r i AM-Australia-TinyBaby     05-16 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Australia-Tiny Baby,0199</SECOND>
<HEAD>10-Inch Baby Doing Well</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SYD1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 10-inch baby believed to among the
smallest ever born was making good progress Wednesday, a hospital
spokesperson said.
   Two-week-old Nicole Shiralee Faunce, who weighs only 14.7
ounces, was delivered 11 weeks prematurely by Caesarean section
after she stopped growing in the womb.
   Nicole is being kept alive in a ventilator and has put on 1.4
ounces since being born.
   ``She is making good progress,'' said Royal North Shore Hospital
spokeswoman Samantha Jones.
   Dr. Garth Leslie was optimistic Nicole would survive.
   ``She is a fighter and has a better than 50 percent chance of
living,'' he said.
   Nicole's parents, Ray and Jenny Faunce, live 90 minutes by car
north of Sydney but visit the child every other day.
   ``We'd like to come down ever day but just can't afford it,''
said Ray Faunce, who works as a firefighter.
   According to the Guinness Book of Records, the lowest birth rate
recorded for a surviving baby was 10 ounces. It says Marian Chapman
was 12.4 inches long when born prematurely at South Shields,
England, in 1938. She died in 1983.
</TEXT>
