<HEAD>Marcos Back In Intensive Care, Lapses Into Critical Condition</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE with Marcos downgraded to critical
condition, quotes, details; picks up 5th graf: `Marcos and his ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Philippine President Ferdinand Marcos,
suffering from recurrent pneumonia, lapsed into critical condition
Tuesday, a hospital official said.
   ``It's an episodic thing, he has pneumoia and his condition has
been downgraded,'' said Eugene Tiwanak, assistant administrator of
St. Francis Hospital. ``It's impossible to say more than that.''
   Marcos was returned to the intensive care unit Monday after a
month in the telemetry unit, according to a hospital statement.
   A nursing supervisor refused to elaborate on the statement,
which said Marcos was relying on a respirator to help him breathe.
   The 71-year-old Marcos has been hospitalized since January for
treatment of heart and respiratory ailments.
   On April 12, Marcos was transferred from the intensive care unit
to one that cares for heart patients. Doctors said then that he was
``chronically ill'' and unlikely to recover.
   Marcos aides said last week that the ousted leader appeared to
be improving and had requested that a reclining chair be brought to
his hospital room from his Makiki Heights home.
   Hospital officials on Tuesday refused to detail the downturn in
Marcos' health, but Marcos spokesman Gemmo Trinidad said Marcos
suffered a sudden drop in blood pressure.
   ``I really don't know much more than that,'' he said. ``His
blood pressure dropped and they thought he should be back in ICU.''
   Marcos and his wife, Imelda, are under U.S. indictment on
charges they plundered the Philippine government of more than $100
million and stashed much of the money in the United States in the
form of art and real estate.
   A judge ruled Marcos will not have to stand trial unless he
recovers.
   The Marcoses have lived here in exile since February 1986, when
they were ousted in a popular revolt that lifted Corazon Aquino to
power.
</TEXT>
