<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Angels     05-16 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Angels,0392</SECOND>
<HEAD>London-Trained Guardian Angels Begin Work</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British-trained Guardian Angels began their first
subway anticrime patrols Tuesday and immediately ran into trouble;
so many reporters and photographers followed them around that
underground traffic jams developed. London transport police
intervened, telling the mob of journalists pursuing the Angels
through subway cars to split up to stop the overcrowding.
   ``We had received a number of complaints, not about the Guardian
Angels but about the pressmen accompanying them who were causing an
obstruction,'' said a transport police spokesman, who refused to be
identified.
   ``They were asked to leave and split into smaller groups.''
   Thirty Angels completed three months of training Sunday and 11
began work Tuesday, led by American Curtis Sliwa, who founded the
group in New York and helped spread chapters throughout the United
States.
   ``Be courteous, vigilant and alert,'' Sliwa told his recruits,
who have been criticized by police as ``vigilantes.''
   ``The police have been negative. The public will ask many
questions. Let them know you are the newly qualified London
Guardian Angels.
   ``So far they have been used to Brooklyn and Bronx accents,''
Sliwa said, referring to initial patrols made by Sliwa and other
New York-based Angels.
   Most subway passengers paid no attention to the Angels in their
signature red berets and T-shirts, but one woman walked up to shake
Sliwa's hand.
   ``I am delighted to see you,'' said Marrion Caullen, 64. ``Your
presence is very reassuring to pensioners (senior citizens) like
myself.''
   Meanwhile, the Police Federation chairman, Alan Eastwood, told
his group's annual conference in Blackpool that groups like the
Angels tended to work according to their own laws.
   ``If you dress people in T-shirts and berets, and invest them
with spurious powers, they start to run the neighborhood the way
they want it but not necessarily the way the law says it should be
done,'' Eastwood said.
   He said police were studying bringing back a World War II-era
association of retired police officers called ``Dad's Army,'' which
fought street crime. It was disbanded in the late 1950s.
   ``We are looking at it as a possible means of resisting the
growth of uncontrolled and unaccountable private security while at
the same time giving chief officers greater flexibility in dealing
with manpower problems,'' he said.
</TEXT>
