<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-89 0826EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i PM-CampaigninginPoland Adv22   05-16 0937</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Campaigning in Poland, Adv 22,0964</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv22</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon PMs, May 22, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>A Day on Poland's Election-Campaign Trail</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Poland's election campaign is under way with
opposition candidates in the running. An Associated Press
correspondent went out into the countryside recently to watch Poles
experiencing something new in their lives. This is his report.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SUWALKI, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the lazy afternoon sun the people of
this vacation area close by the Soviet border gathered around a
park bandshell where a union troubadour strummed a guitar.
   Men in white golfing hats emblazoned with the red Solidarity
logo handed out paper flags to children, while at folding tables
volunteers sold campaign ``bricks,'' coupons printed to look like
bricks to build a campaign fund.
   In a scene similar to the Fourth of July in small-town America,
Solidarity was going to the people in Poland's experiment with a
new political style _ democracy.
   Historian Bronislaw Geremek and filmmaker Andrzej Wajda were
kicking off their campaigns for the National Assembly in Warsaw on
the ticket of the Solidarity Citizens Committee.
   A deal between the Solidarity-led opposition and communist
authorities lets the opposition seek 161 seats in the existing
460-seat Sejm and creates a 100-member Senate, the East bloc's
first fully democratic legislative chamber.
   Solidarity has 261 candidates campaigning in all of the
country's 49 provinces.
   Their bustling election offices are provided by authorities and
staffed by volunteers, while leaflets, placards and flags are paid
for from small campaign donations collected at tables set up by the
local citizens committees. Officials say the money comes in too
quickly to count.
   Some communist candidates also have been out meeting voters, but
in general they've been slower to take up the Western-style
campaigning.
   Despite occasional murmurs about carpetbaggers from Warsaw _
Wajda last lived in Suwalki when he was 7 years old and Geremek
never lived here _ this town of 59,000 people was puffed up to have
two such renowned candidates and gave them a warm reception. Even
the communist mayor received them.
   Wajda is Poland's best-known filmmaker. Geremek, one of Lech
Walesa's closest advisers, is an architect of the ``round-table''
talks that ended April 5, making Solidarity legal again and opening
the way to the June 4 vote.
   Joining them were the local members of the Solidarity slate:
Jerzy Pietkiewicz, a 41-year-old teacher from nearby Elk and
Stanislaw Bernatowicz, an elderly scientist active in protecting
the region's lakes and forests.
   Wajda and Bernatowicz, running for Senate, and Geremek and
Pietkiewicz, for the Sejm, sounded similar themes at the park rally
with about 1,000 townspeople: Poland needs independence, the system
has failed and voters should use the elections to end the power
monopoly held by the Communist Party, officially the Polish United
Workers Party.
   At first slow and nervous, the intense Pietkiewicz soon was
being interrupted by cheers.
   ``Do we really live in a Polish state,'' he asked, ``if those
who have ruled have had to go to Red Square for instructions?''
   He said Poland was victimized by a Marxist-Leninist philosophy
that wrongly thought it could create ``paradise of earth'' through
``materialistic values'' that ignored religion and truth.
   Said Geremek: ``It cannot be any longer as it is now. ...
Everyday suffering, lines, lack of money or lack of goods, hard
life for women, lack of hope and lack of prospects for youth. ...
It has to be changed.''
   Candidates stressed the elections are a step to totally free
voting in four years. Authorities promised as much at the round
table, but the opposition is skeptical. Making Solidarity a
parliament force is seen as a way to hold the communists to their
word. Or as one pamphlet put it: ``Each vote for our candidates is
a step toward freedom.''
   Earlier, Geremek visited a hospital and Wajda a technical school
where bulletin boards were covered with posters showing scenes from
his films.
   He shared early memories of Suwalki with about 500 students of
voting age (18) and discussed his plans for a documentary about the
World War II massacre of Polish officers, including his father, at
Katyn in the Soviet Union. The government has been edging toward
acknowledging Soviet guilt for the massacre.
   In a province where a committee actively seeks the fate of some
200 residents rounded up by the Soviet secret police in 1945 and
believed executed, the allusion to Katyn was vivid.
   ``I'd vote for him,'' 19-year-old Bartosz Iwanowski said.
   ``Support for Wajda and Geremek is quite big. When people see
these names they immediately just sign underneath. ... Even party
members sign our list for Wajda,'' said Grzegorz Wilczynski,
helping to manage the Solidarity Citizens Committee office, three
small rooms in city hall.
   ``The church's support has been a big help,'' he added. ``It's
not done so openly, ... just on the part of individual priests. But
the people know.''
   He said people are elated to have a chance to make a real choice.
   ``If it turns out that we lose, I suspect many people will just
go into exile. ... We're laying out all our cards in this game.''
   But for one woman in the park, on a monthly pension of 23,000
zlotys _ $33 at the official rate _ the time for optimism has
passed.
   ``I don't support either the party or Solidarity. How can I make
a choice having only 23,000?'' she said bitterly as people gave
1,000-zloty donations a few steps away. ``Hope is the mother of
fools. I have no more.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Mon PMs May 22</NOTE>
