<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-89 0941EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e PM-APArts:Crumb Adv22   05-16 0639</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP Arts: Crumb, Adv 22,0655</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv22</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon PMs, May 22, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Ann Crumb Discovers ``Aspects'' of Success</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT WOLF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After appearing in the ill-fated Broadway run of
``Chess,'' Ann Crumb is on much firmer ground for her leading role
in Andrew Lloyd Webber's new megasmash, ``Aspects of Love.''
   The eagerly awaited musical opened April 17 at the Prince of
Wales Theater to an advance sale of $8.5 million, and is sold out
through 1989. Based on a little-known novel by English writer David
Garnett, ``Aspects of Love'' spans 17 years and much of Europe.
   It casts Crumb as Rose Vibert, a volatile French actress
enmeshed in romantic liaisons involving her husband, an expatriate
painter named George (Kevin Colson); his nephew, Alex (Michael
Ball); and George's Italian mistress, Giulietta (Kathleen Rowe
McAllen).
   It's the biggest exposure yet for the dark-haired, petite
actress, who keeps her age secret but looks 30ish. A chorus
performer in ``Chess'' and an alumna of ``Les Miserables'' both on
Broadway and on the road, Crumb finds herself tackling what she
calls ``the rangiest piece ever written in the musical theater.''
   The singing stretches her voice higher than ``Chess,'' and her
performance has won critical approval, with Jack Tinker in The
Daily Mail calling her work ``vibrantly intelligent and
commanding.''
   Crumb described the tempestuous Rose as ``a woman who lives on
the edge all the time.''
   ``She's the one who screams and cries and all that,'' Crumb
said. ``You can't say, `Isn't she pathetic?' or `She's so sweet.'
That's the challenge of carrying it.''
   Crumb's performing savvy comes naturally. Her father, George, is
the noted contemporary composer. Her mother, Elizabeth, teaches
music. Crumb intended to be a violinist, but had to give up when an
accident put her arm in plaster for two years. Singing seemed like
the next best bet, but she found herself daunted by her
surroundings.
   ``The irony was I was embarrassed to sing in a house where I'd
only heard some of the finest classical singers,'' she said. ``I
never opened my mouth in the house.''
   During college and graduate school at the University of Michigan
at Ann Arbor, Crumb performed on the side, while preparing for a
career in clinical medicine. It was only later, while working as a
clinician in her hometown of Philadelphia, that she took a job in
the national tour of ``El Grande de Coca Cola.''
   She was hooked.
   Crumb went into medicine because she wanted to help people. Now,
she says in an interview over lunch, she's finding that the theater
is also a way of giving something to people.
   Crumb is contracted to ``Aspects'' for six months as part of an
exchange agreement between New York and London branches of the
actors' union, Equity. She said she was the trade-off for Sarah
Brightman, Lloyd Webber's wife, who appeared in the Broadway
production of ``The Phantom of the Opera'' last year.
   She finds acting a fraught profession. ``There's really so
little work and so many terrific people.''
   However, she's pleased with the quantity of London theater,
which she said surpasses New York, and hopes to have a head start
when ``Aspects'' makes the inevitable move to Broadway.
   Still, despite sharing an apartment in London's posh Hampstead
district with her boyfriend, an American screenwriter, Crumb said
occasional pangs for New York do creep in.
   ``At first, I thought it was going to be hard to go back because
the quality of life here for the average person is much gentler and
kinder.
   ``But I must say in the last few weeks, I've gotten a little
homesick,'' she said. ``The other night after the show, we were
trying to find a place to eat, and there was no place to go.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PM Mon May 22</NOTE>
