<DOCNO> AP890516-0211 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-89 1210EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e PM-APonTV-Everybody'sBaby Adv17   05-16 0842</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP on TV-Everybody's Baby, Adv 17,0853</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wed PMs, May 17, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>You Saw the Real Event: Now See the Movie</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Did anybody who wasn't down a well miss the
mass-publicized rescue of little Jessica McClure, the Texas toddler?
   For those who missed it or just want to relive it, ABC offers a
dramatized replay Sunday in ``Everybody's Baby: The Rescue of
Jessica McClure.''
   Roxana Zal, who won an Emmy Award two years ago for ``Something
About Amelia,'' plays Cissy McClure, the young mother who realizes
that her 18-month-old baby has disappeared into an 8-inch opening
in the ground. Will Oldham plays her husband, Chip. Veteran film
actor Pat Hingle is no-nonsense, good-ol'-boy Fire Chief James
Roberts. Beau Bridges plays Richard Czech, the overly optimistic
chief of police. Patty Duke plays Carolyn Henry, a victim's
assistance volunteer who stayed with the McClures through the
ordeal.
   The movie is a well-acted, well-directed, straightforward
retelling of the drama. In fact, during the first hour, we may
wonder why we must engage in this seemingly pointless re-creation
exercise.
   But the rescue of the tot who, in October 1987, fell down an
abandoned water well in her aunt's Midland, Texas, backyard,
catches hold in the second hour, when the drama escalates and the
filmmakers' purpose begins to emerge. As we begin to suspect, and
are assured in a tag-line message at the conclusion, the movie is a
tribute to volunteerism.
   Scriptwriter David Eyre Jr. and director Mel Damski capture
moments of humor, as well as the horror of the situation, and such
subleties as Cissy's fear of informing her house-painter husband
that she lost the baby down a well. Eyre's dialogue is pretty
credible West Texas-ese. Pet peeve: Zal tells Duke at one point,
``ya'll don't look old enough'' to have a grown daughter. ``Ya'll''
ain't singular. It means ``you all,'' as in two or more of you.
   Except for a few scene-setters filmed in Midland, the movie was
shot in Bellflower, Calif. The set designers did such a good job
re-creating the scene, it might be hard to tell, if they were shown
side by side, which is the real footage of the rescue and which is
the movie. Viewers of the movie get to go where they did not during
the news coverage _ down the shaft rescuers dug through solid rock
alongside the well.
   There was some bickering in Midland last year over who should
get the rights to the story. Eventually those involved settled on
Interscope Productions in association with the Campbell Soup Co.
The real-life folks in Midland-Odessa who are depicted in the film
ought to be pretty happy with the results, since they're portrayed
as good-hearted, right-thinking people ready to do absolutely
anything to save someone else's baby.
   The Chamber of Commerce might not be overly delighted with the
opening establishing shots of rusting oil-field equipment, but the
scenes effectively depict the state of the oil economy at the time
_ down a dry hole itself. That underlines the generosity of the oil
industry that brought in experts and equipment to help save
Jessica, at no small cost.
   The rescue was the biggest media event of the year. But, as
usual, the news media are a faceless mass of shouting imbeciles
blinding decent folk with flashbulbs and TV lights _ as they no
doubt appeared to the McClures at the time. There is one exception.
KMID-TV reporter Rodney Wunsch, who plays himself, stays on the
story so long without sleep, he gets into a hysterical shouting
match with one of the police officers and has to be sent home for
awhile.
   Most touching is the portrayal of emergency medical technician
Robert O'Donnell (Whip Hubley), who must confront his fear of the
gravelike shaft, then can't quite reach the child on the first try
and has to come up empty-handed. A doctor on the scene warns him
before his second attempt that the child's time is running out and
if he has to break her bones to get her out, he should.
   At the conclusion, when Cissy is sitting in the waiting
ambulance and hears the cheers go up from the crowd in the
backyard, it's almost like watching the real scenes that the
networks interrupted prime-time for in 1987. It's not a bad moment
to re-create.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   YOU'RE IN TROUBLE NOW _ ABC has ratted on 3 million women it
says watch soap operas at work. The network's motive was not
tattle-tale, but rather to make the point that the Nielsen ratings
don't necessarily reflect all the viewers of daytime drama. ABC
said a survey it conducted showed that 8 percent of women who watch
soap operas do so at their place of business. That comes out to 2.8
million working women sneaking peeks at daytime dramas while the
boss isn't looking _ unless, of course, they're the boss, in which
case go right ahead.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed PMs, May 17</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890516-0212 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-89 1344EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv17   05-16 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 17,0516</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release PMs Wednesday, May 17</HEAD>
<HEAD>Big Changes Since the 1970s</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Factors helping to restrain inflation today are
the experience of the 1970s, the lingering pains associated with it
and a determination not to let it happen again.
   You can see it in the marked resistance to price increases these
days, especially in the automobile market but also in retailing,
housing, insurance, travel and several other product and service
areas.
   The 1980s are not like the 1970s in that respect. Back then, an
attitude prevailed that existing prices were the best that would be
seen for a while, so why not buy. Today's consumer prefers to wait
and see.
   In the 1970s, many consumers, and producers too, didn't care as
much about holding the price line. For consumers, automatic pay
raises took care of higher living costs. For businesses, price
increases were regular.
   In the 1980s, automatic cost-of-living adjustments are less
common than before. Unions aren't as strong and businesses are more
intent on keeping down labor costs. They have to.
   The reason is competition. Today's markets are much more global
in nature, and that means a manufacturer must keep prices in line
or a foreign competitor will undersell him. It's happened before,
and it might again.
   That same factor prevents foreigners from raising their prices
in the United States. With the decline in the value of the dollar,
American producers are more competitive. Foreigners, therefore,
must fight for markets here.
   In general, these foreign producers have been good fighters;
many, in fact, have chosen to hold prices low by ``eating'' some of
their expenses rather than passing them on. That is, they have
voluntarily cut their margins.
   Third parties were a big factor in consumer, or demand
inflation, during the 1970s. Americans learned from that
experience, particularly in regard to health insurance and many
contracts now limit the role of the third party.
   The most specific example of this change is the tendency of
employers today to lower their involvement in paying for health
policies from 100 percent, with workers picking up the difference.
   When you pay for a service yourself, if only partially, you are
less likely to overuse it, or at least that's one of the
conclusions at work today based on the experience of the '70s.
   Unfortunately, health care remains an inflation problem in the
'80s, and probably will continue to be so in the 1990s. The reason
isn't a mystery if you consider the question: How do you control
spending when lives are at stake?
   Still another similarity exists between the '70s and the '80s:
the inability of consumers to resist price increases dictated by
the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries.
   But in those other respects, the American challenge to inflation
this decade is a sharp contrast to its acquiescence to inflation in
the prior one. History, at least recent history, hasn't been
ignored.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End advance for PMs Wednesday, May 17</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890516-0213 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-89 1338EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a AM-ReligionToday Adv19   05-16 0845</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Religion Today, Adv 19,0865</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv19</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release AMs Friday, May 19, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Religious Leaders Exert Pressure on Television Advertisers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRIGGS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A group that organizers contend is ``the largest coalition of
Christians ever mobilized to deal with an urgent moral concern'' is
targeting television advertisers in a campaign to reduce sex and
violence on the small screen.
   Christian Leaders for Responsible Television, or CLEAR-TV,
recently put advertisers on notice: If they are among the top 10
sponsors of sex, violence and profanity on network television
during the May ``sweeps'' period, when ratings determine rates for
advertisers, they may become boycott targets.
   ``We'll pick one or two corporations out of that list, and we're
going to boycott them,'' said the Rev. Billy Melvin, chairman of
CLEAR-TV. ``By early June, we'll announce who's going to be
boycotted.''
   With more than 1,600 Christian leaders backing it, CLEAR-TV is
no ordinary pressure group. The coalition features top officials
from 70 mainline and conservative Protestant denominations and more
than 100 Roman Catholic bishops, including such heavyweights as
Cardinal Joseph Bernardin of Chicago and Archbishop John L. May of
St. Louis, president of the National Conference of Catholic Bishops.
   The group relies on the monitoring system of the Rev. Donald
Wildmon's Tupelo, Miss.-based American Family Association. He's a
United Methodist.
   ``I think it's an idea not only whose time has come, but it's
long overdue,'' said the Rev. Milton Efthimious, a founder of
CLEAR-TV and executive director of the Department of Church and
Society of the Greek Orthodox Church of North and South America.
``A lot of the things you see on television today would never have
been shown 15 years ago.''
   Melvin said the coalition turned to advertisers after network
executives ignored an appeal to voluntarily reduce the portrayals
of sex, violence and profanity on the small screen.
   The coalition's last attempt two years ago at a boycott of
advertisers was successful, Melvin said, with both Noxell Corp. and
Mazda Motor of America Inc. dropping out of CLEAR-TVs ``top 10''
list of advertisers sponsoring offensive programs.
   Melvin said the boycott of Noxell, maker of Cover Girl
cosmetics, was lifted within two months, and the boycott of Mazda
was dropped after four months.
   Both companies said CLEAR-TV made them more sensitive to the
type of programs they were sponsoring, but said the actions they
took conformed to their own standards.
   Albert Goldberg of the Mazda Information Bureau in Los Angeles
said the company stopped advertising on ``Miami Vice'' and
``Hunter,'' two shows criticized for excessive violence, ``on our
own accord.''
   He added, ``It is true it was brought to our attention by
CLEAR-TV.''
   Deborah A. Alford, manager of corporate communications for
Noxell, said after discussions with CLEAR-TV, the company
``formalized what was an existing policy'' to steer away from
programming that is overly violent or contains gratuitous sex and
profanity.
   Earlier this year, Tambrands Inc., Proctor &amp; Gamble Co.,
McDonald's Corp. and Kimberly Clark Corp. decided not to advertise
on Fox Broadcasting Corp.'s ``Married ... With Children.'' The
corporate decisions followed a letter-writing campaign by Terry
Rakolta, a Michigan woman who objected to the sexual innuendo and
the treatment of women in the popular comedy about a blue-collar
family.
   Melvin of Wheaton, Ill., who also is executive director of the
National Association of Evangelicals, said advertisers are saying,
``For crying out loud, give us something decent to present to the
American public.''
   The networks have taken a low profile toward groups such as
CLEAR-TV, and some advertising agencies say they face a dilemma in
balancing concerns about sex and violence while meeting their
clients' needs.
   ``ABC has chosen not to comment on the operations of this
organization,'' said Janice Gretemeyer, director of press relations
for ABC.
   Thomas Somerset, an executive at the advertising firm handling
Mazda's account, said it is a sensitive issue because viewers tend
to be attracted to things that are sensational, but companies do
not want to run the risk of being targeted by groups such as
CLEAR-TV.
   ``Do these groups have an influence in what goes on? Yes. Is it
right? I'm not sure,'' said Somerset, a senior vice president of
Foote, Cone &amp; Belding.
   Leaders of CLEAR-TV such as Efthimious expressed mixed opinions
about the tactics of pressuring advertisers, but he said the
networks have to take repsonsibility for the ``slime and sleaze''
sent into American homes.
   ``The thing I'm uncomfortable about is I don't think the church
or the synagogue should be an inquisition,'' Efthimious said.
``But, by the same token, I don't think the media should hide
behind the First Amendment.''
   Roman Catholic Bishop Stanislaus J. Brzana of Ogdensburg, N.Y.,
a member of the executive committee of CLEAR-TV, said the religious
community is exercising its own right to free speech.
   ``We are also citizens of this country. The airwaves belong to
everybody,'' he said. ``We are trying in a fair way to exert our
influence. We don't know how far we will get, but we are trying. We
are trying.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs May 19</NOTE>
</DOC>
