<DOCNO> AP890516-0214 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-89 1340EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-Preacher'sProgress Adv21   05-16 1141</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Preacher's Progress, Adv 21,1177</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv21</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, May 21, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Minister's Work in Providing Homes, Fighting Drugs Draws Attention</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note language in 3rd graf.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With a finger pointed to the rear of the church,
the minister commanded a young man to stand.
   ``Michael Stone!'' said the Rev. Johnny Ray Youngblood before
1,000 witnesses. ``I'm goin' a tell you what my mama once told me:
At the rate you're goin', someone's goin' a kill you. Man, you got
a baaaaad attitude. You hear me?
   ``And friends of Michael's, if you see him in trouble, you jack
his ass right up, you deal with him. You hear me?''
   The St. Paul Community Baptist Church congregation heard, all
right, punctuating his scolding with amens and yessirs.
   Youngblood's words were daring, but his daring has a solid
record:
   _As co-chairman of the East Brooklyn Congregations, a group of
55 churches and a synagogue, he led an effort that turned an
abandoned section of eastern Brooklyn into a community of
working-class families by building 1,250 homes. The project, called
Nehemiah after the Biblical prophet who rebuilt the walls of a
burned-out Jerusalem, has inspired similar plans in Baltimore and
Los Angeles. Congress recently passed a ``Nehemiah'' law that
provides incentives for cities to copy the Brooklyn project.
   _He formed an alliance two years ago with city banks to secure
jobs for black high school graduates; 300 now have entry-level
positions.
   _And the church, located in one of New York City's toughest
areas, was surrounded by storefront drug operations until he
lobbied police to enforce a law that locked up buildings in which
people were arrested for drugs; then, the church bought 14
properties. The church now rents 11 stores and three houses.
   ``We need a whole new culture,'' the 40-year-old Youngblood said
in an interview. ``And I think the church might have to become the
incubator.''
   Politicians, community activists and preachers from more than
100 cities have made pilgrimmages to Nehemiah homes. Many then go
to hear Youngblood's gospel.
   ``He's a new type of leader,'' said Gov. Mario Cuomo, one of
those escorted by Youngblood to the homes. ``He's good at putting
together coalitions and working cooperatively. ... There's none of
the demagogue in him.''
   ``He's making the Old Testament come alive,'' said Michael
Gecan, the New York area organizer for the Industrial Areas
Foundation, a group founded by the late Saul Alinsky to train
community organizers and build citizen groups. ``He's becoming a
national leader, quietly.''
   Some black leaders say too quietly.
   ``As a clergyman, he's a premier example of the strong, new
black clergy today,'' said the Rev. Calvin Butts, pastor of the
Abyssinian Baptist Church in Harlem and a civil rights activist.
``But in terms of whether he's had a profound impact on the major
issues this city faces today, I say he has no public presence.
   ``On the issue of police brutality, when you look at the number
of people who took radical stands, Johnny Ray Youngblood is not
there. When you think of the lack of proper health care for the
poor, Johnny Ray Youngblood is not there. And at a time when we
need new leaders in this city to improve the climate of racial
tension, he has not spoken out,'' Butts said.
   ``Speaking out,'' said Youngblood, ``is not always the best way
to get results. I think I am involved in the vital issues. Housing
is one. Education is one.''
   And yet Youngblood has found that his behind-the-scenes work has
not led to more Nehemiah homes elsewhere in New York _ and he's
starting to speak out.
   ``We will build in the South Bronx,'' Youngblood told a crowd of
5,000 at a recent rally at a 4.2-acre Bronx site that is now all
rubble and broken glass.
   The demonstration came after Mayor Edward Koch had rebuffed
Nehemiah backers who wanted to build homes there. Koch favors a
developer's plan to build 350 condominiums, starting at $95,000,
while Nehemiah wants to build 90 homes, beginning at $57,000.
   Nehemiah depends on interest-free loans from a $10 million
church fund, large tracts of land donated by the city, property tax
abatements and city grants of $10,000 a house.
   ``You will own homes in the South Bronx,'' Youngblood vowed.
``The South Bronx may look like a graveyard, but all resurrecting
takes place in graveyards.''
   Youngblood is a Southerner, raised in a three-room house in New
Orleans by a God-fearing mother and a stern father. In his youth,
he liked ``to go out with the guys, run with the girls,'' but his
mother set him straight. ``Her word was like the echo of God,'' he
said.
   He earned a master's degree in divinity in Rochester, N.Y., and
in 1974, St. Paul's deacons hired him.
   He was 26, married, with an infant son.
   ``We were looking for a leader,'' recalled William Brandon, a
church member since 1934 and a deacon in 1974. ``We had been
through a lot of crises with different ministers. We decided to
turn him loose.''
   Then, the congregation had only 72 people.
   But Youngblood's oratory and community work drew scores of
newcomers. In 1979, the congregation moved to a bigger building,
which they expanded this year.
   Now, St. Paul has 4,500 members.
   The church has a $2.5 million budget, 27 staff members, 400
volunteer workers and an elementary school. About 45 percent of the
families are tithers, meaning they pledge 10 percent of their
salaries to the church.
   Crowds of 1,000 or more pack the two Sunday services, which
begin the instant music director Eli Wilson hits the keys of an
electronic keyboard. The 80-member choir, two drummers and
congregation are a beat behind and in seconds people are up,
clapping their hands and stamping their feet. The floor bounces.
   From the pulpit, Youngblood is part entertainer and part
teacher. He is funny at times, fiery at times, straight-talking all
times.
   He asks the black men to stand, visitors to stand and children
with report cards to come to the front as their grades are read.
There is calculation in this: He wants more men to come, more new
members and better grades for the children.
   The reverend pays special attention to young people. ``We are
rallying around the African proverb that it takes a whole village
to raise a child,'' he said in an interview.
   Michael Stone knows.
   ``It was hard to hear what he said,'' the 17-year-old said a few
weeks after Youngblood disciplined him from the pulpit for getting
into a fight after Bible class.
   ``But I've been controlling my temper better these days,'' he
said. ``His doing that made a lot of people keep an eye out on me.
It helped.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, May 21</NOTE>
