<FIRST>u f PM-BusinessHighlights     05-16 0832</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0866</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   WPP Group PLC said it had agreed to acquire its
rival Ogilvy Group Inc. for $864 million in a deal that would
create the world's second largest advertising and marketing
services company.
   The announcement, which was made shortly after midnight, said
the London-based WPP Group would pay $54 a share for all of
Ogilvy's common stock. The agreement was approved by the boards of
both companies.
   Ogilvy began formal dicussions with the London-based WPP last
week after WPP indicated it was willing to pay more than $50 a
share.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Early May sales of cars and trucks made by
U.S.-based automakers dropped 8.2 percent compared with last year,
when consumers were flocking to showrooms before incentives
expired, the companies reported.
   The eight major companies making vehicles in North America said
Monday they sold cars and light trucks at an average daily rate of
36,480 during the May 1-10 period this year, compared with a rate
of 39,771 during the same time last year.
   Cars sold at a rate 9.8 percent lower than in early May last
year, and truck sales were down 5.3 percent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. industrial operating rate rose
moderately to 83.9 percent in April, but factories remain under
less strain than when the year began, the government said.
   Although the Federal Reserve Board's report Monday showed
industry using more of its capacity last month, it revised its
figures for the first three months of the year to show less
activity than previously reported.
   The capacity rate hit its most recent peak of 84.3 percent in
December _ a 10-year high. The rate held steady in January and
slipped in both February and March.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Natural Resources Defense Council and
Ralph Nader are calling on the Environmental Protection Agency and
Congress to immediately ban use of the chemical Alar on apples.
   The International Apple Institute said Monday the apple industry
is already taking action to rid the food supply of the chemical,
used to regulate growth and extend the shelf life of the fruit.
Janet S. Hathaway, an attorney for the council, said Alar will be
applied to this year's crop in June if the EPA does not take
emergency action.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In an important victory for the securities
industry, the Supreme Court has ruled that disputes between
investors and brokers must be resolved by arbitration, not in court
suits.
   By a 5-4 vote, the justices Monday overturned a 1953 high court
decision that permitted lawsuits under an anti-fraud provision of
the Securities Act of 1933. The case stemmed from a challenge by 17
first-time investors to standard brokerage contracts that order
arbitration to settle all disputes.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cray Research Inc., the world's largest
supercomputer maker, will split into two companies by spinning off
the division that has been developing what Cray says will be the
world's fastest supercomputer, the company said.
   The new company, to be called Cray Computer Corp., will be
formed around Cray-3 operations based in Colorado Springs, Colo.,
where founder Seymour Cray has been developing his latest
supercomputer, the company said Monday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of 16- to 24-year-olds seeking work
this summer will be about 706,000 below the level of last year
because of a continued population decline in that age group, the
government said.
   An estimated 3.3 million people in that age group, mostly
students seeking summer jobs and high school and college graduates
looking for permanent jobs, will enter the labor force between now
and July, the Labor Department said Monday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The rate of coal mining fatalities matched a
record low pace in the first quarter of 1989 while the rate of
deaths in the non-coal mining sector was up from the same period
last year, the government said.
   The Labor Department's Mine Safety and Health Administration on
Monday reported 12 coal mining deaths in the first three months of
this year, compared with 11 during the same period last year. But
because of an increase in the number of hours worked in coal mining
over last year, the agency said the fatality rate matched last
year's record low of 0.03 for every 200,000 hours worked.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market kept moving ahead Monday, following through on
its strong rally at the end of last week. The Dow Jones industrial
average climbed 24.19 to 2,463.89 on top of its 56.82-point jump
Friday, establishing a new post-crash high for the second straight
session.
   The dollar surged in foreign exchange, reaching more than 2-year
highs against several key currencies. Bond prices were mixed.
   Copper futures prices closed sharply lower on New York's
Commodity Exchange on word of a sharp rise in copper stocks. On
other markets, grain and soybean futures were mostly lower,
precious metals futures were down, livestock and meat prices were
mixed and energy prices were mostly higher.
</TEXT>
