<FIRST>r f PM-ComedyChannel     05-16 0552</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Comedy Channel,0569</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Hold for release at 10 a.m. EDT _ time set by source</HEAD>
<HEAD>Time Inc.'s HBO Unit to Launch Comedy Channel on Basic Cable</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pay-television programmer Home Box Office
Inc. said today it plans to launch the first advertiser-supported
channel devoted entirely to comedy starting this fall.
   The new service, which would be offered to cable operators for
inclusion at no extra charge to subscribers to their basic service,
would represent the Time Inc. unit's first venture into basic cable
programming.
   The new service will have to fight for channel space with
several other recently launched cable networks. Among the newcomers
are Turner Broadcasting System Inc.'s Turner Network Television,
the National Broadcasting Co.'s Consumer News and Business Channel
and an array of regional sports networks.
   Michael Fuchs, Home Box Office chairman and chief executive,
said in a news release disclosing the plans that his company has
presented the concept of a comedy network to cable operators across
the country over the past several months and that the idea has
received ``strong support.''
   ``We anticipate demographics that will attract strong advertiser
attention, consistent programming that will score well with
consumers and a new basic service that will generate a healthy cash
flow for the cable operator,'' he said.
   Home Box Office could face competition from the MTV Networks
division of Viacom Inc., which also is considering launching an
all-comedy network.
   Home Box Office currently operates the HBO and Cinemax pay-TV
services, which already include comedy shows within their lineup of
movies, sports, music, drama, documentaries and other special
programs.
   Fuchs said the concept of a comedy channel appealed to ``a
number of motion picture distributors'' who he said liked the
promotional opportunities the channel offers for generating
awareness of their comedy programs.
   The channel will feature comedy hosts who will have their own
shows incorporating a variety of programming ranging from
promotional clips from stand-up performances, current comedy films,
classic TV shows and theater to full-length motion pictures. There
also will be live comedy features and visits by established and new
comedians.
   Programming would originate from studio facilities in New York.
   Fuchs said Home Box Office has already established strong
professional relationships with the comedy community through HBO's
involvement dating to 1976 with its ``On Location'' series that has
featured comedians such as Rodney Dangerfield, Robin Williams and
Steve Martin.
   He said HBO research indicates comedy programs maintain higher
ratings even over repeated viewings than non-comedy programs and
that 64 percent of cable subscribers between ages 18 and 34 have
expressed interest in a comedy channel.
   Barry Kluger, a spokesman for MTV Networks, said MTV has been
looking into whether a comedy channel could make it for five years
and may make a decision soon on whether to launch an all-comedy
service.
   ``We have tried to put together a business plan. We are active
in that. It's something that is on front burner. But the key is
distribution,'' he said.
   He said there is ``so little space these days'' on cable systems
that a waiting list of cable networks has developed at some of them.
   But he noted that MTV already has considerable experience in
running basic cable services, including its MTV: Music Television,
VH-1 and Nickelodeon networks.
</TEXT>
