<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-89 0142EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-AutoSales Bjt   05-16 0489</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auto Sales, Bjt,0503</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sales Down, But Last Year's Period Was Strong</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. sales of cars and light trucks fell 8.2
percent during early May from the same period last year, when
procrastinating customers headed to showrooms to take advantage of
incentives.
   The eight major companies making cars and light trucks in North
America said Monday they sold a combined average of 36,480 vehicles
a day during the May 1-10 period this year. That compared with an
average of 39,771 during the same time last year. Car sales were
down 9.8 percent and truck sales were off 5.3 percent.
   But year-to-year comparison was colored by one of the strongest
10-day periods last year, the second-best selling year in auto
industry history. A large portion of the incentives in effect in
early May last year expired May 11, prompting buyers who had waited
to head to dealerships to take advantage of the enticements.
   Incentives also were in effect during the period this year. Ford
Motor Co.'s program expires May 31, General Motors Corp.'s dies
June 5 and Chrysler Corp.'s runs indefinitely. All offer buyers the
option of cash rebates or low-interest financing.
   Despite the statistical drop, dealers said Monday that business
was good.
   ``We had a very good March, April and May last year,'' said Joe
Matts, new car sales manager at Jones-West Ford-Mitsubishi in Reno,
Nev. ``If you compare it to last year, it's off, but that was a
very good year.''
   Herb Adcox, owner of Herb Adcox Chevrolet-Geo in Chattanooga,
Tenn., agreed, saying incentives helped sales.
   ``Most of them are taking the money,'' he said of the rebates.
``We're doing little or none on financing.''
   The automakers began the incentive programs at the start of the
second quarter after sales during the first three months came in
below expectations. Production continued at an ambitious pace,
meaning swelling inventories.
   Incentives have helped trim inventory levels, but analysts now
say that production cuts in the third period are likely.
   For the year, the companies reported car and truck sales running
4.1 percent behind last year's pace, with car sales off 6.1 percent
and truck sales down 0.5 percent.
   GM's car sales fell 9.5 percent during the May 1-10 period and
were 10.6 percent below the 1988 year-to-date rate. GM's truck
sales were up 6.1 percent in early May but down 0.5 percent for the
year.
   Ford's car sales were off 11.1 percent in early May and down 0.8
percent for the year. The company's light truck sales during early
May this year were 11.9 percent behind last year's rate and 3.6
percent lower than the year-to-date rate last year.
   Chrysler's car sales dropped 14.6 percent during the period and
were running 16.8 percent behind last year's pace. Sales of
Chrysler's light truck sales were off 9.3 percent for the period
and up 1.1 percent for the year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
