<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-89 0905EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-NYCDrought     05-16 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NYC Drought,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>City, Westchester County Lift Drought Restrictions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN SHANAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York City declared an end to drought
restrictions on water use after recent heavy rains filled upstate
reservoirs to nearly 90 percent.
   ``I asked people to pray for rain and the prayers worked,'' said
Mayor Edward I. Koch Monday. ``Thank you, New York for praying and
conserving.''
   When the drought emergency was declared in March, the reservoirs
were at 55 percent of capacity.
   Two weeks of rain brought levels up to 89.6 percent of capacity,
prompting the state Drought Emergency Task Force to recommend
Monday that water-use restrictions be lifted throughout the state.
   Normally at this time of year the reservoirs are at 100 percent
of capacity.
   ``The recovery made by our reservoirs is nothing short of
amazing,'' Koch said. ``It's the miracle of May.''
   Suburban Westchester County, which gets 85 percent of its water
from the city reservoir system, also announced Monday that
mandatory water restrictions were being eliminated, though
industries were urged to continue conserving water voluntarily.
   The city's restrictions had limited business use of water,
including in air conditioners, and banned the use of water for
lawns, flowers and washing cars, and had also urged personal
conservation.
   ``They are lifted! Go out and shower!'' Koch said.
   A few conservation measures remain in force despite the end of
the drought, said Harvey W. Schultz, commissioner of the city
Department of Environmental Protection.
   Hoses or sprinklers can be used to water lawns and shrubs only
between 7 p.m. and 11 a.m., and water can be served in restaurants
only upon request.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
