<DOCNO> AP890516-0226 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-89 0923EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-TreasuryBills     05-16 0178</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Treasury Bills,0183</SECOND>
<HEAD>Interest On Short-Term Securities Hits Lowest Level This Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on short-term Treasury
securities fell to the lowest level this year in the government's
latest auction.
   The Treasury Department sold $6.6 billion in three-month bills
at an average discount rate of 8.21 percent Monday, down from 8.41
percent last week. Another $6.6 billion was sold in six-month bills
at an average discount rate of 8.19 percent, down from 8.39 percent
last week.
   The rates were the lowest since three-month bills sold for 8.14
percent on Dec. 19 and six-month bills averaged 8.13 percent on
Nov. 28.
   The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors
_ 8.50 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling
for $9,792.50 and 8.66 percent for a six-month bill selling for
$9,586.00.
   In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said Monday that the
average yield for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index
for making changes in adjustable rate mortgages, fell to 9.05
percent last week, down from 9.16 percent the previous week.
</TEXT>
