<SECOND>PM-Sears Incentives, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0512</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: City-State Offer Sears $104 Million Deal, May Not Be Enough</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lede to CORRECT to `and,' sted `&amp;,' in Sears name. Picks
up 2nd graf, ``The Chicago....'' ^mfcnbchscgbs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sears, Roebuck and Co. has been offered an
incentive package worth more than $100 million to keep its
Merchandise Group in Chicago, but $72 million more may be needed to
convince the retailing giant to stay, according to a published
report today.
   The Chicago Sun-Times quotes unidentified sources as saying the
city and state offered Sears a 12-year, $40 million property tax
abatement and an agreement to designate a relocation site at O'Hare
International Airport as an Illinois enterprise zone.
   The incentive package also includes $16 million in
transportation improvements, 80 acres of virtually free land valued
at $48 million, and $10 million in investment tax credits and other
tax breaks, the newspaper reported.
   But the newspaper reported that an official familiar with the
negotiations between Sears and government officials said the
present O'Hare offer is not enough to prevent the state's largest
private employer from moving the Merchandise Group _ involving
6,700 jobs _ to the Sun Belt.
   The deal may have to be sweetened by up to $72 million more, the
newspaper said.
   Sources said the city has offered to lease Sears 80 acres at the
airport site for $10 a year for 99 years, the newspaper said.
   But the city has demanded that the retailer pay ``market value''
_ or about $72 million _ for 140 acres adjacent to the O'Hare site
that Sears wants to develop for other purposes, the newspaper said.
   A government source said the city must discount the cost of the
140 acres sharply to ``keep the Chicago site alive.''
   The official said other states have offered Sears up to 400
acres of free airport land plus lucrative tax breaks and employee
training.
   Last winter, the company announced a restructuring plan that
would relocate the Merchandise Group from the Sears Tower and put
the world's tallest building up for sale.
   It has been reported that Sears has been eyeing sites in
Charlotte, N.C.; Denver, Dallas and elsewhere for its merchandising
center. A final decision has been promised next month.
   Jay Hedges, executive director of the Illinois Department of
Commerce and Community Affairs, refused to discuss specifics of the
offer laid out to Sears last week by Gov. James R. Thompson and
Mayor Richard M. Daley.
   ``The ball is clearly in Sears' court,'' Hedges said. ``It's up
to them to come back to us and tell us what it would take to strike
an agreement.''
   Thompson expressed optimism Monday that Sears would keep the
Merchandise Group in Chicago. He said the city and state were
offering the retailer ``the largest incentive package we have ever
put together to retain a company.''
   Neither John Parsons, the Sears official in charge of the move,
nor John Schmidt, Daley's acting chief of staff, would comment on
negotiations.
</TEXT>
