<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-89 1033EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-Satellite     05-16 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Satellite,0310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rival Publishers Link Satellite, Cable TV Operations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rival publishers Rupert Murdoch and Robert Maxwell
said Tuesday they have agreed to link their satellite and cable
television operations in a five-year deal worth ``several
millions'' of dollars.
   The agreement means Maxwell Cable TV (MCTV) will carry all five
of Murdoch's Sky Television channels to cable subscribers.
   One of Murdoch's channels, the general entertainment Sky
Channel, is already available on cable. To view the remaining four,
Britons must purchase home receiving dishes.
   Maxwell said it cost the satellite company ``several millions''
to gain access to his cable customers. The agreement takes effect
June 1.
   Sky Television began bouncing signals off the Astra satellite in
February, bringing the first direct satellite-to-home television
signals to Britain. Potential customers have been discouraged from
subscribing to the service because of a shortage of receiving
dishes.
   A government-approved consortium, British Satellite
Broadcasting, begins broadcasting this fall, bouncing signals off
three of the five satellite channels allocated to Britain under
international treaty.
   ``It means an immediate addition of over 50,000 homes for Sky
Television,'' said Andrew Neil, editor of Murdoch's Sunday Times
newspaper and executive chairman of Sky Television.
   ``There is a potential for us to reach a million homes of people
who won't have to buy dishes, often living in areas where you
couldn't get a dish because they live in high rise blocks,
apartments and so on.''
   Only three of London's 32 boroughs, plus a handful of other
regions in Britain, are wired to receive cable. The Cable
Television Association says there are about 270,000 subscribers,
only 18.8 percent of homes capable of receiving it.
   MCTV, the largest cable operator in Britain, collects satellite
signals at its central receiving dish and relays them by cable to
50,000 subscribers.
</TEXT>
