<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-89 1137EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-ConsumerSurvey     05-16 0221</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Consumer Survey,0230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survey Says Americans Worried About Paying The Mortgage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paying the mortgage has replaced writing checks
for the monthly bills as the main financial worry of Americans,
according to a new study.
   In a survey of 1,000 U.S. households conducted for the
International Association for Financial Planning, 19 percent listed
``payments on the house'' among their two or three biggest
financial concerns, making it the most frequent response in the
study.
   In an IAFP survey last year, house payments ranked third at 9
percent, behind monthly bills and taxes, the organization said.
   In a related survey of 300 households with income of $50,000 or
more, house payments also ranked No. 1 at 21 percent, according to
the report.
   The survey on financial attitudes was conducted for the IAFP by
The Gallup Organization. The results were released Monday in
Atlanta.
   The survey also found that 25 percent of the respondents did not
have plans for retirement. Of those that did have plans, the
largest percentage _ 35 percent _ intended to rely on employee
retirement programs.
   Forty-three percent of the respondents said they are concerned
about outliving their retirement money, a drop from 49 percent last
year.
   ``Survey data indicates Americans have been distracted from this
long-term financial worry by near-term mortgage woes,'' the IAFP
said.
</TEXT>
