<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>Forecasts of Rain Drive Down Prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened lower this
morning on the Chicago Board of Trade in dealings influenced by
optimistic forecasts of precipitation in most crop areas.
   Wheat prices were down amid reports of rain in Kansas, where the
winter crop has sustained major damage because of hot, dry
conditions.
   Soybean prices were forced down by National Weather Service
forecasts of rain for some of the drier growing areas.
   Corn futures also were pressured by the weather service's 6- to
10-day forecast for increased precipitation. However, corn prices
may be helped by the Agriculture Department's announcement
yesterday that the Soviet Union has purchased 450-thousand metric
tons of corn.
   In early trading, corn was 3 cents to 4{ cents lower, with the
contract for delivery in May at 2.77} a bushel; wheat was 7\ cents
to 11 cents lower with May at $4.07 a bushel; soybeans were 5 cents
to 10 cents lower with May at $7.42 a bushel; oats were 4} cents to
6{ cents lower with May at $1.84 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were lower in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .15 cent lower to .10 cent higher with June at
71.77 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent lower to .10 cent
higher with May at 77.20 cents a pound; hogs were .42 cent lower to
.02 cent higher with June at 48.42 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were 1.10 cents to 1.37 cents lower with May at 34.65 cents
a pound.
   Livestock futures settled mixed Monday, while pork futures were
mostly higher.
</TEXT>
