   The stock market moved lower in active trading
today amid selling to collect profits amassed during the past two
strong sessions.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was off 13.74 at
2,450.15 by noon on Wall Street.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by more than 7 to 5 in the tally of
New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 783 issues down, 516 up
and 540 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 91.48 million shares by midday
compared to 86.61 million shares at the same point in Monday's
session.
   Besides the profit-motivated selling, analysts attributed the
downturn to renewed doubts about the economic outlook and about the
ability of companies to maintain profit growth if the economy
stalls.
   Federal Reserve policy makers meeting today have abundant
evidence of slower economic growth to sift through as they plot
their monetary policy course for the next six weeks.
   A report from a real estate trade group today said rising
mortgage rates hit home sales and prices hard in Northeast cities
in the first three months of 1989, while booming West Coast markets
fared much better.
   Occidental Petroleum led the list of actively traded NYSE
issues, showing a gain of ~ at 28[.
   Niagara Mohawk Power, the second most heavily traded stock, was
up [ to 11.
   International Business Machines was unchanged at 112}. IBM
unveiled a new OfficeVision family of computer software designed to
be more consistent and better integrated than its existing software.
   Among retail stocks, J.C. Penney shares lost 1[, falling to 58~,
after the company reported a 2.2 percent earnings decline for its
first quarter.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
slipped 0.45 to 175.80. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was off 0.57 at 349.47.
