<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-89 1240EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-InsiderTrading-Boston     05-16 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Insider Trading-Boston,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>SEC Charges Insider Trading Ring In Boston</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission filed
insider trading charges today against a 24-year-old former
paralegal and five others who allegedly made more than $800,000
from her tip about a leveraged buyout of a department store chain.
   The SEC alleged that the paralegal, Kerry A. Hurton, learned
from confidential documents that Hooker Corporation Ltd. planned to
announce a proposed buyout of Birmingham, Ala.-based Parisian Inc.
in July 1987.
   Ms. Hurton worked in the Boston office of the major New York law
firm Skadden, Arps, Slate, Meagher &amp; Flom.
   She allegedly passed information to her boyfriend, Eric Laboz of
New York City, and directly or indirectly to several other people
who made a total of $823,825 in profits by trading in Parisian
stock, the SEC said.
   One of the alleged illegal traders is a deputy U.S. marshal,
Bernard Stone of Norwell.
   The civil complaint, filed in U.S. District Court in Boston,
seeks to force the defendants to return the alleged profits and pay
up to three times the amount in penalties.
   According to the complaint, the defendants directly or
indirectly caused the purchase of 65,020 shares of Parisian stock
at an average price of about $18 a share in June and July 1987,
shortly before the proposed buyout.
   After the buyout was announced, Parisian stock rose to about $30
a share, the SEC said.
   Hooker, an Australian real estate and retailing company,
completed the acquisition of Parisian for $30.65 a share, or a
total of about $230 million, in April 1988. Parisian is a fashion
retailer with 16 stores in Alabama, Texas, Georgia and Florida.
   Skadden, Arps did not immediately a telephone call seeking
comment on the case. Ms. Hurton no longer works for the firm.
   Besides Ms. Hurton, Laboz and Stone, the defendants named in the
complaint are Jonathan R. Beck of North Hills, N.Y.; Bruce E.
Maurice of Danvers; and Sheldon M. Stone of Marblehead.
   The charges result from a one-year investigation that began
after the SEC ``was alerted by a private individual'' to the
possible illegal activity, said John Sturc, the agency's associate
director for enforcement in Washington.
</TEXT>
