<DOCNO> AP890516-0245 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-89 1241EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-PollutionCrackdown 2ndLd-Writethru f0106 05-16 0502</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pollution Crackdown, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0106,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>Massachusetts Plans Crackdown on Polluters</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Restores byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts plans to use undercover agents,
aerial surveillance and search warrants in a pollution crackdown
environmentalists and state officials today predicted will be the
broadest in the country.
   Escorted by dozens of uniformed enforcement officers, Gov.
Michael S. Dukakis today stood between the shore of the Charles
River and a new jail to underscore Massachusett's desire to hit
polluters with criminal penalties.
   ``These are violent crimes. They do violence against others,
against houses, against neighborhoods and against the water we
drink and the air we breathe,'' Dukakis said.
   A 33-member strike force of lawyers, scientists and police
officers will be used to find polluters and build cases against
them.
   Dukakis was joined by Attorney General James Shannon and the
state's entire environmental establishment, but not by federal
officials. Dukakis aides said, however, that they plan to
coordinate with the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency and the
local U.S. attorney.
   ``The state is thinking big and thinking properly,'' said Elissa
Parker, policy director at the Environmental Law Institute in
Washington.
   She said Maryland, Ohio and Pennsylvania have strike forces that
concentrate on toxic dumping and water pollution while
Massachusetts will include the protection of wetlands and other
habitats.
   Except for those three states, ``there aren't any statewide
initiatives that even come close to what Massachusetts is doing,''
she said.
   ``A lot of people viewed previous environmental enforcement as
an acceptable risk of doing business _ you could live with civil
penalties and a slap on the wrist,'' Shannon said.
   ``We're saying, `If you violate these laws, you run the risk of
criminal prosecution, a prison sentence and damn heavy fines.'''
   Daniel Greenbaum, who heads the state Department of
Environmental Quality Engineering, said up to 50 percent of people
discharging pollutants into sewers or the air do not have required
permits, and many who have permits violate them.
   State Secretary of Environmental Affairs John DeVillars said
polluters have ruined 103 water supplies in the state, created more
than 1,000 toxic dumps and cost the state $90 million a year in
losses from contaminated shellfish beds.
   He said state laws generally are tough enough, but have not been
enforced adequately. He also said Dukakis will file legislation
this year for tougher penalties.
   But Joseph Duggan of the Greater Boston Chamber of Commerce said
that the strike force is ``all stick and no carrot.''
   ``People who are intentionally disobeying the law, fouling the
land and atmosphere, should be cracked down on and made to pay,''
he said.
   But others find out after buying property that it was
contaminated and are told, ```You're responsible: Clear it up.' We
are objecting to that. We don't think it's the right approach,'' he
said.
   The environment became a focal point in last year's presidential
campaign when then-Vice President George Bush toured Boston Harbor
to criticize Dukakis, the Democratic candidate, for delaying a
cleanup of the harbor.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890516-0246 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-89 1245EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-California-Growth     05-16 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-California-Growth,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study Says California will Keep On Growing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALO ALTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All regions of California will post
population gains of more than 20 percent by the year 2000 and
Sacramento will be the fastest growing area, according to a new
study.
   The study released on Tuesday by the Center for Continuing Study
of the California Economy said the state's population will add
nearly 6 million people in the next decade to reach 35 million by
2000.
   San Diego will be the state's second fastest growing region
while the Los Angeles Basin will add nearly 3 million residents.
The San Francisco Bay area will grow by around a million.
   The forecast was higher than those by most state and regional
agencies. The study by the center projected a statewide population
more than 2 million higher than the state Department of Finance.
   ``Slow growth is not realistic,'' said Stephen Levy, the
center's director. ``The choices are either planned growth or
unplanned growth so we need to stop wishing and start preparing.''
   The study said foreign immigration plays a key role in the
state's growth with nearly 1 in 2 new residents a recent immigrant.
The center predicted the trend will continue with the addition of
more than 250,000 foreign immigrants each year.
   ``In 1988 ethnic minorities accounted for 40 percent of the
state's residents,'' the study said. ``By 2000 the share will be
nearly 50 percent.''
   The demographics underlying the housing market should remain
strong, the forecast added.
   ``Household growth is projected to range from 190,000 to 275,000
a year, depending on income growth and the behavior of recent
immigrants. Much of the growth wil be in the 35-54 age group which
has the highest income levels.''
</TEXT>
