<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-89 1247EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-Pubs     05-16 0223</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Pubs,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brewers To Draw Up Own Proposals To Counter Industry Shake-up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British brewers are drawing up their own proposals
to restructure the country's beer industry in an attempt to head
off government-proposed anti-monopoly reforms that would force
brewers to sell up to 22,000 pubs.
   The move by the brewers follows a meeting with Trade and
Industry Secretary Lord Young on Monday, during which he said he
would entertain alternative proposals as long as they remedied what
he calls a ``complex monopoly situation in the supply of beer.''
   Representatives of the Brewers' Society, the major trade group,
are to hold further meetings with Department of Trade and Industry
officials over the next two weeks to present their case.
   ``We are in a state of negotiations with the DTI,'' a society
spokesman said Tuesday. He wasn't identified in accordance with
British custom.
   The debate centers on recommendations made public in March by
the Monopolies and Mergers Commission aimed at promoting greater
competition in the way beer is supplied.
   Among the measures proposed was a limit of 2,000 on the number
of public houses, or pubs, that any single brewer could own. If
implemented, this measure could result in the forced sale of up to
22,000 pubs. Young said at the time he was inclined to implement
the commission's proposed reforms.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
