<HEAD>Ford Expands Canadian Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKVILLE, Ontario (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. of Canada Ltd. on
Tuesday announced a $225 million expansion at its St. Thomas,
Ontario, assembly plant to build a new line of full-size cars.
   Kenneth Harrigan, president and chief executive officer of the
Canadian subsidiary of the No. 2 U.S. automaker, said the expansion
will continue at its present level of employment, about 3,700
people.
   The expansion project includes money for increasing the number
of robots to 87 from 36 and improving a paint shop.
   The factory will begin producing the Ford LTD Crown Victoria and
the Mercury Grand Marquis in 1991.
   More than 80 percent of the 250,000 cars assembled annually at
the plant are exported to the United States.
