<FIRST>u f PM-CasinoClosing     05-16 0201</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Casino Closing,0208</SECOND>
<HEAD>Commission Votes To Shut Down Atlantis Casino</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAWRENCE, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Casino Control Commission voted
today for the first time to close a casino, ordering Elsinore's
Atlantis Casino Hotel to shut down Monday.
   The closure, sought by the Division of Gaming Enforcement, was
approved 5-0 after a three-day hearing.
   The Atlantis, which a month ago became the first New Jersey
gaming house denied a license renewal, has been losing money,
adding daily to a multimillion-dollar debt.
   ``The record in this case leads us inexorably to only one
conclusion,'' Commission Chairman Walter Read said. ``The casino
can no longer be operated on a sound and businesslike basis.''
   Conservator Joseph Nolan, appointed last month when the casino's
license expired, had sought permission to stay open at least
through the lucrative Memorial Day weekend.
   The Atlantis was sold last month to New York developer Donald
Trump, who already owns two casinos and one under construction in
Atlantic City. Trump had said that if the deal became final, he
would close the Atlantis' casino and operate it a first-class
hotel. State law bars ownership of more than three casino licenses
in Atlantic City by any one corporation or individual.
</TEXT>
