<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Retail     05-16 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Retail,0280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Penney's Posts Quaterly Earnings Drop, Dayton Hudson Has Gain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   J.C. Penny Co. said Tuesday that its first quarter profit fell 2
percent over a year ago due to costs of discontinuing a television
shopping network, while another large retailer, Dayton Hudson
Corp., posted a 29 percent jump in earnings.
   Penney said net income for the three months ended April 29 was
$128 million, or 97 cents a share, vs. $131 million, or 96 cents,
in the 1988 quarter. Sales totaled $3.34 billion, up 5 percent from
3.17 billion last year.
   Dayton Hudson said it netted $40 million, or 51 cents a share,
in the first quarter on sales of $2.83 billion. That compared with
earnings of $31 million, or 36 cents, and $2.54 billion in sales
last year.
   Dallas-based Penney said its latest results included a $20
million after-tax charge for discontinuing the operations of the
television shopping network Teleaction. Without the charge,
first-quarter earnings would have risen 13 percent, it said.
   Penney also said that revenue from other businesses, including
its life insurance operations, JCP Realty and JCPenney National
Bank, declined mainly because of its decision to leave the casualty
insurance business. It said it was talking to several major
insurance companies about the sale of J.C. Penney Casualty
Insurance Co.
   Dayton Hudson Chairman Kenneth A. Macke attributed the improved
quarterly results at the Minneapolis retailer to strength in the
Mervyn's department store chain and direct sales subsidiary.
   But he said Target's operating profit was below last year's
first quarter due to the opening of 38 new stores, largely in the
Southeast.
</TEXT>
