<HEAD>Hewlett-Packard Expects Apollo Acquisition Completed Within A Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALO ALTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hewlett-Packard Co. said Tuesday it
expected to complete the acquisition of Apollo Computer Inc. of
Chelmsford, Mass., by Monday.
   The deal will move Hewlett-Packard past Sun Microsystems Inc. to
become the world's largest maker of work stations, the desktop
machines that are more powerful than personal computers and are
generally used by scientists and engineers.
   More than 35 million shares of Apollo common stock, or 97
percent of outstanding shares, have been tendered for sale to
Hewlett-Packard, the company said.
   ``We're extremely pleased with the results of the tender offer,
which will allow us to move swiftly ahead with the combination of
our businesses,'' said John A. Young, Hewlett-Packard's president
and chief executive officer.
   The statement said Apollo will become a wholly owned subsidiary
of Hewlett-Packard. All necessary U.S. regulatory approvals were
obtained earlier this month and the plan has already been approved
by directors of both companies.
   Hewlett-Packard's tender offer of $13.125 per share for the
Apollo stock expired at midnight Monday.
