<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   05-16 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0276</SECOND>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices fell sharply
Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade in reaction to forecasts of
rainfall in crop producing states hurt recently by dryness.
   The drop in soybean prices also was attributed to technical
selling and softness in the export market.
   ``Everyone was negative from the start of trading,'' said Jerry
Gidel, an analyst with LIT America Inc. in Chicago.
   National Weather Service forecasts of rain in the Southern
Plains were augmented by private forecasters who predicted heavy
rains would spread to Kansas and Nebraska and other states in the
upper-Midwest plagued by dry conditions. The forecasts put the
market on the defensive.
   Gidel said soybean futures sell-stops were activated early in
trading, pushing new crop soybean prices below $7 for the first
time in weeks. He said rumors of interest in soy oil by the Soviet
Union had little effect on the market.
   Corn prices were not helped by the Agriculture Department's
announcement Monday that the Soviets would buy 450,000 metric tons
of corn.
   Reports of an above-average yield in the Indiana, Michigan and
Ohio soft red wheat crop caused a selloff in wheat futures, Gidel
said.
   At the close, wheat was 7\ cents to 8{ cents lower, with the
contract for delivery in May at $4.09{ a bushel; corn was 3{ cents
to 5\ cents lower with May at $2.77{ a bushel; oats were 6{ cents
to 7 cents lower with May at $1.84 a bushel; soybeans were 15 cents
to 20\ cents lower with May at $7.33 a bushel.
</TEXT>
