<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-89 1630EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-MortgageSurvey     05-16 0482</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mortgage Survey,0500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survey: Top Money Worry Among Americans is Paying The Mortgage</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Housing Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Long-term financial anxieties such as retirement
and old-age health care are taking a back seat to immediate worries
about paying the mortgage, a study shows.
   In a survey of 1,000 U.S. households, conducted for the
International Association for Financial Planning, 19 percent listed
``payments on the house'' among their two or three biggest
financial concerns, making it the most frequent response.
   In an IAFP survey last year, the monthly house payments ranked
third in frequency at 9 percent, the organization said, behind
monthly bills and taxes.
   The survey also suggests Americans are worrying less about
inflation, with only 2 percent of the respondents expressing
concern about rising consumer prices. In last year's IAFP survey,
inflation was listed by 9 percent of the respondents.
   ``If you look, their concerns are short- instead of long-term,''
IAFP President Charles Finn said Tuesday.
   Finn said rising interest rates are behind the heightened
concern about mortgage payments.
   ``The force that drives that the most is adjustable rate
mortgages,'' he said. ``I think you'll see that (the concern about
the mortgages) as long as the interest rates are up.''
   The survey, conducted by The Gallup Organization and released
Monday in Atlanta, also included a related study involving 300
households with income of $50,000 or more. In that group, house
payments also ranked No. 1 at 21 percent as a primary worry.
   The survey found that worries about making the mortgage payments
may be leading some people to divert attention from retirement
planning and long-term health care.
   The survey found 25 percent of respondents didn't have plans for
retirement. Of those that did, the largest percentage _ 35 percent
_ intended to rely on employee retirement programs.
   Saving for retirement was listed by only 3 percent of the
respondents, and was ranked next-to-last, above inflation.
   ``Survey data indicates Americans have been distracted from this
long-term financial worry by near-term mortgage woes,'' the survey
said.
   Only one in 10 in the survey said they would use their own
savings or earnings to pay for a family member's long-term health
care.
   If people do not make adequate arrangements for their retirement
or elderly health care, Finn said, they will have to rely on
government social programs.
   ``With the increases in life expectancy and the larger (elderly)
population, this has dramatic implications for the country,'' Finn
said. ``The message we are trying to get across is they should plan
for the future.''
   The IAFP is an Atlanta-based professional organization for the
financial planning industry.
   Gallup conducted the main survey in April using a random sample
described by the IAFP as ``representative of the U.S. as a whole.''
Scott Larsen, an IAFP spokesman, said the survey had a margin of
error of plus or minus 3.1 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890516-0260 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-89 1643EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Ogilvy-WPP Bjt   05-16 0753</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ogilvy-WPP, Bjt,0776</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ogilvy Chief Says WPP Buyout Offer Couldn't Be Beaten</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY103</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of Ogilvy Group Inc. said Tuesday he
investigated every reasonable alternative but could not find
anything to beat WPP Group PLC's record $864 million buyout offer
for the advertising giant.
   Kenneth Roman, Ogilvy's chairman, said he also was confident
there would be few if any client defections in the wake of the
buyout agreement reached late Monday, under which Ogilvy's board
unanimously approved WPP's proposal for a $54 a share tender offer
for all of Ogilvy's stock.
   Martin Sorrell, chief executive of London-based WPP, said at a
news conference that he intended to keep Ogilvy and its management
intact. As part of the deal, he signed an agreement that guarantees
Ogilvy will be run autonomously.
   The deal, the largest takeover ever in the advertising business,
comes less than two years after WPP broke onto the U.S. advertising
scene with a hostile $566 million buyout of the parent of another
huge ad agency, J. Walter Thompson. The Thompson buyout had been
the previous ad industry record.
   The addition of Ogilvy, the world's fifth-largest advertising
company, to the arsenal at WPP, the third-largest ad concern last
year, creates the world's second largest advertising and marketing
services company. The new company has billings of about $13.5
billion, a shade below industry leader Saatchi &amp; Saatchi PLC.
   Sorrell had proposed a friendly buyout at $45 a share in late
April, sweetened the proposal to $50 a share early last week and
boosted it to $54 a share this past weekend.
   The Ogilvy board approved the latest offer late Monday night,
the two sides announced early Tuesday. Roman and Sorrell appeared
together at a midmorning news conference to discuss the deal and
Roman later presided at the previously-scheduled Ogilvy annual
shareholders meeting.
   Sorrell said Ogilvy fit his plan to build WPP into a group of
quality name brands. ``We are not the largest nor do we want to
be,'' he said.
   WPP will pay for Ogilvy stock by raising about $350 million with
an issue of securities that can be converted into WPP stock. The
rest will come from bank loans.
   Roman said Ogilvy, which was founded 41 years ago and has such
blue-chip clients as American Express Co., American Telephone &amp;
Telegraph Co. and Unilever NV, would have preferred to remain
independent.
   He said the company ``pursued every reasonable course'' to do so
but found the WPP offer was ``far and away the best'' for Ogilvy
clients, shareholders and employees. Roman will remain chairman of
Ogilvy.
   At the shareholders' meeting, Roman said management considered
``everything from white knights to white squires to
recapitalization to leveraged buyouts'' but found it could not beat
WPP's all-cash offer.
   Roman declined to identify any of those he talked with about
alternatives.
   The shareholders' meeting attracted about 250 people and lasted
some 35 minutes, including a 12-minute presentation of the
company's commercials. Shareholders asked only three questions and
none voiced an opinion on the deal.
   Ogilvy stock traded in the mid-$20s a share a year ago and
closed at $32 a share the day before WPP's initial proposal was
disclosed. Ogilvy closed at $53.12{ a share Tuesday, down 12{ cents
from Monday's close.
   David Ogilvy, the Ogilvy founder who has been named chairman of
WPP as part of the takeover deal and had reportedly been critical
of WPP's initial advances, attended the meeting but did not address
it. He also declined to discuss the takeover with reporters.
   Burt Manning, the head of J. Walter Thompson, said he welcomed
Ogilvy's addition to WPP and said the buyout ``improves WPP's
chances for competing in the marketplace.''
   He said Thompson would nonetheless compete fiercely with
Ogilvy's main agency, Ogilvy &amp; Mather Worldwide, for clients.
   Some analysts have said WPP's acquisition of Ogilvy could prompt
some advertisers to take their business elsewhere.
   Thompson works for Eastman Kodak Co., for instance, while Ogilvy
works for rival Polaroid Corp.
   Greg Ostroff, who follows advertising stocks for Goldman Sachs &amp;
Co., said there may be potential conflicts involving as much as
$650 million of the new company's billings. But he declined to
estimate how much business the two companies may lose by sharing
the same corporate parent.
   Ostroff said the friendly tone of the Ogilvy buyout contrasts
with the hostility of the deal for Thompson's parent, JWT Group.
Several sizeable clients left Thompson after that takeover,
dissatisfied with turmoil in agency management.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
