<HEAD>Crude Oil Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crude oil futures soared above $21 a barrel
Tuesday before settling with moderate gains, while prices for
refined petroleum products headed lower.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the June contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil, ended
the day 19 cents higher to close at $20.70 a 42-gallon barrel.
   The near-month contract had risen as much as 80 cents a barrel
to $21.31 earlier in the session before profit-taking by
professional traders eroded the gain.
   Among refined petroleum products traded on the exchange, June
heating oil settled at 49.19 cents a gallon, down 0.68 cent. June
wholesale unleaded gasoline slid 0.29 cent to 65.80 cents a gallon.
   Madison Galbraith, a senior trader with Merrill Lynch Energy
Futures, said internal market influences were largely responsible
for the runup in crude, which began in Europe, in the absence of
fresh fundamental news.
