<FIRST>u f BC-Minorco-GoldFields     05-16 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Minorco-Gold Fields,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Gold Giants Merger Bid Collapses After New York Ruling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A deal that would have created the world's largest
gold company collapsed Tuesday after a New York judge refused to
lift an order blocking South Africa-controlled Minorco S.A. from
acquiring Consolidated Gold Fields PLC.
   Minorco Chief Executive Sir Michael Edwardes said his company's
bid would lapse Wednesday after U.S. District Court Judge Michael
Mukasey maintained an injunction barring Minorco from buying more
Gold Fields shares.
   Luxembourg-based Minorco is the world's largest gold producer in
the non-communist world and Gold Fields is second.
   Edwardes said Minorco continued to be the largest single
shareholder in Gold Fields, with a nearly 30 percent stake, and
would ``keep the position under close review.''
   ``We will now energetically implement our strategy of
transforming Minorco into an operating company,'' he said.
``Minorco is now a familiar name in the market, both in Britain and
overseas, and has a very positive future.''
   Gold Fields Chief Executive Rudolph Agnew said he was ``highly
delighted'' with the result of the battle, calling it ``a
tremendous victory.''
   Minorco's $6 billion offer for all outstanding shares of Gold
Fields stock was to expire at midnight Wednesday.
   Gold Fields' share price fell by 47 pence to 13.73 pounds, or
$22.37, on the London Stock Exchange Tuesday, indicating the market
expected the takeover bid to fail.
</TEXT>
