<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     05-16 0575</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0597</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Lower; Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar's sharp ascent stalled Tuesday as the
rally ran up against nervousness over government reports on foreign
trade and inflation.
   The Federal Reserve sold some dollars, but traders were divided
on whether the central bank's intervention was an important factor
in halting the currency's rise.
   The dollar finished higher against the French franc and Italian
lira but slightly lower against other major currencies.
   On Monday the dollar had reached its highest point against the
West German mark since the end of 1986 and its highest point
against the Japanese yen since November 1987. In one week the
dollar had tacked on 2.2 percent against each currency.
   ``The market is still bullish. Customers are willing to buy the
dollar and are looking for numbers to buy it,'' said Frank Conte, a
vice president at Barclays Bank PLC in New York.
   The Commerce Department was scheduled to report on the March
merchandise trade deficit on Wednesday and the Labor Department was
to announce figures on April consumer prices on Thursday.
   Although currency traders largely have ignored trade figures in
recent months, a particularly large deficit figure might be enough
to puncture the bubble of the recent speculative run-up in the
dollar, some traders believe.
   A big increase in consumer prices might actually help the dollar
by increasing the chance the Federal Reserve would push up interest
rates, something that makes dollar-denominated investments more
attractive.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.6398 to buy one pound, more expensive than $1.6385 late Monday.
Later in New York the dollar also lost ground as the pound rose to
$1.6435 from $1.6410.
   In Tokyo, the dollar closed up 0.20 yen at 137.00 yen, despite
reported intervention by the Bank of Japan. Later in London, the
dollar was quoted at 137.28 yen. By the end of the trading day in
New York, the dollar dropped to 136.81 yen from 137.15 on Monday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York compared with late Monday's
rates included: 1.9363 West German marks, down from 1.9390; 1.7310
Swiss francs, down from 1.7370; 1.1888 Canadian dollars, down from
1.1898; 6.5560 French francs, up from 6.5550; and 1,409.75 Italian
lire, up from 1,409.00.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe compared with late Monday:
1.9426 West German marks, up from 1.9415; 1.7360 Swiss francs, down
from 1.7438; 6.5685 French francs, down from 6.5725; 2.1820 Dutch
guilders, down from 2.1905; 1,408.75 Italian lire, down from
1,411.00; 1.1892 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1905.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid price of $374.25 a troy ounce,
compared with $374.00 late Monday.
   In Zurich, gold closed at a bid $374.40 compared with $379.25
late Friday. Bullion markets were closed in Switzerland on Monday.
   In Hong Kong on Tuesday, gold rose 69 cents an ounce to close at
$375.99.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery fell to $375.50 an ounce from $375.60 on Monday.
   Later, Republic National Bank of New York said gold was bid at
$374 an ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, down from $374.10 late Monday.
   Silver bullion prices rose on the London market where the metal
was trading at a late bid price of $5.55 a troy ounce, compared
$5.53 Monday. On New York's Comex, silver edged up to $5.500 an
ounce from $5.491 on Monday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
