<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     05-16 0729</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0756</SECOND>
<HEAD>Forecasts of Rain Causes Drop in Grain Soybean Prices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices plunged Tuesday
on the Chicago Board of Trade in reaction to forecasts of increased
rain.
   On other markets, copper prices continued to slide, livestock
and meat prices were mostly lower, energy futures were mixed in
volatile trading, and precious metals were mixed in quiet trading.
   Wheat settled 7{ cents to 8{ cents lower, with the contract for
delivery in May at $4.09{ a bushel; corn was 3\ cents to 5\ cents
lower with May at $2.77{ a bushel; oats were 6{ cents to 7{ cents
lower with May at $1.84 a bushel; soybeans were 15} cents to 20}
cents lower with May at $7.32\ a bushel.
   ``Everyone was negative from the start of trading,'' said Jerry
Gidel, an analyst with LIT America Inc. in Chicago.
   National Weather Service forecasts of rain in the Southern
Plains were augmented by private forecasters who predicted heavy
rains would spread to western crop states.
   Soybean futures sell-stops were activated early in trading,
pushing new-crop prices below $7 for the first time in weeks, Gidel
said.
   Corn prices were not helped by the Agriculture Department's
announcement Monday that the Soviets would buy 450,000 metric tons
of corn, and expectations of an above-average yield in the Indiana,
Michigan and Ohio soft red wheat crop caused a selloff in wheat
futures, Gidel said.
   Copper prices continued a plunge that began Monday on the New
York's Commodities Exchange.
   ``The market is reflecting a supply-and-demand equation that has
deteriorated considerably in the last month,'' said William
O'Neill, an analyst with Elders Futures Inc. in New York.
``Technical selling has added to the momentum downward.''
   O'Neill said that there is lessening concern about the U.S.
labor situtation.
   ``The early indications are the tone the talks will take will
not be as negative as was thought at one time,'' he said.
   Copper was 2.50 cents to 2.90 cents lower with the contract for
delivery in May at $1.171 a pound.
   Energy futures were mixed on the New York Mercantile Exchange in
frantic trading spurred by rumors and news from non-OPEC nations
meeting in London.
   The near-month contract crude oil prices rose as much as 80
cents a barrel to $21.31 early in the session before profit-taking
by professional traders eroded the gain.
   Prices were affected by word that the Organization of Petroelum
Exporting Nations will not raise the ceiling on production at their
next meeting, said Jerry Samuels, an analyst with Shearson Lehman
Hutton Inc in New York.
   Ministers of non-OPEC nations announced Tuesday they haven't
made a decision on the amount of oil they will produce in the
second half of the year. However, they did indicate they favored
cooperating with OPEC.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil was .11 cents to 19 cents
higher with June at $20.70 a barrel; heating oil was .68 cent lower
to .15 cent higher with June at 49.19 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .48 cent lower to .23 cent higher with June at 65.80
cents a gallon.
   Trading in precious metals was in a very narrow range on the
Commodities Exchange. A pause in the rise in the dollar, caused a
pause in the drop of precious metals futures.
   Gold was .30 cents lower to .20 cents higher with May at $375.50
a troy ounce; Silver was .08 cent to .09 cent higher with May at
$5.50 a troy ounce.
   Livestock and meat futures plunged on the Chicaago Mercantile
Exchange, with frozen pork bellies down the 2 cents limit because
of concern over high inventory.
   There were reports that Agriculture Department's cold storage
report due out Monday will show near-record stocks of pork bellies
of about 156.5 million pounds, said Dale Benson of Dean Witter
Reynolds Inc. in New York.
   Cattle prices were forced lower on weak cash sales and a
spillover from the selloff of hog futures.
   Live cattle were .15 cent lower to .05 cent higher with June at
71.52 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent lower to .12 cent
higher with May at 77.12 cents a pound; hogs were .20 cent to .85
cent lower with June at 47.97 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were 1.60 cents to 2 cents lower with May at 33.75 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
