<DOCNO> AP890516-0272 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-89 1826EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-ComedyChannel     05-16 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Comedy Channel,0401</SECOND>
<HEAD>Time Inc.'s HBO Unit to Launch Comedy Channel on Basic Cable</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Home Box Office Inc., which provides the
pay-television services HBO and Cinemax, said Tuesday it plans to
launch the first advertiser-supported channel devoted entirely to
comedy starting this fall.
   The new service, which would be offered to cable operators for
inclusion at no extra charge to subscribers to their basic service,
would represent the Time Inc. unit's first venture into basic cable
programming.
   Backers of the project say comedy offers a distinctive new
programming vehicle that could help cable operators draw new
subscribers.
   But the new service will have to fight for channel space with
several other recently launched cable networks such as Turner
Broadcasting System Inc.'s Turner Network Television, the National
Broadcasting Co.'s Consumer News and Business Channel and an array
of regional sports networks.
   Michael Fuchs, Home Box Office chairman and chief executive,
said in a news release cable opertors told of the plans for the
comedy service over the past several months have expressed ``strong
support.''
   Richard Beahrs, president of the HBO comedy channel, said he has
only just begun asking cable operators for commitments to carry the
service and declined to say how many he has received.
   Time also owns a cable operation, American Television and
Communications Corp., that could provide several million
subscribers to get the comedy channel started, however.
   Beahrs declined to say how much Home Box Office was prepared to
spend to launch the service but said the company realized it may
take a number of years to be profitable.
   Home Box Office may also face competition from a rival comedy
channel from the MTV Networks division of Viacom Inc.
   Barry Kluger, a spokesman for MTV Networks, said MTV has been
examining for five years the possibility of launching a comedy
channel and may make a decision soon on whether to launch an
all-comedy service.
   Home Box Office currently includes comedy shows in its HBO and
Cinemax lineups of movies, sports, music, drama, documentaries and
special programs.
   Its comedy channel will feature hosts who will have their own
shows usually running two hours and incorporating live performances
with clips from stand-up performances, current comedy films,
classic TV shows and theater. It will also carry an occasional
full-length motion picture or situation comedy.
</TEXT>
