<FIRST>r f AM-Avon-Amway     05-16 0221</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Avon-Amway,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>Amway: Would Keep Avon's Direct Sales Network Separate From Its Own</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amway Corp. said Tuesday it would operate Avon
Products Inc.'s direct-selling business separately from its own
distributor organization if Amways's $2.1 billion bid for Avon is
successful.
   Amway Chairman Jay Van Andel and President Richard M. DeVos also
stated in a letter to Avon's board of directors that they don't
contemplate making any radical changes in the Avon direct-sales
organization.
   They said, however, that they would attempt to increase the
quantity and type of products available from Avon sales
representatives.
   Instead of selling primarily cosmetics and beauty aids, ``we see
a substantial opportunity to expand the Avon product line to
include a full range of health aids under the Avon name.''
   Avon says it has about 1.5 million sales representatives
marketing Avon products in 85 countries. Amway has about 1 million
distributors who handle Amway's own products and some products and
services of other companies.
   The Amway executives, co-founders of the privately held company
based in Ada, Mich., said they intend to ``explore enhancements in
the compensation structure and benefits'' for the Avon
representatives.
   They repeated their offer to discuss all aspects of their
$39-a-share takeover offer.
   Avon executives didn't return telephone calls for comment at the
company's New York headquarters late Tuesday.
</TEXT>
