<FIRST>u f AM-HancockAwards     05-16 0653</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hancock Awards,0669</SECOND>
<HEAD>Associated Press, Los Angeles Times Among Hancock Winners</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Financial writers from The Associated Press, The
Wall Street Journal and the Los Angeles Times were among the
winners of the 22nd annual Awards for Excellence in Business and
Financial Journalism announced Tuesday by John Hancock Financial
Services.
   Awards also went to writers from The Kansas City Times, The
Daily Sentinel of Grand Junction, Colo., the Washington Post
Writers Group and the National Journal magazine.
   The Hancock awards annually recognize ``lucid reporting,
interpretation and writing of business and financial news,'' the
Boston-based financial services company said in a statement from
Chairman E. James Morton.
   The winners, whose work was judged to have improved the public's
understanding of business issues during 1988, will be honored at a
dinner in New York in November at a program co-sponsored by John
Hancock and Fordham University's Graduate School of Business.
   The honors carry a cash award of $5,000 in each of the seven
categories.
   The winners are:
   _The Associated Press in the syndicated and news service writers
category for eight articles on the rush of corporate mergers and
restructurings that followed the October 1987 stock market crash.
The seven writers contributing to the project were Rick Gladstone,
Peter Coy, John Cunniff, Chet Currier, Marcy Gordon, Vivian Marino
and Skip Wollenberg. The Hancock award was the second in a row and
the ninth overall for the AP. In 1987, the AP won for its coverage
of the stock market crash.
   _Bruce Stokes of The National Journal in the category for
writers of national magazines of general interest for his
three-part series, ``Land of the Rising Yen.'' The series previewed
the next round of Japanese challenges to America's economic
strength, including the banking industry.
   _Bernard Wysocki Jr. of The Wall Street Journal among writers
for financial and business newspapers and magazines for his report,
``The Final Frontier.'' The project examined how the U.S. lead in
technology is imperiled by ever-stronger competition, particularly
from the Japanese. It is the fifth time the Journal has been a
Hancock recipient.
   _A team of nine writers from the Los Angeles Times in the
category of newspapers with circulation above 300,000 for a
four-part series on the struggles Americans encounter working for
Japanese companies. Contributing to the project were James
Flanigan, Nancy Yoshihara, Jonathan Peterson, Jim Schachter,
Douglas Frantz, Sam Jameson, Michael A. Hiltzik, James Risen and
Karl Schoenberger. It is the sixth time the Times has won a Hancock.
   _Charlie Crumpley of The Kansas City Times in the category of
newspapers with circulations between 100,000 and 300,000 for a
five-part series analyzing the transformation of the Kansas
City-area economy from manufacturing to service industries. The
series also pointed out roadblocks to the area's future growth.
   _Gary Harmon of The Daily Sentinel among newspapers with
circulations under 100,000 for an eight-part series on workers'
compensation. The project examined how the cost of workers'
compensation insurance has severely hampered the competitiveness of
Colorado business.
   _Robert Kuttner of the Washington Post Writers Group among
financial and business columnists for his analyses of topics such
as America's changing role in world politics, the surging economy,
the wealth of the Japanese, the U.S. government's role in
developing industrial technology and the health of the Social
Security system. It is the second time the Washington Post Writers
Group has won the award.
   Winners were selected by a panel of judges consisting of Richard
Des Ruisseaux, of The Louisville (Ky.) Courier-Journal and
president of the National Society of Newspaper Columnists; Peter
Holmes, assistant managing editor of The Washington Times and
president of the National Press Club; Philip Moeller, business
editor of The Baltimore Sun and president of the Society of
American Business Editors & Writers; William Small, director of the
Center for Communication at Fordham University; and Roberta Yafie,
financial reporter for Knight-Ridder Financial News and president
of the New York Financial Writers' Association.
</TEXT>
