<FIRST>r f AM-SouthAfrica-Mobil     05-16 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa-Mobil,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Black Workers Expand Strike Protesting Divestment</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: also on general news wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Black workers on Tuesday
expanded a strike protesting Mobil Corp.'s failure to negotiate
with their union prior to announcing the sale of its South African
holdings.
   The Chemical Workers Industrial Union, which represents about 80
percent of Mobil's 1,500 black employees in South Africa, said 350
workers were on strike at depots throughout the Johannesburg region
and at the ports of East London and Port Elizabeth.
   The union had said 240 workers were involved when work stoppages
began Monday around Johannesburg. Mobil officials confirmed the
strike but released no details about the impact on operations.
   The union plans to poll its members this week to determine if
they support a nationwide strike against Mobil because of its
refusal to negotiate the terms of its disinvestment.
   The U.S. company announced on April 28 that it was selling its
holdings in South Africa to the General Union Mining Corp., a
conglomerate known as Gencor that owns a petroleum subsidiary.
   Mobil said Gencor would honor all existing arrangements with the
union. But union officials said Mobil had lied when it rebuffed
previous attempts to open negotiations by insisting there were no
plans for divestment.
   Jacques Franken, industrial relations manager for Mobil's South
African operation, said Tuesday that the South African management
had informed the union about the disinvestment as soon as the news
was received from U.S. headquarters.
   ``The disinvestment has nothing to do with Mobil South Africa,
as it is the U.S. corporation that is disinvesting,'' he said.
   The union had approached Mobil and several other foreign
companies in South Africa, asking for one-year advance notice of
any pullout, guarantees of job security and disclosure of the terms
of sale.
   Scores of U.S. companies have withdrawn from South Africa in the
past five years, citing economic considerations and pressure from
the anti-apartheid movement.
</TEXT>
