<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-Markets 1stLd-Writethru   05-16 0182</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru,0188</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates throughout with morning Nikkei, comments; no pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar was slightly higher against the
Japanese yen Wednesday morning, while prices on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange ended trading with a moderate gain.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which gained
210.16 points the previous day, added another 52.27 points, or 0.15
percent, to finish the morning session at 33,978.72.
   The dollar, which opened at 137.12 yen, up 0.12 yen from
Tuesday's 137.00-yen close, was changing hands at 137.13 yen at
late morning.
   Although the dollar slightly weakened after central bank
interventions in Tokyo and in New York overnight, investors began
buying again Wednesday morning following an uptrend in the Sydney
market, which opened earlier, traders said.
   Most market players, however waited on the sidelines ahead of
the release of fresh U.S. economic data. The United States is to
announce the nation's trade figures for March later Wednesday.
   On the stock exchange, share prices rose because market players
were reassured as the yen's fall slowed down at around 137-yen,
dealers said.
</TEXT>
